{"title_page": "Philadelphia Naval Asylum", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =U.S. Naval Home\n  | nrhp_type = nhl\n  | image = Naval Asylum.jpg\n  | caption =\n  | location= Gray's Ferry Ave. at 24th St.<br />[[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|56|38|N|75|11|2|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Philadelphia#Pennsylvania#USA\n| area =\n| built =1827\n| architect= [[William Strickland (architect)|William Strickland]]\n| architecture= Greek Revival\n| added = August 21, 1972\n| governing_body = Department of the Navy\n| refnum=72001173<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Philadelphia Naval Asylum''' is a complex of buildings at Gray's Ferry Avenue in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Built in 1827 as a hospital, it later housed the '''Philadelphia Naval School''', served as a [[Old soldiers home|home for retired sailors]] for the [[United States Navy]] from 1834 to 1976, and was ultimately redeveloped as luxury condominiums. The site was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] and designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1971, primarily for its architecture.<ref name=\"nrhp nom\">{{cite web|last=Pitts|first=Carolyn|title=Philadelphia Naval Asylum|url={{NRHP-PA|H001489_01H.pdf}}|work=National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form|publisher=Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission|accessdate=December 21, 2013|year=1975}}</ref>\n\nSet on more than {{convert|20|acre|ha}}, the campus includes three buildings designed by architect [[William Strickland (architect)|William Strickland]] that are considered some of the best examples of [[Greek Revival]] architecture in the [[United States]]: Biddle Hall (the 1833 main building), the surgeon's residence and the governor's residence.<ref name=\"nrhp nom\"/>\n\nFor seven years, the campus housed the Philadelphia Naval School, a precursor to the [[United States Naval Academy]]. Beginning in 1838, [[midshipmen]] approaching examinations for promotion were assigned to the school for eight months of study. In 1842, [[William Chauvenet]] was placed in charge of the school and formalized much of the study. When the Naval Academy was formed in 1845, four of the seven faculty members came from the Philadelphia school.\n\nIn 1889, its name was changed to '''Naval Home'''. In 1976, the Naval Home was moved to [[Gulfport, Mississippi]], after it was determined that the Philadelphia facility could not be economically expanded and modernized.\n\nIn 1988, the property was sold to residential developer [[Toll Brothers]]. The main building was damaged by [[arson]]ists in 2003. It has since been restored as [[Naval Square, Philadelphia|luxury condominiums]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia}}\n*[[Schuylkill Arsenal]]\n*[[Naval Square, Philadelphia]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Philadelphia]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in South Philadelphia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://archives.pacscl.org/shows/navalhome/index.html Philadelphia Area Consortium of Special Collections Libraries]\n*[http://www.navalsquare.com/ Naval Square]\n*[https://www.usna.edu/Library/sca/man-findingaids/MS_247.EAD.xml Records of the U.S. Naval Home, Philadelphia, 1831-1936, MS 247] held by Special Collections & Archives, Nimitz Library at the United States Naval Academy\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1827]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1833]]\n[[Category:Military academies of the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Closed installations of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Old soldiers' homes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Southwest Center City, Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1827 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =U.S. Naval Home\n  | nrhp_type = nhl\n  | image = Naval Asylum.jpg\n  | caption =\n  | location= Gray's Ferry Ave. at 24th St.<br />[[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|56|38|N|75|11|2|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Philadelphia#Pennsylvania#USA\n| area =\n| built =1827\n| architect= [[William Strickland (architect)|William Strickland]]\n| architecture= Greek Revival\n| added = August 21, 1972\n| governing_body = Department of the Navy\n| refnum=72001173<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Philadelphia Naval Asylum''' is a complex of buildings at Gray's Ferry Avenue in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Built in 1827 as a hospital, it later housed the '''Philadelphia Naval School''', served as a [[Old soldiers home|home for retired sailors]] for the [[United States Navy]] from 1834 to 1976, and was ultimately redeveloped as luxury condominiums. The site was placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] and designated a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1971, primarily for its architecture.<ref name=\"nrhp nom\">{{cite web|last=Pitts|first=Carolyn|title=Philadelphia Naval Asylum|url={{NRHP-PA|H001489_01H.pdf}}|work=National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form|publisher=Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission|accessdate=December 21, 2013|year=1975}}</ref>\n\nSet on more than {{convert|20|acre|ha}}, the campus includes three buildings designed by architect [[William Strickland (architect)|William Strickland]] that are considered some of the best examples of [[Greek Revival]] architecture in the [[United States]]: Biddle Hall (the 1833 main building), the surgeon's residence and the governor's residence.<ref name=\"nrhp nom\"/>\n\nFor seven years, the campus housed the Philadelphia Naval School, a precursor to the [[United States Naval Academy]]. Beginning in 1838, [[midshipmen]] approaching examinations for promotion were assigned to the school for eight months of study. In 1842, [[William Chauvenet]] was placed in charge of the school and formalized much of the study. When the Naval Academy was formed in 1845, four of the seven faculty members came from the Philadelphia school.\n\nIn 1889, its name was changed to '''Naval Home'''. In 1976, the Naval Home was moved to [[Gulfport, Mississippi]], after it was determined that the Philadelphia facility could not be economically expanded and modernized.\n\nIn 1988, the property was sold to residential developer [[Toll Brothers]]. The main building was damaged by [[arson]]ists in 2003. It has since been restored as [[Naval Square, Philadelphia|luxury condominiums]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philadelphia}}\n*[[Schuylkill Arsenal]]\n*[[Naval Square, Philadelphia]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Philadelphia]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in South Philadelphia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[http://archives.pacscl.org/shows/navalhome/index.html Philadelphia Area Consortium of Special Collections Libraries]\n*[http://www.navalsquare.com/ Naval Square]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1827]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1833]]\n[[Category:Military academies of the United States]]\n[[Category:History of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Closed installations of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Old soldiers' homes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Southwest Center City, Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:1827 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "Stonewall61", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Naval_Asylum"}
{"title_page": "I Stay in Love", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Stay in Love\n| cover      = I Stay in Love Mariah Carey.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mariah Carey]]\n| album      = [[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]\n| released   = {{start date|2008|10|28}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Airplay|radio airplay]]}}\n| recorded   = 2007\n| studio     =Stone Groove Studios ([[Lake County, Illinois]])\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=31}}\n| label      = [[The Island Def Jam Music Group|Island Def Jam]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Mariah Carey]]|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]|[[Adonis Shropshire]]|[[Kendrick Dean]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Carey|Cox}}\n| prev_title = [[I'll Be Lovin' U Long Time]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n| next_title = [[My Love (The-Dream song)|My Love]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n}}\n\n\"'''I Stay in Love'''\" is a song by American [[singer-songwriter]] [[Mariah Carey]], taken from her eleventh studio album, ''[[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]'' (2008). It was written by Carey, [[Bryan-Michael Cox]], [[Adonis Shropshire]] and [[Kendrick Dean]], and produced by the former two. \"I Stay in Love\" was released through [[Island Records]] on October 28, 2008, as the fourth and final single from the album.  Drawing influence from the  [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music genre, the song features a piano and keyboard-driven melody, and a strong accompanying drum-beat. Lyrically, the song finds Carey getting \"her cry on with the connect-the-dots break-up track.\" She describes the old time she shared with her [[Romantic interest|love interest]]. She narrates that even though they said let go, and that she is aware that there is nothing left in their relationship, she still \"stays in love with him\".\n\n\"I Stay in Love\" received generally positive reviews from music critics, with many considering the song a strong ballad and a highlight from the album, while complimenting its production and piano-driven melody, despite criticizing the similarities to Carey's previous single, \"[[We Belong Together (Mariah Carey song)|We Belong Together]]\" (2005). The song performed weak commercially, becoming Carey's first single from the album to not chart on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], although peaking at number eighty-one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart, and becoming Carey's fourteenth number one on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart. In the United Kingdom, the song debuted and peaked at number ninety-five, and spent only one week on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nCarey performed \"I Stay in Love\" live on two high-profile televised events. First, on November 8, 2008, she was featured as a guest judge and musical performer of the [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth season]] of the popular British talent competition, ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''. Additionally, Carey performed it live at the [[American Music Award]]s, held on November 23, 2008. The song's accompanying music video was filmed by Carey's husband, [[Nick Cannon]], and features Carey as a dancer in a Las Vegas show at the [[Bellagio (hotel and casino)|Bellagio Hotel and Casino Resort]]. Additionally, during the show and its preparations, Carey realizes that her ex-lover has found love with one of her fellow dancers, leading her to blow up the car he gave her, as well as its accompaniments in the [[Mojave Desert]].\n\n==Background and composition==\n\"I Stay in Love\" was written and produced by [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Bryan-Michael Cox]], with additional songwriting from [[Adonis Shropshire]] and [[Kendrick Dean]], for Carey's eleventh studio album, ''[[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]'' (2008). Carey produced the track for Maroon Entertainment and by Cox for Blabby Inc. Copyright is held by Rye Songs which is administered by Songs of Universal ([[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]])/W.B.M. Music Corp. O/D/O itself and Songs in the key of B Flat/Noontime South/EMI Foray Music O/B/O itself and Phoenix Ave. Publishing/Christian Combs Publishing (SESAC). The song was recorded  by Brian Garten at Stone Groove Studios in New York, and [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] by [[Phil Tan]] for Riotproof Productions, Inc. All instrumentation was performed by Cox, while Carey sung all the lead and background vocals.<ref name=\"E=MC Booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=E=MC\u00b2 (Liner Notes) |others=Mariah Carey |year=2008|chapter= |first=Mariah |last=Carey |authorlink=Mariah Carey |coauthors= |type=Compact Disc |work=Island Records |location=New York City, New York |ref= }}</ref> In an interview with [[Ed Lover]] for the radio station [[Power 105]] in [[New York City]], Carey revealed that the song was one of her favorites from the album and that she recorded her vocals within a day.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Carey |first=Mariah |subjectlink=Mariah Carey |interviewer=[[Ed Lover]] |title=Interview: Mariah Carey |location=New York City |date=April 21, 2008 |work=The Ed Lover Show }}</ref> Following the commercial underperformance of the album's third single, \"[[I'll Be Lovin' U Long Time]]\", \"I Stay in Love\" was released as the fourth single from E=MC\u00b2.<ref name=\"Flop\">{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/thesound/a135100/that-new-mariah-carey-single.html|title=That New Mariah Carey Single|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=November 9, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> In the United States, it was serviced to [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream]], [[Rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic]] and [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio stations on October 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=1|title=Going for Adds :: CHR/Top 40|work=[[Radio & Records]]|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218184748/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=1|archive-date=February 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=9|title=Going for Adds :: Rhythmic|work=Radio & Records|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530004048/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=9|archive-date=May 30, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=5|title=Going for Adds :: Urban|work=Radio & Records|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512233109/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=5|archive-date=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> A four-track [[Extended play|EP]] consisting of remixes by Jody den Broeder and [[Ralphi Rosario]] was released in the United States on December 16, 2008.<ref name=\"4 track EP\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/i-stay-in-love-remixes-ep/id299356879|title=I Stay in Love - Remixes EP|work=[[iTunes Store]]|date=December 16, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"I Stay in Love\" is a \"beat-driven\" and \"piano-laced\" ballad, that is influenced by [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music genres.<ref name=picks>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20196231,00.html|title=Picks And Pans: Music|first=Chuck|last=Arnold|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=June 10, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The song's instrumentation is derived from a piano melody, and is backed by a strong computerized drum-beat.<ref name=advance>{{cite news|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/entertainment/2008/apr/21/mariah_carey_rides_a_wave-ar-225227/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714175015/http://www2.newsadvance.com/entertainment/2008/apr/21/mariah_carey_rides_a_wave-ar-225227/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |title=Mariah Carey Rides a Wave |last=Ruggieri |first=Melissa |work=[[The News & Advance]] |publisher=[[Media General]] |date=April 21, 2008 |access-date=August 9, 2011 }}</ref> It is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[D-flat major|D{{flat}} major]], with Carey's vocals spanning from the low note of D{{flat}}<sub>3</sub> to the high note of G{{flat}}<sub>5</sub>.<ref name=music>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdVPE.asp?ppn=MN0075069|author=Mariah Carey (Composers and Lyricists)|title=I Stay in Love: Mariah Carey Digital Sheet Music|year=2008|accessdate=April 9, 2011|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Music Publishing]]|format=Musicnotes|at=MN0068511 (Product Number)}}</ref> The song moves at a slow tempo of 65 beats per minute in [[Alla breve|cut time]], and it follows a chord progression of D{{flat}}\u2013B{{flat}}m<small>7</small>\u2013G{{flat}}\u2013A{{flat}}.  The song features a \"double voice\" effect during its final chorus, where Carey's normal singing tone throughout the rest of the song is combined with her raised pitch.<ref name=buff/> She raises the pitch one octave, and layers it over her normal tone.<ref name=buff>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12024F33079B3078&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Discs|last=Demone|first=Larry|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=March 4, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> Lyrically, the song finds Carey getting \"her cry on with the connect-the-dots break-up track.\"<ref name=globe>{{cite news|url=http://articles.boston.com/2008-02-26/ae/29275680_1_paul-mccartney-feeling-album|title=An Early Listen to Possible Hits|last=Rodman|first=Sarah|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=April 12, 2008|accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref> She describes the old time she shared with her lover. She also admits that even though they did attempt to save their relationship, and that she knows that it is definitely over, she still \"stays in love with him\".<ref name=globe/>\n\nOn the United States' ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart, \"I Stay in Love\" became Carey's fourteenth number-one song on February 14, 2009.<ref name=\"MC Exact Dates of Number Ones\">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/474680/mariah-carey-scores-sweet-16th-no-1-on-danceclub-play-songs|title=Mariah Carey Scores Sweet 16th No. 1 On Dance/Club Play Songs|work=Billboard|date=October 12, 2012|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> The track peaked at thirty-seven on the [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] chart,<ref name=\"Rhythmic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/309388/Mariah+Carey/chart?f=378|title=Mariah Carey Rhythmic Chart History|work=Billboard|date=December 27, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> number eighty-one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart,<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mariah-carey-mn0000262255/awards|title=Mariah Carey Awards|work=[[AllMusic]]|year=2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> and number ninety-five on the [[Pop 100]] chart.<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\"/> The track reached number ninety-five on the UK [[UK Singles Chart|Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25943/mariah-carey/|title=Mariah Carey full official chart history|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical reception ===\n\"I Stay in Love\" garnered generally positive reviews from music critics. Many complimented the song's piano-driven melody, as well as Carey's vocals, while some felt it was too similar to her previous single, \"[[We Belong Together (Mariah Carey song)|We Belong Together]]\" (2005). In his review of ''E=MC\u00b2'', Kevin O'Hare of ''[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]'' wrote that Carey \"shines\" on the song,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.masslive.com/playback/2008/04/carey_gets_the_formula_right_o.html|title=Carey Gets Formula Right With 'E=MC2'|last=O'Hare|first=Kevin|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=May 12, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> while [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]' Roger Friedman described it as \"a killer ballad.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,348468,00.html#3|title=Mariah Carey's New Album: First Review|last=Friedman|first=Roger|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=April 3, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''{{'}}s Chuck Arnold named it the best ballad on the album, calling it \"pretty\".<ref name=picks/> The ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''{{'}}s writer Joey Guerra described the single as a \"gently grooving ballad that Janet Jackson should be recording instead of wasting her time on tired sex clich\u00e9s\", while commenting, \"It's doubtful, however, that Jackson could reach the notes Carey effortlessly hits at the end of the song\".<ref name=chron>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ent/music/cdreviews/5700230.html|title=Mariah Gets Equation Right With 'E=MC\u00b2'|last=Guerra|first=Joey|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=April 15, 2008|accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> Richard Cromelin from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' highlighted Carey's raw form of singing on the track, writing, \"its unadorned, and her voice is almost leathery in the lower notes. It's not flattering, but it rings true emotionally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-mariah12apr12,1,6445816.story|title=CD: Mariah Carey's 'E=MC2'|last=Richard|first=David|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=April 8, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref>  Nick Levine of [[Digital Spy]] called \"I Stay in Love\" a \"fairly modern Mariah track\" and that although he believed it was a \"retread\" of one of Carey's previous singles \"[[We Belong Together]]\" (2005), it is not an \"unpleasant retread\".<ref name=\"Flop\"/>\n\nMichael Slezak from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that the song is \"a slower, less addictive variation\" of \"We Belong Together\".<ref name=entrainment>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2008/10/29/mariah-christin/|title=Who Has the New Best Video: Mariah, Xtina or Hilary?|last=Slezak|first=Michael|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=April 18, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Newsday]]'' critic, Glenn Gamboa, also called it a \"We Belong Together-sh ballad\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/1461986051.html?dids=1461986051:1461986051&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+15%2C+2008&author=GLENN+GAMBOA&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=DROPS%3A+On+'E%2C'+confident+Mariah+has+no+%3D&pqatl=google|title=Mariah's New Album|last=Gamboa|first=Glenn|work=[[Newsday]]|publisher=[[Cablevision]]|date=March 1, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> In separate reviews of the song, both David Balls and Nick Levine of [[Digital Spy]] also compared the song to Carey's \"We Belong Together\"; the former rated \"I Stay in Love\" three out of five stars, and wrote, \"It may not be the most original of songs, but Carey's emotion-packed vocals make this a pleasant treat after some vacuous recent offerings.\"<ref name=digitally>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/thesound/a135100/that-new-mariah-carey-single.html|title=That New Mariah Carey Single|last=Levine|first=Nick|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=March 31, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=digitalspy9>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/singlesreviews/a137373/mariah-carey-i-stay-in-love.html|title=Mariah: 'I Stay in Love'|last=Balls|first=David|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=March 31, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> Freedom De Luc from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described the song as an \"emotive ballad\",<ref name=post>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/14/AR2008041403143.html|title=Mariah Sticks to Known Equation|last=De Luc|first=Freedom|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=April 15, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> while Nekesa Mumbi Moody from ''[[Foster's Daily Democrat]]'' noted \"it could have been recorded in her early '90s heyday \u2014 except it's not as saccharine as some of her early work\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080421/GJLIFESTYLES/173868905/-1/FOSLIFESTYLES|title=Music Review: Mariah Carey's 'E=MC2' Recaptures the Magic of Her Best-selling 'Emancipation'|last=Moody|first=Nekesa Mumbi|work=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]]|publisher=[[Geo. J. Foster Company]]|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> However, Evan Sawdey of [[PopMatters]] described it as one of the album's \"worst songs\".<ref name=pop>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/mariah-carey-emc2|title=Mariah Carey: E=MC\u00b2 < Reviews |last=Sawey|first=Evan|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|date=March 1, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n=== Background ===\n{{Citations broken|section|date=January 2019}}\nDirected by Carey's then-husband [[Nick Cannon]], the music video for \"I Stay in Love\" was filmed in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], using a story line that Cannon and Carey co-wrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/news/10731|title=Mariah Set to Shoot Video for New Single I Stay In Love|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> Carey filmed the video on October 5, at The Bank Nightclub of [[Bellagio (hotel and casino)|The Bellagio Hotel and Casino Resort]], and in the [[Mojave Desert]] on October 6, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/30506429.html|title=Bobbitt Trains for Boxing Bout in LV|last=Clarke|first=Norm|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|publisher=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]]|date=October 6, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> In an interview with [[Ryan Seacrest]], Cannon spoke about the video and said that there is a scene where Carey is in bed with a man (played by Andrew Karelis), and that \"Mariah plays the showgirl and there's a guy who cheated and there's flashbacks......\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,446144,00.html|title=Mariah Carey Spied Kissing New Man, And It's Not Her Husband|last=Friedman|first=Roger|work=Fox News|publisher=News Corporation|date=April 3, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> The music video for \"I Stay In Love\" was featured on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[Access Granted]]'' for a behind-the-scenes look and a world premiere on October 27, 2008.<ref name=vidd>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/news/10711|title=Mariah Shoots New Video in Las Vegas|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The entire video was shown every hour on BET until October 28, 2008.<ref name=vidd/> \"I Stay in Love\" music video peaked at #16 on [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'s Hot Videoclip Tracks chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/3103111|title=Hot Videoclip Tracks|magazine=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|date=December 6, 2008|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Synopsis ===\n[[Image:Mimistaywith.jpg|thumb|right|250px|In the image, Carey is seen dressed in white garments and large feathers. She is featured as a dancer in Las Vegas, and is where she discovers her ex-lover has moved on.]]\nThe video, black-and-white, begins with Carey parking her antique automobile in desert. She gets out, with customized black boots with an 'M' on them, and as, she walks towards the camera, the vehicle explodes. As the music begins and the scene shifts to another where Carey applying her eye make-up and earrings. As a form of product placement, her fragrance is shown on a dresser in her [[Boudoir]]. As Carey finishes getting ready, scenery of Las Vegas is shown, before shifting to Carey, now dressed as a Vegas performer. As she walks down a runway dressed in white garments ad feathers, she catches the attention of a man. He turns out to be Carey's ex-lover, who in turn came to the show to meet with one of Carey's fellow dancers. As he caresses the female in the dressing room, Carey sees them, and walks by them, bumping into him purposely. Additional scenes are shown of Carey laying alone on the dark runway, apparently after the show has finished, as well as preparing herself for the show. During the second verse, the video then shows Carey driving down a highway in the desert, and as she drives, past memories of the pair are shown, holding each other intimately in a bed. She then pushes old gifts he had given her into the passengers seat, and pulls over the car, continuing the scene from the beginning of the video. After the car explodes, Carey tears off her necklace in despair, and begins to flail her arms in desperation. The video ends with Carey back at the show in Vegas during the finale, as glitter drops from the top of the stage. Carey, now back in the desert, looks for another ride, and gets into a black [[Cadillac]] [[Escalade]] driven by Nick Cannon.\n\n=== Reception and ''Luscious Pink'' commercial ===\nNick Levine from Digital Spy complimented the video, commenting that it managed \"to be both ridiculous and a little bit moving - quite an achievement.\"<ref name=\"digitally\"/> ''Entertainment Weekly'' writer Michael Slezak described Carey's boots as \"hot\", and considered the cinematography of the music video \"gorgeous\". He also complimented several aspects of the video, saying, \"Mariah\u2019s bod looks totally smokin\u2019, even if her entire wardrobe should be donated to a charity benefiting teenage strumpets and/or truck-stop hookers. Also: That [[Wentworth Miller]] 2.0 ain\u2019t hard on the eyes, either (in reference to the man who played her love interest in \"We Belong Together\").<ref name=entrainment/>\n\nThe commercial for Carey's ''[[Luscious Pink]]'' fragrance uses part of the \"I Stay in Love\" music video, with a clip of the song used as audio.<ref name=frag>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/node/711|title=Watch Mariah's New Luscious Pink Commercial|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The short clip shows Carey getting ready for the Vegas show, by applying her make-up and lipstick, and also applying the fragrance on her neck and cleavage.<ref name=frag/> The release published on Carey's official website described the concept of the commercial as \"a combination of Mariah's two passions - music and fragrance.\"<ref name=frag/>\n\n== Live performances ==\nDue to promotion for ''E=MC\u00b2'' and the single, Carey was featured as a guest judge and musical act on the [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth series]] of the popular British talent competition, ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref name=dailyness>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/2008/11/07/what-a-carey-on-86908-20875348/|title=Mariah Carey Will Show The X Factor What a Diva is, Says Dannii Minogue|last=Dingwall|first=John|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=November 7, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> During that week, all the contestants would have to sing songs from Carey's catalog.<ref name=dailyness/> Prior to her arrival, one of the show's judges [[Dannii Minogue]] said \"Could it get any more nerve-wracking for the contestants?\", due to the general strenuous nature of Carey's songs.<ref name=dailyness/> Before any of the performances by the finalists, Carey performed \"I Stay in Love\", accompanied by three background vocalists. She received a standing ovation from the audience and judges, and continued backstage for a taped session with the contestants. At the end of the program, she performed her classic \"[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]\" (1993), and was eventually joined by the finalists for the finale of the song.<ref name=bbc2>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7718192.stm|title=Laura White is voted off X Factor|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=November 8, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> \"Hero\" was re-recorded by the [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 5)|2008 UK X Factor finalists]] and released as a single, becoming the second best-selling single of 2008 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7802941.stm|title=Duffy and Burke top 2008 charts|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=December 29, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> According to reports, the episode gained a large increase in viewers due to Carey's presence, and was able to surpass its long-time rival program, ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', in the ratings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_mariah-carey-to-appear-on-the-x-factor_1201735|title=Mariah Appears on the X Factor|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|publisher=Diligent Media Corporation|date=November 8, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Carey also made an appearance at the [[American Music Awards]] of 2008 on November 23, at the [[L.A. Live#Nokia Theatre|Nokia Theatre]].<ref name=mtv6/> Wearing a long black gown, she performed the song after receiving an honorary award for her achievements in music.<ref name=mtv6/> Chris Harris from MTV News described it as a \"riveting performance\".<ref name=mtv6>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1599998/kanye-west-offers-his-award-lil-wayne-at-american-music-awards.jhtml|title=Kanye West Offers His Award To Lil Wayne, Chris Brown Named Artist Of The Year At American Music Awards|last=Harris|first=Chris|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Formats==\n'''Remix EP'''<ref name=\"4 track EP\"/>\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Jody den Broeger Radio Edit) \u2013 4:08\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Ralph Rosario Melodic Radio Edit) \u2013 3:50\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Jody Den Broeder House Mix) \u2013 8:29\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Ralph Rosario Big Vocal) \u2013 8:12\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Chart (2008)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Bulgaria Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://acharts.co/song/42577|title=I Stay In Love by Mariah Carey - Music Charts}}</ref>\n| 24\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|95|artist=Mariah Carey|song=I Stay In Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[UK R&B]] (Official Charts Company)<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Pop 100]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\"/>\n| 95\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|81|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|37|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Chart (2009)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|1|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Year-end charts ===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2009)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Dance Club Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2009/hot-dance-club-play-songs|title=Best of 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Dance/Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|48\n|}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|1=E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)}}\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2009 (U.S.)]]\n* [[Artists with the most number-ones on the U.S. dance chart]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|mariah-carey|i-stay-in-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Mariah Carey singles}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:2008 singles]]\n[[Category:Mariah Carey songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mariah Carey]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bryan-Michael Cox]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Nick Cannon]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kendrick Dean]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Adonis Shropshire]]\n[[Category:2008 songs]]\n[[Category:Island Records singles]]\n[[Category:Torch songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Stay in Love\n| cover      = I Stay in Love Mariah Carey.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mariah Carey]]\n| album      = [[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]\n| released   = {{start date|2008|10|28}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Airplay|radio airplay]]}}\n| recorded   = 2007\n| studio     =Stone Groove Studios ([[Lake County, Illinois]])\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=31}}\n| label      = [[The Island Def Jam Music Group|Island Def Jam]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Mariah Carey]]|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]|[[Adonis Shropshire]]|[[Kendrick Dean]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Carey|Cox}}\n| prev_title = [[I'll Be Lovin' U Long Time]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n| next_title = [[My Love (The-Dream song)|My Love]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n}}\n\n\"'''I Stay in Love'''\" is a song by American [[singer-songwriter]] [[Mariah Carey]], taken from her eleventh studio album, ''[[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]'' (2008). It was written by Carey, [[Bryan-Michael Cox]], [[Adonis Shropshire]] and [[Kendrick Dean]], and produced by the former two. \"I Stay in Love\" was released through [[Island Records]] on October 28, 2008, as the fourth and final single from the album.  Drawing influence from the  [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music genre, the song features a piano and keyboard-driven melody, and a strong accompanying drum-beat. Lyrically, the song finds Carey getting \"her cry on with the connect-the-dots break-up track.\" She describes the old time she shared with her [[Romantic interest|love interest]]. She narrates that even though they said let go, and that she is aware that there is nothing left in their relationship, she still \"stays in love with him\".\n\n\"I Stay in Love\" received generally positive reviews from music critics, with many considering the song a strong ballad and a highlight from the album, while complimenting its production and piano-driven melody, despite criticizing the similarities to Carey's previous single, \"[[We Belong Together (Mariah Carey song)|We Belong Together]]\" (2005). The song performed weak commercially, becoming Carey's first single from the album to not chart on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], although peaking at number eighty-one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart, and becoming Carey's fourteenth number one on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart. In the United Kingdom, the song debuted and peaked at number ninety-five, and spent only one week on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nCarey performed \"I Stay in Love\" live on two high-profile televised events. First, on November 8, 2008, she was featured as a guest judge and musical performer of the [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth season]] of the popular British talent competition, ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''. Additionally, Carey performed it live at the [[American Music Award]]s, held on November 23, 2008. The song's accompanying music video was filmed by Carey's husband, [[Nick Cannon]], and features Carey as a dancer in a Las Vegas show at the [[Bellagio (hotel and casino)|Bellagio Hotel and Casino Resort]]. Additionally, during the show and its preparations, Carey realizes that her ex-lover has found love with one of her fellow dancers, leading her to blow up the car he gave her, as well as its accompaniments in the [[Mojave Desert]].\n\n==Background and composition==\n\"I Stay in Love\" was written and produced by [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Bryan-Michael Cox]], with additional songwriting from [[Adonis Shropshire]] and [[Kendrick Dean]], for Carey's eleventh studio album, ''[[E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)|E=MC\u00b2]]'' (2008). Carey produced the track for Maroon Entertainment and by Cox for Blabby Inc. Copyright is held by Rye Songs which is administered by Songs of Universal ([[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]])/W.B.M. Music Corp. O/D/O itself and Songs in the key of B Flat/Noontime South/EMI Foray Music O/B/O itself and Phoenix Ave. Publishing/Christian Combs Publishing (SESAC). The song was recorded  by Brian Garten at Stone Groove Studios in New York, and [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixed]] by [[Phil Tan]] for Riotproof Productions, Inc. All instrumentation was performed by Cox, while Carey sung all the lead and background vocals.<ref name=\"E=MC Booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=E=MC\u00b2 (Liner Notes) |others=Mariah Carey |year=2008|chapter= |first=Mariah |last=Carey |authorlink=Mariah Carey |coauthors= |type=Compact Disc |work=Island Records |location=New York City, New York |ref= }}</ref> In an interview with [[Ed Lover]] for the radio station [[Power 105]] in [[New York City]], Carey revealed that the song was one of her favorites from the album and that she recorded her vocals within a day.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Carey |first=Mariah |subjectlink=Mariah Carey |interviewer=[[Ed Lover]] |title=Interview: Mariah Carey |location=New York City |date=April 21, 2008 |work=The Ed Lover Show }}</ref> Following the commercial underperformance of the album's third single, \"[[I'll Be Lovin' U Long Time]]\", \"I Stay in Love\" was released as the fourth single from E=MC\u00b2.<ref name=\"Flop\">{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/thesound/a135100/that-new-mariah-carey-single.html|title=That New Mariah Carey Single|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=November 9, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> In the United States, it was serviced to [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream]], [[Rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic]] and [[Urban contemporary|urban]] radio stations on October 28, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=1|title=Going for Adds :: CHR/Top 40|work=[[Radio & Records]]|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218184748/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=1|archive-date=February 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=9|title=Going for Adds :: Rhythmic|work=Radio & Records|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530004048/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=9|archive-date=May 30, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10/28/2008&Format=5|title=Going for Adds :: Urban|work=Radio & Records|accessdate=September 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512233109/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=10%2F28%2F2008&Format=5|archive-date=May 12, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> A four-track [[Extended play|EP]] consisting of remixes by Jody den Broeder and [[Ralphi Rosario]] was released in the United States on December 16, 2008.<ref name=\"4 track EP\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/i-stay-in-love-remixes-ep/id299356879|title=I Stay in Love - Remixes EP|work=[[iTunes Store]]|date=December 16, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"I Stay in Love\" is a \"beat-driven\" and \"piano-laced\" ballad, that is influenced by [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music genres.<ref name=picks>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20196231,00.html|title=Picks And Pans: Music|first=Chuck|last=Arnold|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=June 10, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The song's instrumentation is derived from a piano melody, and is backed by a strong computerized drum-beat.<ref name=advance>{{cite news|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/entertainment/2008/apr/21/mariah_carey_rides_a_wave-ar-225227/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714175015/http://www2.newsadvance.com/entertainment/2008/apr/21/mariah_carey_rides_a_wave-ar-225227/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2011 |title=Mariah Carey Rides a Wave |last=Ruggieri |first=Melissa |work=[[The News & Advance]] |publisher=[[Media General]] |date=April 21, 2008 |access-date=August 9, 2011 }}</ref> It is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[D-flat major|D{{flat}} major]], with Carey's vocals spanning from the low note of D{{flat}}<sub>3</sub> to the high note of G{{flat}}<sub>5</sub>.<ref name=music>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdVPE.asp?ppn=MN0075069|author=Mariah Carey (Composers and Lyricists)|title=I Stay in Love: Mariah Carey Digital Sheet Music|year=2008|accessdate=April 9, 2011|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Music Publishing]]|format=Musicnotes|at=MN0068511 (Product Number)}}</ref> The song moves at a slow tempo of 65 beats per minute in [[Alla breve|cut time]], and it follows a chord progression of D{{flat}}\u2013B{{flat}}m<small>7</small>\u2013G{{flat}}\u2013A{{flat}}.  The song features a \"double voice\" effect during its final chorus, where Carey's normal singing tone throughout the rest of the song is combined with her raised pitch.<ref name=buff/> She raises the pitch one octave, and layers it over her normal tone.<ref name=buff>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12024F33079B3078&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Discs|last=Demone|first=Larry|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|publisher=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=March 4, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> Lyrically, the song finds Carey getting \"her cry on with the connect-the-dots break-up track.\"<ref name=globe>{{cite news|url=http://articles.boston.com/2008-02-26/ae/29275680_1_paul-mccartney-feeling-album|title=An Early Listen to Possible Hits|last=Rodman|first=Sarah|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=April 12, 2008|accessdate=August 4, 2011}}</ref> She describes the old time she shared with her lover. She also admits that even though they did attempt to save their relationship, and that she knows that it is definitely over, she still \"stays in love with him\".<ref name=globe/>\n\nOn the United States' ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs]] chart, \"I Stay in Love\" became Carey's fourteenth number-one song on February 14, 2009.<ref name=\"MC Exact Dates of Number Ones\">{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/474680/mariah-carey-scores-sweet-16th-no-1-on-danceclub-play-songs|title=Mariah Carey Scores Sweet 16th No. 1 On Dance/Club Play Songs|work=Billboard|date=October 12, 2012|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> The track peaked at thirty-seven on the [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] chart,<ref name=\"Rhythmic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/309388/Mariah+Carey/chart?f=378|title=Mariah Carey Rhythmic Chart History|work=Billboard|date=December 27, 2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> number eighty-one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart,<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mariah-carey-mn0000262255/awards|title=Mariah Carey Awards|work=[[AllMusic]]|year=2008|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> and number ninety-five on the [[Pop 100]] chart.<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\"/> The track reached number ninety-five on the UK [[UK Singles Chart|Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/25943/mariah-carey/|title=Mariah Carey full official chart history|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical reception ===\n\"I Stay in Love\" garnered generally positive reviews from music critics. Many complimented the song's piano-driven melody, as well as Carey's vocals, while some felt it was too similar to her previous single, \"[[We Belong Together (Mariah Carey song)|We Belong Together]]\" (2005). In his review of ''E=MC\u00b2'', Kevin O'Hare of ''[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]'' wrote that Carey \"shines\" on the song,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.masslive.com/playback/2008/04/carey_gets_the_formula_right_o.html|title=Carey Gets Formula Right With 'E=MC2'|last=O'Hare|first=Kevin|work=[[The Republican (Springfield)|The Republican]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=May 12, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> while [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]' Roger Friedman described it as \"a killer ballad.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,348468,00.html#3|title=Mariah Carey's New Album: First Review|last=Friedman|first=Roger|work=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=April 3, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''{{'}}s Chuck Arnold named it the best ballad on the album, calling it \"pretty\".<ref name=picks/> The ''[[Houston Chronicle]]''{{'}}s writer Joey Guerra described the single as a \"gently grooving ballad that Janet Jackson should be recording instead of wasting her time on tired sex clich\u00e9s\", while commenting, \"It's doubtful, however, that Jackson could reach the notes Carey effortlessly hits at the end of the song\".<ref name=chron>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ent/music/cdreviews/5700230.html|title=Mariah Gets Equation Right With 'E=MC\u00b2'|last=Guerra|first=Joey|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=April 15, 2008|accessdate=August 8, 2011}}</ref> Richard Cromelin from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' highlighted Carey's raw form of singing on the track, writing, \"its unadorned, and her voice is almost leathery in the lower notes. It's not flattering, but it rings true emotionally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-mariah12apr12,1,6445816.story|title=CD: Mariah Carey's 'E=MC2'|last=Richard|first=David|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=April 8, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref>  Nick Levine of [[Digital Spy]] called \"I Stay in Love\" a \"fairly modern Mariah track\" and that although he believed it was a \"retread\" of one of Carey's previous singles \"[[We Belong Together]]\" (2005), it is not an \"unpleasant retread\".<ref name=\"Flop\"/>\n\nMichael Slezak from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that the song is \"a slower, less addictive variation\" of \"We Belong Together\".<ref name=entrainment>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2008/10/29/mariah-christin/|title=Who Has the New Best Video: Mariah, Xtina or Hilary?|last=Slezak|first=Michael|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|date=April 18, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Newsday]]'' critic, Glenn Gamboa, also called it a \"We Belong Together-sh ballad\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/1461986051.html?dids=1461986051:1461986051&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+15%2C+2008&author=GLENN+GAMBOA&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=DROPS%3A+On+'E%2C'+confident+Mariah+has+no+%3D&pqatl=google|title=Mariah's New Album|last=Gamboa|first=Glenn|work=[[Newsday]]|publisher=[[Cablevision]]|date=March 1, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> In separate reviews of the song, both David Balls and Nick Levine of [[Digital Spy]] also compared the song to Carey's \"We Belong Together\"; the former rated \"I Stay in Love\" three out of five stars, and wrote, \"It may not be the most original of songs, but Carey's emotion-packed vocals make this a pleasant treat after some vacuous recent offerings.\"<ref name=digitally>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/thesound/a135100/that-new-mariah-carey-single.html|title=That New Mariah Carey Single|last=Levine|first=Nick|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=March 31, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=digitalspy9>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/singlesreviews/a137373/mariah-carey-i-stay-in-love.html|title=Mariah: 'I Stay in Love'|last=Balls|first=David|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=March 31, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> Freedom De Luc from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described the song as an \"emotive ballad\",<ref name=post>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/14/AR2008041403143.html|title=Mariah Sticks to Known Equation|last=De Luc|first=Freedom|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=April 15, 2008|accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> while Nekesa Mumbi Moody from ''[[Foster's Daily Democrat]]'' noted \"it could have been recorded in her early '90s heyday \u2014 except it's not as saccharine as some of her early work\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080421/GJLIFESTYLES/173868905/-1/FOSLIFESTYLES|title=Music Review: Mariah Carey's 'E=MC2' Recaptures the Magic of Her Best-selling 'Emancipation'|last=Moody|first=Nekesa Mumbi|work=[[Foster's Daily Democrat]]|publisher=[[Geo. J. Foster Company]]|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref> However, Evan Sawdey of [[PopMatters]] described it as one of the album's \"worst songs\".<ref name=pop>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/mariah-carey-emc2|title=Mariah Carey: E=MC\u00b2 < Reviews |last=Sawey|first=Evan|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|date=March 1, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n=== Background ===\n{{Citations broken|section|date=January 2019}}\nDirected by Carey's then-husband [[Nick Cannon]], the music video for \"I Stay in Love\" was filmed in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], using a story line that Cannon and Carey co-wrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/news/10731|title=Mariah Set to Shoot Video for New Single I Stay In Love|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> Carey filmed the video on October 5, at The Bank Nightclub of [[Bellagio (hotel and casino)|The Bellagio Hotel and Casino Resort]], and in the [[Mojave Desert]] on October 6, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lvrj.com/news/30506429.html|title=Bobbitt Trains for Boxing Bout in LV|last=Clarke|first=Norm|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|publisher=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]]|date=October 6, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> In an interview with [[Ryan Seacrest]], Cannon spoke about the video and said that there is a scene where Carey is in bed with a man (played by Andrew Karelis), and that \"Mariah plays the showgirl and there's a guy who cheated and there's flashbacks......\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,446144,00.html|title=Mariah Carey Spied Kissing New Man, And It's Not Her Husband|last=Friedman|first=Roger|work=Fox News|publisher=News Corporation|date=April 3, 2008|accessdate=August 6, 2011}}</ref> The music video for \"I Stay In Love\" was featured on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[Access Granted]]'' for a behind-the-scenes look and a world premiere on October 27, 2008.<ref name=vidd>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/news/10711|title=Mariah Shoots New Video in Las Vegas|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The entire video was shown every hour on BET until October 28, 2008.<ref name=vidd/> \"I Stay in Love\" music video peaked at #16 on [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'s Hot Videoclip Tracks chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/3103111|title=Hot Videoclip Tracks|magazine=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|date=December 6, 2008|accessdate=October 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Synopsis ===\n[[Image:Mimistaywith.jpg|thumb|right|250px|In the image, Carey is seen dressed in white garments and large feathers. She is featured as a dancer in Las Vegas, and is where she discovers her ex-lover has moved on.]]\nThe video, black-and-white, begins with Carey parking her antique automobile in desert. She gets out, with customized black boots with an 'M' on them, and as, she walks towards the camera, the vehicle explodes. As the music begins and the scene shifts to another where Carey applying her eye make-up and earrings. As a form of product placement, her fragrance is shown on a dresser in her [[Boudoir]]. As Carey finishes getting ready, scenery of Las Vegas is shown, before shifting to Carey, now dressed as a Vegas performer. As she walks down a runway dressed in white garments ad feathers, she catches the attention of a man. He turns out to be Carey's ex-lover, who in turn came to the show to meet with one of Carey's fellow dancers. As he caresses the female in the dressing room, Carey sees them, and walks by them, bumping into him purposely. Additional scenes are shown of Carey laying alone on the dark runway, apparently after the show has finished, as well as preparing herself for the show. During the second verse, the video then shows Carey driving down a highway in the desert, and as she drives, past memories of the pair are shown, holding each other intimately in a bed. She then pushes old gifts he had given her into the passengers seat, and pulls over the car, continuing the scene from the beginning of the video. After the car explodes, Carey tears off her necklace in despair, and begins to flail her arms in desperation. The video ends with Carey back at the show in Vegas during the finale, as glitter drops from the top of the stage. Carey, now back in the desert, looks for another ride, and gets into a black [[Cadillac]] [[Escalade]] driven by Nick Cannon.\n\n=== Reception and ''Luscious Pink'' commercial ===\nNick Levine from Digital Spy complimented the video, commenting that it managed \"to be both ridiculous and a little bit moving - quite an achievement.\"<ref name=\"digitally\"/> ''Entertainment Weekly'' writer Michael Slezak described Carey's boots as \"hot\", and considered the cinematography of the music video \"gorgeous\". He also complimented several aspects of the video, saying, \"Mariah\u2019s bod looks totally smokin\u2019, even if her entire wardrobe should be donated to a charity benefiting teenage strumpets and/or truck-stop hookers. Also: That [[Wentworth Miller]] 2.0 ain\u2019t hard on the eyes, either (in reference to the man who played her love interest in \"We Belong Together\").<ref name=entrainment/>\n\nThe commercial for Carey's ''[[Luscious Pink]]'' fragrance uses part of the \"I Stay in Love\" music video, with a clip of the song used as audio.<ref name=frag>{{cite web|url=http://mariahcarey.com/node/711|title=Watch Mariah's New Luscious Pink Commercial|publisher=Mariahcarey.com|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The short clip shows Carey getting ready for the Vegas show, by applying her make-up and lipstick, and also applying the fragrance on her neck and cleavage.<ref name=frag/> The release published on Carey's official website described the concept of the commercial as \"a combination of Mariah's two passions - music and fragrance.\"<ref name=frag/>\n\n== Live performances ==\nDue to promotion for ''E=MC\u00b2'' and the single, Carey was featured as a guest judge and musical act on the [[The X Factor (UK series 5)|fifth series]] of the popular British talent competition, ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref name=dailyness>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/2008/11/07/what-a-carey-on-86908-20875348/|title=Mariah Carey Will Show The X Factor What a Diva is, Says Dannii Minogue|last=Dingwall|first=John|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=November 7, 2008|accessdate=August 9, 2011}}</ref> During that week, all the contestants would have to sing songs from Carey's catalog.<ref name=dailyness/> Prior to her arrival, one of the show's judges [[Dannii Minogue]] said \"Could it get any more nerve-wracking for the contestants?\", due to the general strenuous nature of Carey's songs.<ref name=dailyness/> Before any of the performances by the finalists, Carey performed \"I Stay in Love\", accompanied by three background vocalists. She received a standing ovation from the audience and judges, and continued backstage for a taped session with the contestants. At the end of the program, she performed her classic \"[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]\" (1993), and was eventually joined by the finalists for the finale of the song.<ref name=bbc2>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7718192.stm|title=Laura White is voted off X Factor|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=November 8, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> \"Hero\" was re-recorded by the [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 5)|2008 UK X Factor finalists]] and released as a single, becoming the second best-selling single of 2008 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7802941.stm|title=Duffy and Burke top 2008 charts|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=December 29, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> According to reports, the episode gained a large increase in viewers due to Carey's presence, and was able to surpass its long-time rival program, ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'', in the ratings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_mariah-carey-to-appear-on-the-x-factor_1201735|title=Mariah Appears on the X Factor|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|publisher=Diligent Media Corporation|date=November 8, 2008|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref> Carey also made an appearance at the [[American Music Awards]] of 2008 on November 23, at the [[L.A. Live#Nokia Theatre|Nokia Theatre]].<ref name=mtv6/> Wearing a long black gown, she performed the song after receiving an honorary award for her achievements in music.<ref name=mtv6/> Chris Harris from MTV News described it as a \"riveting performance\".<ref name=mtv6>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1599998/kanye-west-offers-his-award-lil-wayne-at-american-music-awards.jhtml|title=Kanye West Offers His Award To Lil Wayne, Chris Brown Named Artist Of The Year At American Music Awards|last=Harris|first=Chris|work=[[MTV News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Formats==\n'''Remix EP'''<ref name=\"4 track EP\"/>\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Jody den Broeger Radio Edit) \u2013 4:08\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Ralph Rosario Melodic Radio Edit) \u2013 3:50\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Jody Den Broeder House Mix) \u2013 8:29\n# \"I Stay In Love\" (Ralph Rosario Big Vocal) \u2013 8:12\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Chart (2008)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Bulgaria Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=https://acharts.co/song/42577|title=I Stay In Love by Mariah Carey - Music Charts}}</ref>\n| 24\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|95|artist=Mariah Carey|song=I Stay In Love|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[UK R&B]] (Official Charts Company)<ref name=\"UK\"/>\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Pop 100]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref name=\"AllMusic Awards\"/>\n| 95\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|81|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|37|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Chart (2009)\n!scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|1|artist=Mariah Carey|rowheader=true|accessdate=June 5, 2017}}\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Year-end charts ===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2009)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Dance Club Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2009/hot-dance-club-play-songs|title=Best of 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Dance/Club Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|48\n|}\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Wikipedia books|1=E=MC\u00b2 (Mariah Carey album)}}\n* [[List of number-one dance singles of 2009 (U.S.)]]\n* [[Artists with the most number-ones on the U.S. dance chart]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|mariah-carey|i-stay-in-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\