{"title_page": "Ricky Martin", "text_new": "{{about|the singer|other uses|Ricky Martin (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Puerto Rican singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Mart\u00edn|Morales}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ricky Martin\n| image              = File:Ricky Martin in store appearance, Sydney Australia (1).jpg\n| caption            = Martin in 2014\n| birth_name         = Enrique Mart\u00edn Morales\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|12|24}}<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrities/ricky-martin | title=Ricky Martin | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018 |work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref><ref name = IMDb-bio>{{cite web| url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0005193/bio | title=Ricky Martin Biography | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018 |work=[[IMDb]]}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]<ref name = IMDb-bio />\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| citizenship        = {{flatlist|\n* United States\n* Spain\n}}\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* actor\n* author\n* humanitarian.\n}}\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Jwan Yosef]]|2017}}<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/01/11/ricky-martin-reveals-he-and-jwan-yosef-married/1023547001 | title=Ricky Martin reveals he and Jwan Yosef are married: 'I'm a husband' | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=January 11, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n| children           = 4\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Latin music|Latin]]\n* [[urban pop]]\n}}\n| instrument         = Vocals\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Latin]]\n* [[Sony Music|Sony Mexico]]\n* [[Sony Classical]]\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|rickymartinmusic.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Enrique Mart\u00edn Morales''' ({{IPA-es|en\u02c8\u027eike ma\u027e\u02c8tin mo\u02c8\u027eales}}; born December 24, 1971), better known as '''Ricky Martin''', is a [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] singer, actor, and author who is known as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King of Latin Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/ricky-martin-host-biggest-night-latin-music-19-years-after-performing-inaugural-show| title=Ricky Martin To Host The Biggest Night In Latin Music 19 Years After Performing At Inaugural Show| accessdate=October 26, 2019 |date=October 25, 2019 | work=[[Grammy]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://time.com/5526369/grammys-2019-camila-cabello-border-wall | title=Camila Cabello's Grammy Performance Had a Hidden Anti-Wall Message | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=February 11, 2019|work=[[Time (Magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.it/tv/news-tv/amici-2019-ricky-martin-sara-coach-al-serale/450243/ | title='Amici 2019', Ricky Martin sar\u00e0 coach al serale | accessdate=March 17, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019|work=[[Roling Stone]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://qnews.com.au/king-of-latin-pop-vetos-religious-freedoms-bill-ricky-martin-qn-magazine | title=King of Latin Pop vetoes 'religious freedoms' bill | accessdate=July 8, 2019 |date=June 14, 2019 | work=[[QNews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/national-puerto-rico-day-parade-brings-generations-boricuas-together-n1015521 | title=National Puerto Rico Day Parade brings generations of boricuas together | accessdate=July 8, 2019 |date=June 9, 2019 | work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ricky-martin-announces-hes-expecting-20332022 | title=Ricky Martin announces he's expecting fourth child with husband Jwan Yosef | accessdate=October 1, 2019 |date=September 29, 2019 | work=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> He holds dual American and Spanish citizenship,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2011/11/04/ricky-martin-granted-spanish-citizenship/ | title=Ricky Martin granted Spanish citizenship | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=November 4, 2011}}</ref> and began his career at age 12 with the all-boy pop group [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8465853/ricky-martin-watch-scenes-from-emmy-nominee-acting-career | title=Watch Scenes From 'The Assassination of Gianni Versace' Emmy Nominee Ricky Martin's Acting Career | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018}}</ref> After five years with the group, he released several Spanish-language solo albums throughout the 1990s. Since the beginning of his solo career in 1991, Ricky Martin has became one of [[List of best-selling Latin music artists|the\u00a0best-selling Latin music artists\u00a0of all time]] with sales estimates ranging from 70 million records <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/2019/07/25/nota/7442625/ricky-martin-no-dejes-caer-puerto-rico-ahora-es-cuando-mas|title=Ricky Martin: No lo dejes caer, Puerto Rico, ahora es cuando m\u00e1s tenemos que trabajar |work=[[El Universo]]|accessdate=February 16, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> to 85 million albums.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/02/10/ricky-martin-world-tour-concert-phoenix/23177461/|title=Ricky Martin bringing One World Tour to Phoenix|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref> He also acted on stage and on TV in [[Mexico]], where he achieved modest stardom. In 1994, he appeared on the US TV soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]'', playing a Puerto Rican singer.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emmys-flashback-ricky-martin-steamed-up-general-hospital-1994-1130669 | title=Emmys Flashback: Ricky Martin Steamed Up 'General Hospital' in 1994 | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> He also ranks among the most influential Latin artists of all time.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6546212/most-influential-latin-artists | title=The 30 Most Influential Latin Artists of All Time | accessdate=April 25, 2019 |date=April 28, 2015 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1999, after releasing several albums in Spanish, Martin performed \"[[The Cup of Life]]\" at the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]] show, which became a catalyst in bringing Latin pop to the forefront of the U.S. music scene.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9905/17/latin.music/|work=CNN |title=Ricky Martin leading the Latin (music) revolution - May 17, 1999|publisher=}}</ref> Following its success, Martin released \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\", which helped him attain success worldwide. It is generally seen as the song that began the [[Latin pop]] explosion of 1999 and made the transition easier for other Spanish-speaking artists to move into the English-speaking market. His first English-language album (also titled ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]''), sold 15 million copies and is his best selling album to date.<ref>{{cite book|last=Adams|first=Steve|title=Martin's World View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64|date=November 4, 2006|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=64\u2013|id=00062510}}</ref> His other studio albums include: ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]'' (1993), ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]'' (1995), ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998), ''[[Sound Loaded]]'' (2000), ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003), ''[[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]'' (2005), ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' (2011), ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' (2015) and ''Movimiento'' (2020). In 2018, he portrayed [[Antonio D'Amico]] in the miniseries ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'', which earned him a nomination for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===1971\u20131982: Early life===\nMartin was born on December 24, 1971, in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], to Nereida Morales, an accountant, and Enrique Mart\u00edn Negroni (son of Enrique Mart\u00edn and Iraida Negroni Arizmendi),<ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVJX-4LXN Enrique Martin] - Puerto Rico, (Marriage) Civil Registration</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V683-S2T Iraida Negroni Arizmendi] - United States Census, 1930</ref> a psychologist.<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29272|pure_url=yes}}|title=Ricky Martin \u2013 Biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=April 8, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Otfinoski138\">Otfinoski, 2007. p. 138</ref><ref name=\"zen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20133136,00.html|title=Ricky Martin : Zen and Now|work=People|publisher=Time, Inc.|last=Tresniowski|first=Alex|date=December 4, 2000|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin42\">Martin, 2010. p. 42</ref> The youngest of three boys on his mother's side and oldest of four children on his father's side, he has four brothers and one sister. His parents divorced when he was two years old, and Martin spent much of his childhood shifting between his father's home in the suburbs of University Gardens, a suburban middle-class neighborhood of San Juan, and his paternal grandmother's house nearby.<ref name=\"favorite\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-my-favorite-martin-vol-51-no-24/|title=My Favorite Martin|work=People|publisher=Time, Inc.|last=Schneider|first=Karen S.|date=June 28, 1999|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin20\">Martin, 2010. p. 20</ref> Martin has two older maternal half-brothers, Fernando and \u00c1ngel Fern\u00e1ndez, two younger paternal half-brothers, Eric and Daniel Mart\u00edn, and a younger paternal half-sister, Vanessa Mart\u00edn.<ref name=\"zen\"/> Martin, in an interview with newspaper ''[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]'', described his origins as [[Spaniards|Spanish]], of [[Basques|Basque]] and [[Canary Islanders|Canarian]] descent and that the Mart\u00edns left Spain for Puerto Rico in 1779.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/cultura/musica/abci-ricky-martin-nunca-abierto-respecto-sentimientos-como-ahora-201609160149_noticia_amp.html|title=Ricky Martin: Nunca fui tan abierto con respecto a mis sentimientos como ahora|language=Spanish|website=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.revistavanityfair.es/celebrities/articulos/entrevista-ricky-martin-hijos-novio-yo-soy-papa-y-mama-a-mis-hijos-les-contare-la-verdad/20329 |title=Yo soy papa y mama a mis hijos|magazine=Vanity Fair |language=Spanish|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=galaz>{{cite news |url =http://www.elpais.com/articulo/gente/tv/gobierno/concede/Ricky/Martin/nacionalidad/espanola/poder/casarse/elpepugen/20111104elpepuage_3/Tes |title = El gobierno concede a Ricky Martin la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola para poder casarse|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|author = Galaz, Mabel|date = November 4, 2011|accessdate =November 8, 2011}}</ref> He also has some [[Corsicans|Corsican]] heritage through his paternal grandmother.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D5H6yvflq-wC&pg=PT15&lpg=PP1&focus=viewport&dq=ricky%20martin%20me&output=html_text|title=Me|first=Ricky|last=Martin|date=November 2, 2010|publisher=Penguin|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin21\">Martin, 2010. p. 21</ref>\n\nMartin grew up in a [[Roman Catholic]] home and was an [[altar server|altar boy]] throughout his childhood.<ref name=\"Martin18\">Martin, 2010. p. 18</ref> He began singing at age 6, using wooden kitchen spoons as pretended microphones; he often interpreted songs by Menudo as well as English-language rock groups such as [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Journey (band)|Journey]], and [[REO Speedwagon]].<ref name=\"Martin16\">Martin, 2010. p. 16</ref> His mother's side of the family was musically inclined, and his maternal grandfather was a poet, which inspired young Martin to write songs.<ref name=\"Martin16\"/> Martin later reflected on his time spent with his family as a child: \"Every time I find myself in front of an audience, be it twenty people or one hundred thousand, once again I feel the energy that consumed me back at the family gatherings of my youth.\"<ref name=\"Martin17\">Martin, 2010. p. 17</ref> After discovering, with his father, a newspaper advertisement about auditions for commercials, 9-year-old Martin began appearing in Puerto Rican television commercials for products such as soft drinks, toothpaste, and restaurants.<ref name=\"Martin2425\">Martin, 2010. pp. education24-25</ref> In a year and a half, he starred in 11 commercials.<ref name=\"Martin2425\"/>\n\n===1983\u20131990: Menudo===\n{{Listen\n| filename    = Menudo - Rayo de Luna.ogg\n| title       = Menudo \"Rayo de Luna\" (1984)\n| description = At age thirteen, Martin made his recording debut on the song \"Rayo de Luna\", from Menudo's 1984 album, ''[[Evoluci\u00f3n (Menudo album)|Evoluci\u00f3n]]''.<ref name=\"Delatorre34\">De La Torre, 1997. p. 34</ref>\n| format      = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nAfter achieving modest fame in Puerto Rico for his work in television commercials, Martin auditioned for membership in the [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] [[boy band]] [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]]. Although the executives enjoyed his dancing and singing at his first two auditions, Martin was rejected because he was too short.<ref name=\"Martin31\">Martin, 2010. p. 31</ref> By the third audition, his persistence impressed executives, and in 1984, 12-year-old Martin became a member.<ref name=\"Martin3132\">Martin, 2010. pp. 31\u201332</ref> A month after joining Menudo, he made his debut performance with the group at the [[Luis A. Ferr\u00e9 Performing Arts Center]] in San Juan.<ref name=\"Martin33\">Martin, 2010. p. 33</ref> During this performance, he inadvertently disobeyed the choreography by walking around the stage, when it was planned that he would stay still, and was chastised by the band manager after the show: \"The mistake was such a big deal that from that moment on, never again did I move when I wasn't supposed to move...That was the discipline of Menudo: You either did things the way you were told or you were not part of the group.\"<ref name=\"Martin3334\">Martin, 2010. pp. 33\u201334</ref> The song \"Asignatura Pendiente\" from ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003) was inspired by the first time Martin left Puerto Rico to tour with Menudo.<ref name=\"Martin47\">Martin, 2010. p. 47</ref>\n\nAlthough Martin enjoyed traveling and performing onstage with Menudo, he found the band's busy schedule and strict management exhausting, and later reflected that the experience \"cost\" him his childhood.<ref name=\"Martin28\">Martin, 2010. p. 28</ref> He considered leaving the group while on tour in Brazil, but ultimately decided to stay out of fear of media backlash and being sued for breach of contract.<ref name=\"Martin3637\">Martin, 2010. pp. 36\u201337</ref> Martin also began struggling with his sexuality, noting the stark contrast between his status as a [[sex symbol]] and his own emotions.<ref name=VH1behindthemusic>(2002) ''[[Behind the Music]]'': Ricky Martin episode. [[VH1]].</ref> Despite this, Martin acknowledged his \"opportunity to have so many amazing experiences with so many amazing people\" during his time with the group.<ref name=\"Martin37\">Martin, 2010. p. 37</ref>\n\nHe developed an interest in philanthropy when the group became [[UNICEF]] ambassadors, often working with impoverished children in third world countries.<ref name=\"Martin37\"/> His experiences as an ambassador affected him greatly and inspired him to continue working with charities later in life.<ref name=\"Martin37\"/>\n\nBy 1987, Menudo's record sales began to decline, and the group changed its image, adopting an edgier look and performing more rock-influenced songs.<ref name=\"Martin44\">Martin, 2010. p. 44</ref> The band released the album ''[[Somos Los Hijos del Rock]]'' in Spanish, and to appeal to the Menudo's Filipino fanbase, the group released ''[[In Action (Menudo album)|In Action]]'', recording songs in both English and [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]].<ref name=\"Martin44\"/>\n\nAfter recording 11 albums with the group, Martin left Menudo in July 1989, at age 17, hoping to rest and evaluate his career path.<ref name=\"Martin46\">Martin, 2010. p. 46</ref> He performed his final show with the group at the same venue where he'd performed his first performance as a member.<ref name=\"Martin46\"/> Martin returned to Puerto Rico to graduate from high school, and 13 days after turning 18, he moved to New York City to celebrate his financial independence; since he was a minor during his time as a member of Menudo, Martin was not allowed to access his own bank accounts.<ref name=\"Martin58\">Martin, 2010. p. 58</ref> He was accepted into [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], but months before classes began, Martin dropped out and moved to [[Mexico City]] to perform in the play ''Mama Ama el Rock'' (''Mom Loves Rock'').<ref name=\"Martin1819\">Martin, 2010, pp. 18\u201319</ref>\n\n===1991\u20131994: Acting and first two solo albums===\nWhile he was performing onstage in ''Mama Ama el Rock'', a producer in the audience took notice of Martin's acting and offered him a role in the Mexican [[telenovela]] ''[[Alcanzar una estrella]]'' after the show.<ref name=\"Martin66\">Martin, 2010. p. 66</ref> He also joined the cast for the second season of the show, titled ''[[Alcanzar una estrella II]]''.<ref name=\"Martin66\"/> A film based on the TV series, titled ''M\u00e1s que alcanzar una estrella'', was also produced in which Martin starred and in 1993 earned an El Heraldo Award for his role.<ref name=\"Martin67\">Martin, 2010. p. 67</ref> The show centered around a fictional musical group called [[Mu\u00f1ecos de Papel]], in which Martin played Pablo Loredo, one of the six members; the group toured several cities in Mexico and recorded two albums.<ref name=\"Martin66\"/> Although he had hoped to take a break from touring after Menudo, Martin enjoyed the experience because he got along with the other members well.<ref name=\"Martin67\"/>\n\n{{Quote box |bgcolor=#bbccff |salign=right |width=240px |align=right | quote = I was so excited about getting back into the music world that I didn't care what the conditions were...All of the hard work and passion I had exerted was finally now starting to come to fruition, and music came back to my life powerfully and definitively. | source =\u2013 Martin, on recording his debut album.<ref name=\"Martin70\">Martin, 2010. p. 70</ref>}}\n\nIn 1990, Martin was signed to [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Discos]], the [[Sony Music Entertainment]]'s Latin imprint. Eager to make his first solo album, Martin signed the contract without reading it and inadvertently signed a deal in which he would only be awarded one cent of royalties for each album sold.<ref name=\"Martin70\"/> Despite viewing the contract as unfair, Martin referred to the record as \"the start of something phenomenal\" for him.<ref name=\"Martin70\"/> After working \"around the clock\" to finish filming ''Alcanzar una estrella II'' and recording music, Martin released his debut solo album, the Spanish-language ''[[Ricky Martin (1991 album)|Ricky Martin]]'', in November 1991.<ref name=\"Martin7071\">Martin, 2010, pp. 70\u201371</ref> ''Ricky Martin'' included the singles: \"[[Fuego Contra Fuego]]\" and \"[[El Amor de Mi Vida (song)|El Amor de Mi Vida]]\". \"Fuego Contra Fuego\" was certified Gold in Mexico, Argentina, Puerto Rico, and the United States.<ref name=\"Martin71\">Martin, 2010. p. 71</ref> To promote the album, Martin toured throughout Latin America, which the singer referred to as \"an indescribable feeling, almost like coming home.\"<ref name=\"Martin71\"/>\n\nAfter the success of ''Ricky Martin'' and its subsequent tour, Martin's record company met him with acclaimed producer Juan Carlos Calder\u00f3n on his second solo album, ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]''. Although Martin felt \"very grateful\" for the opportunity to work with Calder\u00f3n, he noted, \"I always felt that that record was more his than mine.\"<ref name=\"Martin87\">Martin, 2010, p. 87</ref> Released in May 1993, ''Me Amaras'' features a Spanish-language cover of the [[Laura Branigan]] song \"[[Self Control (Raf song)|Self Control]]\", titled \"[[Self Control (Raf song)#Ricky Martin version|Que Dia Es Hoy]]\".<ref name=\"MeamarasAM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/me-amar%C3%A1s-mw0000100600|title=Review: Ricky Martin \u2013 Me Amaras|last=Henderson|first=Alex|work=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> In his review, Alex Henderson of [[AllMusic]] wrote, \"The CD isn't without its pleasures...but on the whole, ''Me Amaras'' is too glossy, too calculated, and much too contrived for its own good.\"<ref name=\"MeamarasAM\"/>\n\nIn 1994, Martin's agent encouraged him to move to Los Angeles to act in an American sitcom called ''[[Getting By]]''.<ref name=\"Martin76\">Martin, 2010. p. 76</ref> The show was canceled after two seasons, but soon afterward, Martin was given the role of singer/bartender Miguel Morez on the soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref name=\"Martin7778\">Martin, 2010, pp. 77\u201378</ref> Martin felt he lacked chemistry with the rest of the ''General Hospital'' cast and observed that people treated him differently because of his Puerto Rican accent.<ref name=\"Martin7879\">Martin, 2010, pp. 78\u201379</ref> At the time, it was relatively uncommon for Hispanic people to appear on American television, and people suggested that he take accent reduction classes, which he refused.<ref name=\"Martin7778\"/> It was during this time, however, that Martin began his first committed relationship with a man.<ref name=\"Martin81\">Martin, 2010. p. 81</ref> He \"stopped fearing his sexuality\", and soon [[Coming out|came out]] to his mother, who was supportive of him.<ref name=\"Martin81\"/> However, after the relationship ended, Martin \"locked [his] feelings even deeper inside\", and began dating women again.<ref name=\"Martin82\">Martin, 2010. p. 82</ref> He recalled, \"I already felt it was hard to be a Latino in Hollywood; what could have been more difficult than being Latino and gay?\"<ref name=\"Martin84\">Martin, 2010. p. 84</ref>\n\n===1995\u20131998: ''A Medio Vivir'', ''Vuelve'', and breakthrough===\nIn 1995, Martin refocused on his music career, and began work on his third album, ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]''. The first single, the ballad \"[[Te Extra\u00f1o, Te Olvido, Te Amo]]\", written by the producer of [[Lynda Thomas]], Carlos Lara, was reminiscent of his earlier work.<ref name=\"Martin102\">Martin, 2010. p. 102</ref> With the song, Martin furthered his expansion from Latin American and Spanish-speaking audiences to the European and Asian markets.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r224606|pure_url=yes}} AllMusic]</ref> However, the record also made a shift from his traditional ballad-style compositions to a more risky fusion of music centered around traditional Latin sounds, epitomized by the song \"[[Mar\u00eda (Ricky Martin song)|Maria]]\". Taken aback by the starkly different musical style, record label executives felt that the song would ruin Martin's career.<ref name=\"Martin103\">Martin, 2010. p. 103</ref> Despite this, \"Maria\" was chosen as the album's second single, and became a breakthrough hit, reaching number one in France, Spain, Germany, Belgium, Holland, Switzerland, Finland, Italy, Turkey, and the entire continent of South America.<ref name=\"Martin103\"/> With ''A Medio Vivir'', Martin was credited, along with singers [[Chayanne]] and [[Marc Anthony]], for popularizing the music of Puerto Rico in Spain.<ref name=\"spanishmarket\">{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA61-IA2&lpg=RA1-PA61-IA2&dq=ricky+martin+a+medio+vivir&source=bl&ots=bqqrnCl1FZ&sig=fBmYD5iWZNkusJcpy1xthEWLRMI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xa0LUL7rCIfMqAHrtK28Cg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=ricky%20martin%20a%20medio%20vivir&f=false|title=Breaking Into the Spanish Market|last=Llewellyn|first=Howell|work=Billboard |date=October 7, 2000|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> The album has sold over 3 million copies worldwide.\n\nIn a 1996 interview with ''[[The Miami Herald]]'', Martin expressed an interest in performing on Broadway. Days after the interview was released Martin received a phone call from producer [[Richard Jay-Alexander]], offering him the role of [[Marius Pontmercy]] in the play ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''.<ref name=\"Martin89\">Martin, 2010. p. 89</ref> After the conclusion of a worldwide tour in support of ''A Medio Vivir'', Martin returned to New York to appear in the play in an eleven-week run.<ref name=\"Martin90\">Martin, 2010. p. 90</ref> He greatly enjoyed the experience, calling his time in the play an \"honor\" and \"the role of [his] life\".<ref name=\"Martin90\"/> Martin continued to tour after the conclusion of the show's run, and noted that his audiences were growing in both size and enthusiasm.<ref name=\"Martin104\">Martin, 2010. p. 104</ref> In 1997, Martin was invited to the prestigious [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in [[Sanremo]], Italy. After landing in Milan, Martin's scheduled helicopter trip to Sanremo had to be postponed due to poor weather conditions.<ref name=\"Martin106\">Martin, 2010. p. 106</ref> Hoping to arrive at the festival on time, Martin and his crew drove through the mountainous terrain at over 120 miles per hour. The car then turned too quickly and flipped over.<ref name=\"Martin106\"/> However, \"none of us had more than a couple of scratches and bruises\" and he arrived at the festival on time by taxi later that day.<ref name=\"Martin106\"/> In the summer of 1997, Martin embarked on a tour of Spain, performing 45 shows in 36 cities.<ref name=\"Martin107\">Martin, 2010. p. 107</ref>\n\nWhile on tour, Martin returned to the studio to record his fourth album, ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998). He called the experience of touring and recording at the same time \"brutal and incredibly intense\".<ref name=\"Martin108\">Martin, 2010. p. 108</ref> As he was finishing the record, the singer was contacted by [[FIFA]] to write a song for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]]; Martin subsequently wrote \"[[The Cup of Life|La copa de la vida]]\" with [[K. C. Porter]] and [[Draco Rosa]].<ref name=\"Martin108109\">Martin, 2010. pp. 108\u2013109</ref> He performed the song at the World Cup final in the [[Stade de France]] on July 12, 1998.<ref name=\"Martin109\">Martin, 2010. p. 109</ref> The performance, which was broadcast to over a billion viewers in 187 countries, was described as a \"global moment for Latin pop\".<ref name=\"Holt165\">Holt, 2007. p. 165</ref> \"La copa de la vida\" reached No. 1 on the charts around the world and went gold and platinum in various countries. It was awarded Pop Song of the Year at the 1999 [[Lo Nuestro Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=490994 |title=Lo Nuestro 1999 \u2013 Historia de Premio lo Nuestro |publisher=Univision |accessdate=August 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403132343/http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=490994 |archivedate=April 3, 2010 }}</ref> The [[Vuelve (Ricky Martin song)|title track]] and the ballad \"[[Perdido Sin T\u00ed]]\" both hit number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. Further singles included: \"[[La Bomba (Ricky Martin song)|La Bomba]]\", \"[[Por Arriba, Por Abajo]]\" and \"[[Corazonado]]\". ''Vuelve'' spent twenty-six weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]]. It became Martin's first top forty album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the United States, where it was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. The album also went to number one in Spain and Norway, and sold over eight million copies worldwide.<ref>[http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Ricky+Martin&titel=Vuelve&cat=a/ Ricky Martin \u2013 Vuelve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102155613/http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Ricky+Martin&titel=Vuelve&cat=a%2F |date=January 2, 2016 }}. norwegiancharts.com. Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nMartin was nominated for his first Grammy Award for ''Vuelve'' in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]], and was booked to sing on the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]] live TV broadcast. His acclaimed performance of \"La copa de la vida\" earned Martin an unexpected standing ovation and introduced him to the mainstream American audience. Being aware of performing on the Grammy, he said that:\"The excitement is more than being nominated for the award. The audience in front of me are people who are hard to please. [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]! [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]! [[Luciano Pavarotti]]! To get the acceptance of your peers really means a lot.\"<ref name=\"smashing\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/01/entertainment/ca-34681|title=A Smashing Start for Ricky Martin|work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 1, 1999|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin115\">Martin, 2010. p. 115</ref> Martin won the Grammy Award later that evening, and even superstars [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] went backstage to congratulate him.<ref name=\"Martin116\">Martin, 2010. p. 116</ref> His appearance sparked nationwide interest in Latin music. Writing for ''Billboard'' on April 24, 1999, Michael Paoletta noted, \"In the weeks since [the performance], it seems like every record label exec has been in a heated search for the next Latin hottie.\"<ref name=\"paoletta\">{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eigEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=ricky+martin+sensation&source=bl&ots=-XoJZ-_KcN&sig=YqsasIUw3LbdUP1fhkzilnoqdAM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZPkbUJjdB4GciQLV9YDoCg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=ricky%20martin%20sensation&f=false|title=Can New Jersey's Spicy Sin Match Martin's Latin Sizzle?|work=Billboard |last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=April 24, 1999|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1999\u20132002: Crossover to English===\n{{Listen\n| filename    = Ricky Martin Livin La Vida Loca.ogg\n| title       = Ricky Martin \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" (1999)\n| description = \n| format      = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nAfter receiving commercial success throughout [[Asia]], [[Europe]], and [[Latin America]], Martin prepared his first English album in 1999 in an attempt to cross over to the United States market.<ref name=\"Martin112\">Martin, 2010. p. 112</ref> The [[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|self-titled]] album, which debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and sold 661,000 copies in its first week of release, became the most successful album debut on the ''Billboard'' charts by a Hispanic artist.<ref name=\"debuts\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1999-05-21/news/9905210215_1_ricky-martin-pop-music-charts-divorce|title=Ricky Martin Debuts As No. 1|work=Orlando Sentinel |publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 21, 1999|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> It contained material by writers and producers such as [[Desmond Child]], [[Diane Warren]], [[William Orbit]], [[George Noriega]] and his longtime childhood friend [[Draco Rosa]]. The album also featured special guests: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] on the Spanish-English duet \"Be Careful (Cuidado con mi Coraz\u00f3n)\" and [[Sertab Erener]] on \"[[Private Emotion]]\".<ref name=\"rickymartinrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ricky-martin-1999-mw0000238986|title=Ricky Martin \u2013 Album Review|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|work=AllMusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after the album's release, Martin was featured on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' with the title \"Latin Music Goes Pop!\".<ref name=\"timecover\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19990524,00.html|title=Time Magazine Cover: Ricky Martin \u2013 May 24, 1999|work=Time|publisher=Time, Inc.|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> Before the album's release, [[Janet Jackson]] collaborated with Ricky Martin for the Latin American version of \"[[Ask for More]]\", a promotional single and commercial released as part of an advertising campaign for soft drink company [[Pepsi]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xXQnfMiZIos Janet Jackson & Ricky Martin \u2013 \"Ask for More\" Pepsi Ad (Latin American Version)]. Retrieved on June 17, 2013</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Basham |first=David |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431862/ricky-martin-inks-endorsement-deal-with-pepsi-preps-fall-tour.jhtml |title=Ricky Martin Inks Endorsement Deal With Pepsi, Preps For Fall Tour |publisher=Mtv.com |date=October 15, 1999 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe first and most prominent single was \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\", which reached number one in many countries around the world, including the United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Ireland and New Zealand. \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" is Ricky Martin's biggest hit. The video for \"Livin 'La Vida Loca\" was directed by [[Wayne Isham]] and starring model [[Nina Moric]]. It was followed by \"[[She's All I Ever Had]]\" which peaked at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Both tracks peaked at number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" is generally seen as the song that began the [[Latin pop]] explosion of 1999 and made the transition of other Latin artists (first [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Enrique Iglesias]], then later [[Shakira]]) into the English-speaking market easier. ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' became one of the top-selling albums of 1999, and was certified 7\u00d7 platinum in the United States, selling over 15 million copies worldwide. In October 1999, Martin embarked on a very successful year-long [[Livin' la Vida Loca Tour]].\n\nAfter this success, a new English-language album, ''[[Sound Loaded]]'', was released in November 2000. It debuted at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and was certified 2\u00d7 platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. \"[[She Bangs]]\" and \"[[Nobody Wants to Be Lonely]]\" (duet with [[Christina Aguilera]]) peaked at number twelve and thirteen on the Billboard Hot 100, respectively. Both singles reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs. ''Sound Loaded'' has sold over 8 million copies worldwide.\n\nIn February 2001, Martin released a Spanish greatest hits album entitled ''[[La Historia (Ricky Martin album)|La Historia]]'', which went to number one for five weeks on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] and debuted at number eighty-three on the Billboard 200. It also topped the chart in Sweden for three weeks. The album contained reworkings of two of his early songs \"[[Fuego Contra Fuego]]\" and \"[[El Amor de Mi Vida (song)|El Amor de Mi Vida]]\". In November 2001, an English-language greatest hits album, ''[[The Best of Ricky Martin]]'' was released outside North America. It contained two new remixes of \"[[Amor (Ricky Martin song)|Amor]]\".\n\n===2003\u20132006: ''Almas del Silencio''===\n[[File:Ricky Martin 2005.jpg|thumb|Ricky Martin in 2005.]]\n\nIn May 2003 Martin released a new Spanish album ''[[Almas del Silencio]].'' The first single \"[[Tal Vez]]\" debuted at number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]] and stayed there for eleven weeks becoming the best performing Latin single of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/yearendcharts/2003/htltitl.jsp|title=Year-End Charts: Hot Latin Songs|date=December 27, 2003|work=Billboard |accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref> Martin said of the new album: \"I really needed to go back to focus, to my center, to the beginning. I had the need to search within, and really dig deep, and find those emotions that, because of the adrenaline and the euphoria that I lived for a couple of years, were probably sabotaged.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2003/vol7n26/LivinSerious-en.html |title=Livin' The Serious Life; Ricky Martin's New Album Matches His Outlook |publisher=Puertorico-herald.org |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' debuted at number twelve on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and reached number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] where it stayed for six weeks. The album sold more than one million copies worldwide.<ref name=BB>Adams, Steve: \"Martin's World View\", ''Billboard'' magazine, November 4, 2006, pp. 64\u201366.</ref> The next singles, \"[[Jaleo (Ricky Martin song)|Jaleo]]\" and \"[[Y Todo Queda en Nada]],\" reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs. \"[[Jaleo (Ricky Martin song)|Jaleo]]\" also topped the chart in Spain for four weeks.\n\nIn October 2005, he released his album [[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]. He commented on the album: \"I was really in touch with my emotions. I think this album is very multi-layered, just like life is. It's about feeling anger. It's about feeling joy. It's about feeling uncertainty. It's about feeling. And all my emotions are part of this production.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/11/11/earlyshow/leisure/music/main1038774.shtml|title=Ricky Martin Lets 'Life' Happen|author=Tatiana Morales|date=November 11, 2005|accessdate=February 15, 2010|publisher=Cbsnews.com}}</ref> The album debuted at number six on the [[Billboard 200]]. The first single from the album \"[[I Don't Care (Ricky Martin song)|I Don't Care]]\" featured rap verses by [[Fat Joe]] and [[Amerie]]. It peaked at number three on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] and number sixty-five on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Another song from the album \"[[It's Alright (Ricky Martin song)|It's Alright]]\" was re-recorded as a duet with French singer [[M. Pokora]]. It was successful in French-speaking countries and reached #4 in France.\n\n===2006\u20132007: ''MTV Unplugged'' and a world tour===\nOn August 17, 2006, Ricky Martin taped his ''[[MTV Unplugged (Ricky Martin album)|MTV Unplugged]]'' concert in Miami. It premiered on [[MTV Latin America]], [[Tr3s|MTV Tr3s]] and [[WJPX|MTV Puerto Rico]] in October 2006 and was released on CD and DVD in November 2006. The album was a critical and commercial success. It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] and number thirty-eight on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. At the [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2008]], ''MTV Unplugged'' received [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Album]] and for [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]. The first single, \"[[Tu Recuerdo (Ricky Martin song)|Tu Recuerdo]]\" which featured La Mari of [[Chambao]], reached number one for three weeks on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. The next single, \"[[P\u00e9gate]]\" peaked at number six on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].\n\nOn February 19, 2007, Martin began his worldwide [[Black and White Tour]]<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> which started with a performance at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum]] in Puerto Rico and concluded with a presentation at the [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City on October 14, 2007.<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> He also recorded a duet with [[Eros Ramazzotti]], \"[[Non siamo soli]]\" which topped the Italian chart for eleven consecutive weeks.\n\n===2007\u20132010: Career break===\nAfter finishing his worldwide tour, Martin took a break from the music industry and focused on his private life. In November 2007, [[Sony Music Latin|Sony BMG Norte]] released ''[[Ricky Martin Live: Black and White Tour]]'' on CD, DVD, and Blu-ray Disc. One year later, a Spanish-language greatest hits album was released, titled ''[[17 (Ricky Martin album)|17]]''. It was a summary of 17 years of Martin's musical career, which included mostly Spanish-language songs.\n\n===2010\u20132013: Autobiography, ''M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo'' and ''Evita''===\n[[File:Ricky Martin Chicago.jpg|thumb|180px|Martin performing in Chicago on April 19, 2011.]]\nRicky Martin's autobiography, ''Me'', was published on November 2, 2010. The book became part of [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2010-11-21/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jennifer | last=Schuessler | title=Hardcover}}</ref> debuting at number five on the Hardcover Nonfiction list. A Spanish-language edition entitled ''Yo'' was published simultaneously.\n\nMartin's single, \"[[Lo Mejor de Mi Vida Eres T\u00fa]]\" featuring [[Natalia Jimenez]] also premiered on November 2, 2010 and peaked at number seventy-four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and topped the [[Hot Latin Songs]] for two weeks. It was followed by a new studio album, ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' released on January 31, 2011.<ref name = \"2011 album\">[http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i1c1499752deb3a60c4f4222c2ce37750 Leila Cobo, \"Ricky Martin Confirms Bilingual Album\"], ''Billboard'', October 20, 2010</ref> It debuted at number three on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and became the highest charting, primarily-Spanish language album in the United States, since ''[[Dreaming of You (Selena album)|Dreaming of You]]'' by [[Selena]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473151/nicki-minaj-hits-no-1-on-billboard-200-crosses-1-million-sales Nicki Minaj Hits No. 1 on Billboard 200, Crosses 1 Million Sales]. Retrieved February 11, 2011.</ref> ''M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo'' also represents the highest ever chart debut on the Billboard 200 for a [[Sony Music Latin]] release.<ref>[http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/Blog/Post/ec65e9ba-ec27-42da-9908-4ef3431c4c02 Ricky Martin delivers Latin music's highest chart debut in the last 15 years] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129190129/http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/Blog/Post/ec65e9ba-ec27-42da-9908-4ef3431c4c02 |date=January 29, 2013 }}. Retrieved February 11, 2011.</ref> It spent two weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]]. On March 25, 2011, Martin started his [[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo World Tour]], which ended on November 12, 2011. The second single from the album, \"[[M\u00e1s (Ricky Martin song)|M\u00e1s]]\" was released on April 5, 2011 and peaked at number seven on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]]. \"[[Fr\u00edo (song)|Fr\u00edo]]\" featuring [[Wisin & Yandel]] was chosen as the third single.\n\n''[[17: Greatest Hits]]'' was released on July 11, 2011 exclusively in the United Kingdom. Ricky Martin was playing [[Che Guevara in popular culture#In theater|Ch\u00e9]] in the Broadway revival of the show ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'', scheduled to begin previews on Broadway in March 2012, ahead of an opening in April 2012.<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/EVITA_w_Martin_Roger_Begins_Previews_Mar_2012_Opens_Apr_2012_20110121 EVITA w/ Martin & Roger Begins Previews Mar. 2012; Opens Apr. 2012 2011/01/21]. Broadwayworld.com. Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> He received mixed reviews.\n\nMartin guest-starred as a Spanish teacher on the Fox TV show ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode \"[[The Spanish Teacher]]\" on February 7, 2012. Martin premiered his \"Ricky's Lip Conditioner\" lip balm in April 2012 as part of the M.A.C Cosmetics \"Ricky and Nicki for Viva Glam\" campaign. The advertisements for the range paired him with rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Martin's signature is featured on the lip balm packaging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maccosmetics.com/vivaglam2012/collection.html |title=M.A.C Viva Glam Collection |publisher=Maccosmetics.com |date= |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126195524/http://www.maccosmetics.com/vivaglam2012/collection.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013: ''The Voice Australia'', \"Come with Me\" and an Australian tour===\n[[File:Ricky Martin cropped1.jpg#mediaviewer/File:Ricky Martin cropped1.jpg|thumb|Martin in 2011]]\nIn November 2012, Martin was announced as a coach on ''[[The Voice (Australian TV series)|The Voice Australia]]'' and debuted in the first episode of season two, on April 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/ricky-martin-replaces-keith-urban-on-the-voice/story-e6frg6n6-1226526911581 | work=The Australian | title=Ricky Martin replaces Keith Urban on The Voice | date=November 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/first-review-of-the-voice-2013/news-story/f1438bae17f1b6710ef2313695cfb5ab|title=First review of The Voice 2013|date=2013-04-05|website=Daily Telegraph |language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> The finale aired on June 17. His finalist was former [[Ten Tenors]] singer [[Luke Kennedy]]. He became Runner-up losing to eventual winner [[Harrison Craig]].\n\nIn April 2013, Martin released his ''[[Greatest Hits: Souvenir Edition]]'' album in Australia, where it reached number two on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified Gold. In June 2013, he released a new English single titled \"[[Come with Me (Ricky Martin song)|Come with Me]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/1566940/ricky-martins-new-single-come-with-me-listen |title=Ricky Martin's New Single, 'Come With Me': Listen |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> He also embarked on the [[2013 Australian Tour]] in October 2013. In February 2014, he appeared with [[Jennifer Lopez]] & [[Wisin]] on the single and video \"[[Adrenalina (Wisin song)|Adrenalina]]\" taken from Wisin's album ''[[El Regreso del Sobreviviente]]''. The album version contains Spanish lyrics but the single was also made available in a [[Spanglish]] version. In April 2014, the single & video were released for \"[[Vida (Ricky Martin song)|Vida]]\", from the FIFA compilation album ''[[One Love, One Rhythm \u2013 The 2014 FIFA World Cup Official Album]]''. Here, the album version contains Spanglish lyrics, but the digital EP contained versions in Spanish & Portuguese as well as various dance remixes.\n\n===2014\u20132018: ''The Voice Mexico'', ''A Quien Quiera Escuchar'', One World Tour and The Assassination of Gianni Versace===\nIn July 2014, Martin was announced as a coach on ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico|The Voice Mexico]]''. The first episode of season four was aired on September 9, 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.tvnotas.com.mx/2014/09/07/C-65520-todos-los-detalles-del-gran-inicio-de-la-voz-mexico-2014.php | work=TV Notas | title=Todos los detalles del gran inicio de 'La Voz... M\u00e9xico 2014' | date=September 7, 2014}}</ref> On October 3, 2014, Martin started his Mexican One World Tour on [[Mexico City]], followed by [[Guadalajara]], [[Monterrey]] and [[Ensenada, Baja California|Ensenada]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/ | work=Ricky Martin Music | title= Ricky Martin: One World Tour Dates | date=September 7, 2014}}</ref> In November 2014, he was the closing act of the opening ceremony for the 22nd [[Central American and Caribbean Games]] \"[[2014 Central American and Caribbean Games|Veracruz 2014]]\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2264821-central-american-and-caribbean-games-2014-dates-schedule-events-and-countries | work=Bleacher Report | title=Central American and Caribbean Games 2014: Dates, Schedule, Events and Countries | date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince Martin's debut as a coach on [[The Voice Australia]] in 2013, he continued as a coach on [[The Voice (Australia season 3)|Season 3]], in 2014, alongside [[will.i.am]], [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Joel Madden]]. He returned to the panel alongside [[Delta Goodrem]], [[Benji Madden]] (teamed up with his brother [[Joel Madden]]), and newcomer [[Jessie J]] in 2015; before leaving the show before the [[The Voice (Australia season 5)|fifth series]] to focus on music commitments.\n\nMartin released his album ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' in February 2015. The album won the [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Latin Pop Album]], making this Martin's second Grammy win to date.\n\nIt was announced on December 24, 2015 that he would not return to The Voice Australia in 2016 and will be replaced by [[Ronan Keating]].\n\nOn September 22, 2016, Martin released a new song \"[[Vente Pa' Ca]]\" with Colombian singer, [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]. The song skyrocketed in music charts with over 1.6 billion views on the music video as of February 2020.\n\nIn November 2016, Martin announced a Las Vegas residency show, [[All In (residency show)|All In]], which began on April 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7580424/ricky-martin-las-vegas-residency-dates-monte-carlo|title=Ricky Martin Reveals Las Vegas Residency Dates: 'I Have Been Thinking About This for Years'|date=November 16, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Martin portrayed [[Antonio D'Amico]], partner of fashion designer [[Gianni Versace]], in the second season of the true crime television series ''[[American Crime Story]]'', subtitled ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]''. The show was praised but Martin's performance and characterization of D'Amico received mixed reception. Despite this, Martin was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie]], his first ever nomination.\n\nMartin released his single, \"[[Fiebre (Ricky Martin song)|Fiebre]]\", on February 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ricky Martin&nbsp;\u2013 Fiebre (feat. Wisin & Yandel)|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/fiebre-feat-wisin-yandel-single/1350862364|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> And its music video has over 100 million views on YouTube as of November 2019.\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Movimiento'' and Movimiento Tour===\n\nMartin announced his new album will be released on 2020 and he started his world tour, [[Movimiento Tour]] on February 7, 2020.\n\n==Musical style==\nMartin possesses a [[tenor]] vocal range.<ref name=\"books.google.ca\">{{Cite book|title=Rock-N-Roll Gold Rush |last=Dean |first= Maury|authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 2003|publisher= Algora Publishing|location= |isbn= 0-87586-207-1|page= 34|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&dq=Rock-N-Roll+Gold+Rush+mariah+carey&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&q=whitney+houston#PPA34,M1}}</ref> Martin cites a variety of the Latin music genres as influences, including salsa, merengue, and bolero.<ref name=\"Martin72\">Martin, 2010. p. 72</ref> He also is inspired by artists such as the [[Fania All-Stars]], [[Celia Cruz]], [[El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico]], and [[Gilberto Santa Rosa]], some of which his mother played for him as a child.<ref name=\"Martin72\"/> Martin credits these musicians with helping him \"appreciate the richness of [his] island's culture.\"<ref name=\"Martin72\"/>\n\nSome of Martin's additional influences include [[Michael Jackson]], [[Cher]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Daniel Day-Lewis]].\n\n==Other media==\nRicky Martin's first children's book, ''Santiago the Dreamer in Land Among the Stars'', was published in November 2013 with its Spanish-language edition, ''Santiago El So\u00f1ador en Entre Las Estrellas'', released simultaneously. The book was illustrated by Patricia Castelao.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.diariodepontevedra.es/articulo/noticias/patricia-castelao-la-dibujante-pontevedresa-del-nino-de-ricky-martin/20140115170800245779.html|title=Patricia Castelao, la dibujante pontevedresa del ni\u00f1o de Ricky Martin|last=Alvarez|first=Miguel|date=January 15, 2014|website=Diario de Pontevedra |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMartin was raised Catholic but says he is open to all sorts of religious beliefs, especially the [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] philosophy.<ref name=\"buddhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=9,3467,0,0,1,0|title=Ricky Martin admires Buddhist philosophy|work=The Buddhist Channel|publisher=Asian News International|date=November 28, 2006}}</ref> He feels that subscribing to a specific religion can \"limit\" an individual in certain aspects, and noted in 2006, \"I really like the Buddhist philosophy but that doesn't mean that I am of the religion. If I subscribe to Buddhism, I can't be of anything else...I am not going to follow those rules.\"<ref name=\"buddhist\"/> Martin began practicing [[yoga]] after a trip to Thailand in 1997.<ref name=\"zen\"/>\n\nIn November 2011, he acquired [[Spanish nationality law|Spanish nationality]] in recognition of his artistic talents and for having roots in the country \u2013 Martin's grandmother is Spanish, and he owns a residence in [[Madrid]]. In September 2011, he sold his home in Miami.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.miamism.com/ricky-martins-golden-beach-home-for-sale/|title =Ricky Martin's Golden Beach Home For Sale|author =Ines Hegedus-Garcia|date =September 21, 2011|accessdate =January 22, 2012|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20111227081420/http://www.miamism.com/ricky-martins-golden-beach-home-for-sale/|archive-date =December 27, 2011|url-status =dead}}</ref> In a public statement, written in Spanish, Martin explicitly stated that he has not abandoned his Puerto Rican identity: \"I was born in Puerto Rico, I am a Puerto Rican, and Puerto Rico is my homeland. I made the request for Spanish citizenship some time ago, I was just waiting for a response. This step is part of planning for the future within a global community of whom I am part. Spain is a country with which I share many memories and strong ties born of my roots and the love they have given me since I first visited.\"<ref name=galaz/> In January 2013, he relocated to [[Sydney, Australia]] to accommodate his position on [[The Voice Australia|''The Voice'' Australia]]. In 2018, he relocated permanently to [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{Cite av media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2dkl0fUKHAM|title= Inside Ricky Martin's Serene Los Angeles Home}}</ref>\n\n===Coming out===\nMartin was in an on-off platonic relationship with Mexican TV host [[Rebecca de Alba]] for more than 14&nbsp;years. The pair had spoken of starting a family together,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.ca/profiles/rickymartin/|title=Ricky Martin |publisher=Hellomagazine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.ca/music/2003/06/20/rickymartin/|title=Ricky Martin |publisher=Hellomagazine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telemundo52.com/cotorreando/4537195/detail.html |title=Rebeca de Alba saw Ricky Martin as the father of their children (translated) |publisher=TelemundoLA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006021124/http://www.telemundo52.com/cotorreando/4537195/detail.html |archivedate=October 6, 2011 }}</ref> and Martin had at one point considered proposing to her.<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?in_article_id=59812&in_page_id=7&in_a_source=&expand=true Ricky likes being alone]. Metro.co.uk (August 2, 2007). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> In August 2008, Martin became the father of twin boys, Matteo and Valentino, born by a [[Surrogacy|gestational surrogate]] mother.<ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2008/12/59800522/1 Ricky Martin has twins babies and 'no nanny' \u2013 USATODAY.com]. Content.usatoday.com (December 10, 2008). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter the success of \"Livin' la Vida Loca\", Martin's personal life became a subject of interest due to his large gay following, and he was questioned about his sexual orientation. In a December 2000 interview with ''[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]]'', he was asked to comment on the rumors surrounding his sexuality. He replied: \"I don't think I should have to tell anyone if I am gay or not, or who I've slept with or not.\"<ref>Sally Morgan [https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-67755270 \"Ricky Martin \u2013 It's no one's business whether I've been to bed with a cow, a broom or a woman...\",] ''The Mirror'', December 9, 2000</ref><ref>Sally Morgan [http://www.rmtee.com/rmtee/html/press70.shtml \"Ricky Martin \u2013 It's no one's business whether I've been to bed with a cow, a broom or a woman...\",] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043719/http://www.rmtee.com/rmtee/html/press70.shtml |date=March 4, 2016 }} ''The Mirror'', December 9, 2000, as reproduced on rmtee.com</ref> In 2010, [[Barbara Walters]] expressed some regret for pushing Martin in a 2000 interview to admit if he was gay. The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' quoted her as saying, \"When I think back on it now, I feel it was an inappropriate question.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/2010/03/09/barbara-walters-ricky-martin-interview/ |title=Barbara Walters Regrets Ricky Martin Interview |publisher=PopEater.com |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ouzounian |first=Richard |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/article/775131--barbara-walters-what-kind-of-tree-is-she |title=Barbara Walters: What kind of tree is she? |work=Toronto Star |date=March 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 |location=Toronto}}</ref> On March 29, 2010, Martin publicly [[coming out|came out as gay]] in a post on his official website, stating: \"I am proud to say that I am a fortunate homosexual man. I am very blessed to be who I am.\"<ref>[http://www.popeater.com/2010/03/29/ricky-martin-gay/ \"Ricky Martin Gay Bombshell: 'I am a Fortunate Homosexual Man'\"], PopEater.com Staff, March 29, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/29/ricky-martin-comes-out-im_n_517625.html |title=Ricky Martin Comes Out: \"I'm A Fortunate Homosexual Man\" |work=Huffington Post |date= March 29, 2010|accessdate=August 2, 2010 |first=Katherine |last=Thomson}}</ref> Martin said that \"these years in silence and reflection made me stronger and reminded me that acceptance has to come from within, and that this kind of truth gives me the power to conquer emotions I didn't even know existed.\"<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14639/81249 Yep, He's Gay: Ricky Martin Comes Out of the Closet | Rolling Stone Music] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208161915/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14639/81249 |date=December 8, 2010 }}. Rollingstone.com (March 29, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nAlso in 2010, Martin said that for many years he thought he was [[bisexual]], telling [[Oprah Winfrey]] that \"I felt it with a woman, I felt passion and it felt good. And I'm sure I'm not the only gay man that felt attraction towards women...Sometimes I really did fall in love with women, for many years I did.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/commentary/2016/1/25/ricky-martin-bi-closet |title=Is Ricky Martin in the Bi Closet? |publisher=The Advocate |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/ricky-martin-loved-his-affairs-with-women-but-hes-definitely-not-bisexual-20101102 |title=Ricky Martin Loved His Affairs With Women, But He's Definitely Not Bisexual |publisher=Queerty |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref> He announced on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' that he was in a relationship.<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/Ricky-Martin-on-Coming-Out/10 Ricky Martin on Love]. Oprah.com (November 2, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> In 2011, during his acceptance speech of the Vito Russo Award at the [[22nd GLAAD Media Awards]], Martin publicly thanked his boyfriend, Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez Abella, an economist.<ref>[http://www.elnuevodia.com/secasarickymartin-1156746.html Se casa Ricky Martin] on ''[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]'' (January 1, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.popeater.com/2011/03/21/ricky-martin-partner-glaad-media-awards/ Ricky Martin thanks partner at GLAAD Awards] on PopEater; Mitchell, John (March 21, 2011)</ref> His relationship with Gonz\u00e1lez Abella ended in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ricky-martin-splits-from-boyfriend-carlos-gonzalez-abella/|title=Ricky Martin splits from boyfriend Carlos Gonzalez Abella|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, during an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Spanish Vanity Fair]]'', Martin stated, \"I don't regret anything, any of the relationships I've lived. They taught me a lot, both men and women equally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pagesix.com/2012/03/22/ricky-martin-ive-slept-with-women-and-felt-wonderful-things/ |title=Ricky Martin: 'I've slept with women and felt wonderful things' |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/exclusiva-ricky-martin-su-novio-y-sus-hijos-en-una-sesio-n-de-fotos-u-nica/16297 |title=LA NUEVA VIDA DE RICKY |publisher=Spanish Vanity Fair |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref> In 2016, he stated that he is attracted to both men and women, but, because he is only interested in romantic relationships with men, he does not identify as bisexual. \"I know that I like both men and women, I'm against sexual labels, we are simply human beings with emotional and sexual needs,\" he stated in an interview with the Mexican magazine ''Fama!'' He added that \"I am gay, men fascinate me, but I like to enjoy sex in total freedom, so I'm open to having sex with a woman if I feel desire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/people/2016/1/19/ricky-martin-open-sex-women-doesnt-call-himself-bi |title=Ricky Martin 'Open' to Sex With Women, But Doesn't Call Himself Bi |publisher=The Advocate |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref>\n\nMartin has also expressed support for [[same-sex marriage]] in an interview on ''[[Larry King Live]]''.<ref name=\"LK_Live\">{{cite web|url = http://www.samesame.com.au/news/international/6110/Let_Ricky_Martin_get_married|title = Let Ricky Martin Get Married!|publisher = samesame.com.au|author = Akersten, M.|date = November 11, 2010|accessdate = November 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101113135622/http://www.samesame.com.au/news/international/6110/Let_Ricky_Martin_get_married|archivedate = November 13, 2010|df = mdy-all}}</ref> Martin delivered a speech at the United Nations Homophobia Conference on November 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/12/ricky-martin-united-nations-i-lived-in-fear_n_2284350.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Ricky Martin to United Nations: 'I Lived In Fear' | date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Beginning April 2016, he started dating [[Jwan Yosef]], a Syrian-Swedish painter of Kurdish and Armenian descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902041630/http://www.umagmag.com/2015/08/a-conversation-with-artist-jwan-yosef/|title=U+MAG {{!}} A conversation with artist Jwan Yosef|date=2015-09-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ricky-martin-confirms-dating-handsome-7793026|title=Ricky Martin confirms he is dating handsome artist Jwan Yosef|first=Simon|last=Keegan|date=April 20, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The two announced their engagement on November 16, 2016, while on the ''[[Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/809694/ricky-martin-engaged-to-jwan-yosef|title=Ricky Martin Engaged to Jwan Yosef|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2018, Martin announced that he and Yosef are married.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ricky Martin & Jwan Yosef Are Married|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8093813/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-are-married|work=Billboard|accessdate=2018-01-11}}</ref> On December 31, 2018, Martin and Yosef announced, via [[Instagram]], the birth of their daughter Luc\u00eda Martin-Yosef.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Instagram|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BsEY2hjnRtW|work=Instagram}}</ref>\nOn February 2018, in an interview with E. Alex Jung of Vulture, Martin discussed working on ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' as [[Antonio D'Amico]] and how he wanted his portrayal to help normalize open relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/02/ricky-martin-on-american-crime-story-versace-and-coming-out.html|title=Ricky Martin on ACS: Versace, Coming Out, and 'Normalizing' Open Relationships|publisher=Vulture|date=Feb 14, 2018|access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\nIn 2019, while accepting an award during a human rights dinner in Washington DC, Martin announced he and his husband are expecting their fourth child together and on October 29, 2019, Martin and Yosef announced, via [[Instagram]], the birth of their son Renn Martin-Yosef.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://people.com/parents/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-welcome-baby-son-renn| title=Ricky Martin and Husband Jwan Yosef Announce the Birth of Their Fourth Child, Son Renn| accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===Humanitarian work and impact===\n[[File:Ricky Martin at the National Puerto Rican Day Parade.jpg|thumb|left|Ricky Martin at a [[Puerto Rican Day Parade|Puerto Rican Day annual parade]] in New York City]]\nMartin is the founder of ''Fundaci\u00f3n Ricky Martin'' (''Ricky Martin Foundation''), a non-profit organization. Among the events promoted by the foundation was a summer camp, which included Martin's personal participation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.primerahora.com/noticia/farandula/espectaculosasi/ricky_martin_sorprende_a_sus_ahijados/208318 |title=Ricky Martin sorprende a sus \"ahijados\" |newspaper=Primera Hora |language=Spanish |date=July 9, 2008 |accessdate=July 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719114639/http://www.primerahora.com/noticia/farandula/espectaculosasi/ricky_martin_sorprende_a_sus_ahijados/208318 |archivedate=July 19, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nMartin has been honored with accolades including: Leadership in the Arts Award, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s Spirit of Hope Award, [[ALMA Award]], [[GLAAD Media Award|Vanguard Award]], International Humanitarian Award by the [[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]], Hispanic Heritage Award for his humanitarian work through the Sabera Foundation in rescuing three orphan girls from the streets of [[Kolkata]] (September 2002).{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn December 2003, Martin was appointed a UNICEF [[Goodwill Ambassador]]. In his role as UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador, Ricky Martin has supported [[UNICEF]]'s efforts in fighting for children's rights, especially in the area of child trafficking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ricky Martin Goodwill Ambassador |url=https://www.unicef.org/people/people_51425.html |website=UNICEF |accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMartin has also collaborated with the [[International Organization for Migration]] on the ''Llama y Vive'' (''Call and Live''), a campaign which is aimed to facilitate prevention of human trafficking, protection of the youngest victims of child trafficking, and prosecution of the traffickers. For his work against [[human trafficking]], the [[United States Department of State]] named Martin one of its Heroes in Ending Modern-Day Slavery in 2005.\n\n[[File:Ricky Martin Foundation.jpg|180px|Foundation logo|thumb]]\nThe Ricky Martin Foundation was founded by Ricky Martin, with the mission to advocate for the well-being of children around the world.\n\n===Politics===\n[[File:Ricky Martin in Congress.jpg|thumb|right|Ricky Martin (''mid-right'') in Congress, with [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]] (''far left''), [[Tom Lantos]] (''mid-left'') and [[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Chris Smith]] (''far right'').]]\nMartin was a headliner in the 2001 inauguration celebration for President [[George W. Bush]]; he even invited the newly elected president to join him on stage to dance. Photographs of this moment were broadcast throughout the world, and Martin wrote about it in his song \"[[Asignatura Pendiente]]\". Martin's view of President Bush changed over the [[Iraq War]], as expressed in his declaration to the [[Associated Press]] that he will \"always condemn war and those who promulgate it.\"<ref name=\"NewsMax\">{{cite news|url = http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2007/2/16/85325.shtml|title = Singer Ricky Martin 'Fingers' Bush for Iraq Criticism|newspaper = [[NewsMax]], [[Associated Press]]|date = February 16, 2007|url-status=dead|archivedate = February 18, 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070218092851/http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2007/2/16/85325.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work = [[BBC News]]|date = February 16, 2007|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6369705.stm|accessdate = August 9, 2017|title = Ricky Martin defends Bush gesture}}</ref>\n\nDuring his appearance at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] on April 29, 2010, Martin expressed his disagreement with the [[Arizona SB 1070]] bill, a proposed law that would have required police officers to request documents from individuals whom they suspected to be illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"speaksout\">{{cite news|title=Ricky Martin Criticizes Arizona's Immigration Law|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/958416/ricky-martin-criticizes-arizonas-immigration-law|newspaper = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher = [[Prometheus Global Media]]|date = April 30, 2010|accessdate = August 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Ricky Martin albums discography|Ricky Martin singles discography|Ricky Martin videography}}\n{{see also|Menudo (band)#Discography}}\n* ''[[Ricky Martin (1991 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Sound Loaded]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Movimiento]]'' (2020)\n\n==Filmography==\n*1985: ''[[The Love Boat]]'' (TV series) as Ricky\n*1987: ''Por siempre amigos'' (Argentinian TV series) as Ricky\n*1991: ''[[Alcanzar una estrella II]]'' (TV series) as Pablo Loredo\n*1992: ''M\u00e1s que alcanzar una estrella'' as Enrique\n*1993: ''[[Getting By]]'' (TV series) as Martin\n*1994: ''[[General Hospital]]'' (TV series) as Miguel Morez (1994\u201395)\n*1996: ''Barefoot in Paradise'' (TV series) as Sandoval\n*1997: ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]'' (Latin American dub, voice role) as Hercules\n*1999: ''[[Idle Hands]]'' as Man in Car Park\n*2006: ''[[Sos mi vida]]'' (Argentinian TV series) as himself\n*2011: ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'': guest\n*2011: ''[[Susana Gim\u00e9nez]]'': guest\n*2011: ''[[American Dad!]]'' as himself (uncredited)\n*2012: ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' (TV series) as David Mart\u00ednez\n*2013: ''[[The Voice (Australia series 2)|The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' (TV series) as Himself (Judge)\n*2014: ''[[The Voice (Australia series 3)|The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[The Voice Ahla Sawt|The Voice Arabia]]'' as Himself (guest judge) \n*2015: ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' (Latin American dub, voice role) as Herb Overkill\n*2015: ''[[The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2015: ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]]'' as himself (judge and executive producer)\n*2015: ''[[Nuestra Belleza Latina 2015]]'' as himself (Celebrity guest)\n*2017: ''[[Lip Sync Battle]]'' as himself (winner vs. [[Kate Upton]])\n*2018: ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' as [[Antonio D'Amico]]\n*2019: ''[[Amici di Maria De Filippi]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n\n==Theatre==\n*''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'' (1996), Broadway&nbsp;\u2013 [[Marius Pontmercy]]\n*''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'', (2012), Broadway&nbsp;\u2013 Ch\u00e9\n\n==Tours==\n* Ricky Martin Tour (1992)\n* Me Amaras Tour (1993\u20131994)\n* A Medio Vivir Tour (1995\u20131997)\n* [[Vuelve World Tour]] (1998)\n* [[Livin' la Vida Loca Tour]] (1999\u20132000)\n* [[One Night Only with Ricky Martin]] (2005\u20132006)\n* [[Black and White Tour]] (2007)\n* [[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo World Tour]]<ref>[https://twitter.com/ricky_martin/status/13011345884581888 Twitter / Ricky Martin: First stop on my \"Music+So]. Twitter.com (December 9, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> (2011)\n* [[Ricky Martin Live]] (2013\u20132014)\n* Live in Mexico (2014)\n* [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|One World Tour]] (2015\u20132017)\n* Ricky Martin en Concierto (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/events/|title=Events {{!}} Ricky Martin|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/hashtag/RickyMartinEnConcierto?src=hash&lang=en|title=#RickyMartinEnConcierto hashtag on Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n* [[Movimiento Tour]] (2020)\n* [[Enrique Iglesias and Ricky Martin Live in Concert]] {{small|(with [[Enrique Iglesias]])}} (2020)\n\n==Honors and awards==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Ricky Martin}}\nRicky Martin has received numerous awards, including 2 [[Grammy Award]]s, 4 [[Latin Grammy Awards]], 5 [[MTV Video Music Awards]], 3 [[Billboard Music Awards]], 9 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], 2 [[American Music Awards]], 2 [[Latin American Music Awards]], 8 [[World Music Awards]] and has been [[Emmy]]-nominated.\n*Martin was chosen along with [[F\u00e9lix Trinidad]] in 1999, to lead Puerto Rico's worldwide tourism campaign, both exemplifying Puerto Rico's youthfulness, enthusiasm and indefatigable character.\n*In February 2004, Martin received the [[Lo Nuestro Excellence Award|Excellence Award]] at the [[Lo Nuestro Awards]] in Miami.\n*Martin was honored as the 2006 [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences|Latin Recording Academy]] on November 1, 2006. He was chosen for his accomplishments as a world-renowned entertainer, consummate performer and passionate humanitarian. A portion of the proceeds from the evening's tribute dinner was used for benefitting Ricky Martin's charitable efforts.\n*On October 16, 2007, Martin received the 2351st [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] star,<ref>[http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2007/10/16/ricky_martin_gets_walk_of_fame_star/ Ricky Martin gets Walk of Fame star \u2013 Boston.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=February 2010}}</ref> shortly after receiving the [[Freedom of the City|key to the city]] of [[Miami Beach, Florida]] on October 11. The star is located beside the Hollywood and Highland complex. Los Angeles mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] and [[Rita Moreno]] were invited to the unveiling ceremony.<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite book| title=Ricky Martin: Bien ubicada su estrella| publisher=El Nuevo D\u00eda| location=Puerto Rico| chapter=Flash!/Cine| language=Spanish| date=October 14, 2007| page=94}}</ref>\n*In 2011, Martin was awarded Spanish citizenship by the Council of Ministers, to honor his contributions to the arts.<ref name=\"NE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lne.es/sociedad-cultura/2011/11/04/ricky-martin-benicio-toro-nacionalidad-espanola/1152213.html |title=Ricky Martin y Benicio del Toro ya tienen la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola|publisher=lne.es |date=November 4, 2011|accessdate=November 4, 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Latin music|LGBT}}\n*[[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n*[[White Latin American]]\n*[[Corsican immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n*[[Cultural diversity in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book\n| last       = De La Torre\n| first       = David\n| authorlink       = \n| coauthors       = \n| title       = Ricky Martin: la historia verdadera\n| year       = 1997\n| publisher       = Edamex\n| isbn       = 9684099835\n| url       = https://archive.org/details/rickymartinlahis00orta\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last       = Holt\n| first      = Fabian\n| authorlink = \n| coauthors  = \n| title      = Genre in Popular Music\n| year       = 2007\n| publisher  = University of Chicago Press\n| isbn       = 978-0226350394\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last       = Martin\n| first       = Ricky\n| authorlink       = \n| coauthors       = \n| title       = Me\n| year       = 2010\n| publisher       = Celebra Hardcover\n| isbn       = 978-0451234155\n| url       = https://archive.org/details/me00mart\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last       = Otfinoski\n| first       = Steven\n| authorlink       = \n| coauthors       = \n| title       = Latinos in the Arts (A to Z of Latino Americans)\n| year       = 2007\n| publisher       = Facts on File\n| isbn       = 978-0816063949\n| url-access       = registration\n| url       = https://archive.org/details/latinosinarts0000otfi\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n* {{Official website|http://rickymartinmusic.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0005193|name=Ricky Martin}}\n* {{IBDB name|79483}}\n\n{{S-start}} \n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Luis Miguel]]<br />for ''[[Romances (Luis Miguel album)|Romances]]''}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album]]|years = 1999<br />for ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]''}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Rub\u00e9n Blades]]<br />for Tiempo}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Gloria Estefan]]<br />for \"[[No Me Dejes de Querer]]\"}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video]]|years = 2001<br />for \"[[She Bangs]]\"}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Shakira]]<br />for \"[[Whenever, Wherever|Suerte]]\"}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Ricardo Arjona]]<br />for [[Adentro]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Album]]|years = 2007<br />for ''[[MTV Unplugged (Ricky Martin album)|MTV Unplugged]]''}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Juanes]]<br />for [[La Vida... Es Un Ratico]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Diego El Cigala]]<br />for Blanco Y Negro En Vivo}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video]]|years = 2007<br />'''for ''[[MTV Unplugged (Ricky Martin album)|MTV Unplugged]]'' '''}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Julieta Venegas]]<br />for ''[[MTV Unplugged (Julieta Venegas album)|MTV Unplugged]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ricky Martin}}\n{{Ricky Martin singles}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Ricky Martin|Awards for Ricky Martin]]\n|list  = \n{{Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year}}\n{{Premios Juventud for What a Hottie}}\n}}\n{{Menudo|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Ricky}}\n[[Category:Ricky Martin| ]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Australia]]\n[[Category:American humanitarians]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American tenors]]\n[[Category:Child singers]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:Echo (music award) winners]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American male actors]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year honorees]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT Hispanic and Latino American people]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Menudo (band) members]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Spain]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican pop singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican people of Corsican descent]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Singers from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Sony Music Spain artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers of the United States]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the singer|other uses|Ricky Martin (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Puerto Rican singer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Mart\u00edn|Morales}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ricky Martin\n| image              = File:Ricky Martin in store appearance, Sydney Australia (1).jpg\n| caption            = Martin in 2014\n| birth_name         = Enrique Mart\u00edn Morales\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|12|24}}<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrities/ricky-martin | title=Ricky Martin | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018 |work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref><ref name = IMDb-bio>{{cite web| url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0005193/bio | title=Ricky Martin Biography | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018 |work=[[IMDb]]}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], [[Puerto Rico]]<ref name = IMDb-bio />\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| citizenship        = {{flatlist|\n* United States\n* Spain\n}}\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* actor\n* author\n* humanitarian.\n}}\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Jwan Yosef]]|2017}}<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2018/01/11/ricky-martin-reveals-he-and-jwan-yosef-married/1023547001 | title=Ricky Martin reveals he and Jwan Yosef are married: 'I'm a husband' | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=January 11, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n| children           = 4\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer <!-- mandatory field -->\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Latin music|Latin]]\n* [[urban pop]]\n}}\n| instrument         = Vocals\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Latin]]\n* [[Sony Music|Sony Mexico]]\n* [[Sony Classical]]\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|rickymartinmusic.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Enrique Mart\u00edn Morales''' ({{IPA-es|en\u02c8\u027eike ma\u027e\u02c8tin mo\u02c8\u027eales}}; born December 24, 1971), better known as '''Ricky Martin''', is a [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] singer, actor, and author who is known as the \"[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|King of Latin Pop]]\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/ricky-martin-host-biggest-night-latin-music-19-years-after-performing-inaugural-show| title=Ricky Martin To Host The Biggest Night In Latin Music 19 Years After Performing At Inaugural Show| accessdate=October 26, 2019 |date=October 25, 2019 | work=[[Grammy]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://time.com/5526369/grammys-2019-camila-cabello-border-wall | title=Camila Cabello's Grammy Performance Had a Hidden Anti-Wall Message | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=February 11, 2019|work=[[Time (Magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.rollingstone.it/tv/news-tv/amici-2019-ricky-martin-sara-coach-al-serale/450243/ | title='Amici 2019', Ricky Martin sar\u00e0 coach al serale | accessdate=March 17, 2019 |date=March 16, 2019|work=[[Roling Stone]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://qnews.com.au/king-of-latin-pop-vetos-religious-freedoms-bill-ricky-martin-qn-magazine | title=King of Latin Pop vetoes 'religious freedoms' bill | accessdate=July 8, 2019 |date=June 14, 2019 | work=[[QNews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/national-puerto-rico-day-parade-brings-generations-boricuas-together-n1015521 | title=National Puerto Rico Day Parade brings generations of boricuas together | accessdate=July 8, 2019 |date=June 9, 2019 | work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ricky-martin-announces-hes-expecting-20332022 | title=Ricky Martin announces he's expecting fourth child with husband Jwan Yosef | accessdate=October 1, 2019 |date=September 29, 2019 | work=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> He holds dual American and Spanish citizenship,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2011/11/04/ricky-martin-granted-spanish-citizenship/ | title=Ricky Martin granted Spanish citizenship | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=November 4, 2011}}</ref> and began his career at age 12 with the all-boy pop group [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8465853/ricky-martin-watch-scenes-from-emmy-nominee-acting-career | title=Watch Scenes From 'The Assassination of Gianni Versace' Emmy Nominee Ricky Martin's Acting Career | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=July 17, 2018}}</ref> After five years with the group, he released several Spanish-language solo albums throughout the 1990s. Since the beginning of his solo career in 1991, Ricky Martin has became one of the [[List of best-selling Latin music artists|the\u00a0best-selling Latin music artists\u00a0of all time]] with sales estimates ranging from 70 million records <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/entretenimiento/2019/07/25/nota/7442625/ricky-martin-no-dejes-caer-puerto-rico-ahora-es-cuando-mas|title=Ricky Martin: No lo dejes caer, Puerto Rico, ahora es cuando m\u00e1s tenemos que trabajar |work=[[El Universo]]|accessdate=February 16, 2020|language=Spanish}}</ref> to 85 million albums.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/02/10/ricky-martin-world-tour-concert-phoenix/23177461/|title=Ricky Martin bringing One World Tour to Phoenix|work=USA Today|accessdate=February 16, 2020}}</ref> He also acted on stage and on TV in [[Mexico]], where he achieved modest stardom. In 1994, he appeared on the US TV soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]'', playing a Puerto Rican singer.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emmys-flashback-ricky-martin-steamed-up-general-hospital-1994-1130669 | title=Emmys Flashback: Ricky Martin Steamed Up 'General Hospital' in 1994 | accessdate=February 15, 2019 |date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> He also ranks among the most influential Latin artists of all time.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6546212/most-influential-latin-artists | title=The 30 Most Influential Latin Artists of All Time | accessdate=April 25, 2019 |date=April 28, 2015 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1999, after releasing several albums in Spanish, Martin performed \"[[The Cup of Life]]\" at the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]] show, which became a catalyst in bringing Latin pop to the forefront of the U.S. music scene.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9905/17/latin.music/|work=CNN |title=Ricky Martin leading the Latin (music) revolution - May 17, 1999|publisher=}}</ref> Following its success, Martin released \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\", which helped him attain success worldwide. It is generally seen as the song that began the [[Latin pop]] explosion of 1999 and made the transition easier for other Spanish-speaking artists to move into the English-speaking market. His first English-language album (also titled ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]''), sold 15 million copies and is his best selling album to date.<ref>{{cite book|last=Adams|first=Steve|title=Martin's World View|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64|date=November 4, 2006|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=64\u2013|id=00062510}}</ref> His other studio albums include: ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]'' (1993), ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]'' (1995), ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998), ''[[Sound Loaded]]'' (2000), ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003), ''[[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]'' (2005), ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' (2011), ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' (2015) and ''Movimiento'' (2020). In 2018, he portrayed [[Antonio D'Amico]] in the miniseries ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'', which earned him a nomination for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie]].\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===1971\u20131982: Early life===\nMartin was born on December 24, 1971, in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], to Nereida Morales, an accountant, and Enrique Mart\u00edn Negroni (son of Enrique Mart\u00edn and Iraida Negroni Arizmendi),<ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVJX-4LXN Enrique Martin] - Puerto Rico, (Marriage) Civil Registration</ref><ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:V683-S2T Iraida Negroni Arizmendi] - United States Census, 1930</ref> a psychologist.<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29272|pure_url=yes}}|title=Ricky Martin \u2013 Biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=April 8, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Otfinoski138\">Otfinoski, 2007. p. 138</ref><ref name=\"zen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20133136,00.html|title=Ricky Martin : Zen and Now|work=People|publisher=Time, Inc.|last=Tresniowski|first=Alex|date=December 4, 2000|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin42\">Martin, 2010. p. 42</ref> The youngest of three boys on his mother's side and oldest of four children on his father's side, he has four brothers and one sister. His parents divorced when he was two years old, and Martin spent much of his childhood shifting between his father's home in the suburbs of University Gardens, a suburban middle-class neighborhood of San Juan, and his paternal grandmother's house nearby.<ref name=\"favorite\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-my-favorite-martin-vol-51-no-24/|title=My Favorite Martin|work=People|publisher=Time, Inc.|last=Schneider|first=Karen S.|date=June 28, 1999|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin20\">Martin, 2010. p. 20</ref> Martin has two older maternal half-brothers, Fernando and \u00c1ngel Fern\u00e1ndez, two younger paternal half-brothers, Eric and Daniel Mart\u00edn, and a younger paternal half-sister, Vanessa Mart\u00edn.<ref name=\"zen\"/> Martin, in an interview with newspaper ''[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]'', described his origins as [[Spaniards|Spanish]], of [[Basques|Basque]] and [[Canary Islanders|Canarian]] descent and that the Mart\u00edns left Spain for Puerto Rico in 1779.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/cultura/musica/abci-ricky-martin-nunca-abierto-respecto-sentimientos-como-ahora-201609160149_noticia_amp.html|title=Ricky Martin: Nunca fui tan abierto con respecto a mis sentimientos como ahora|language=Spanish|website=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.revistavanityfair.es/celebrities/articulos/entrevista-ricky-martin-hijos-novio-yo-soy-papa-y-mama-a-mis-hijos-les-contare-la-verdad/20329 |title=Yo soy papa y mama a mis hijos|magazine=Vanity Fair |language=Spanish|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=galaz>{{cite news |url =http://www.elpais.com/articulo/gente/tv/gobierno/concede/Ricky/Martin/nacionalidad/espanola/poder/casarse/elpepugen/20111104elpepuage_3/Tes |title = El gobierno concede a Ricky Martin la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola para poder casarse|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|author = Galaz, Mabel|date = November 4, 2011|accessdate =November 8, 2011}}</ref> He also has some [[Corsicans|Corsican]] heritage through his paternal grandmother.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D5H6yvflq-wC&pg=PT15&lpg=PP1&focus=viewport&dq=ricky%20martin%20me&output=html_text|title=Me|first=Ricky|last=Martin|date=November 2, 2010|publisher=Penguin|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin21\">Martin, 2010. p. 21</ref>\n\nMartin grew up in a [[Roman Catholic]] home and was an [[altar server|altar boy]] throughout his childhood.<ref name=\"Martin18\">Martin, 2010. p. 18</ref> He began singing at age 6, using wooden kitchen spoons as pretended microphones; he often interpreted songs by Menudo as well as English-language rock groups such as [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Journey (band)|Journey]], and [[REO Speedwagon]].<ref name=\"Martin16\">Martin, 2010. p. 16</ref> His mother's side of the family was musically inclined, and his maternal grandfather was a poet, which inspired young Martin to write songs.<ref name=\"Martin16\"/> Martin later reflected on his time spent with his family as a child: \"Every time I find myself in front of an audience, be it twenty people or one hundred thousand, once again I feel the energy that consumed me back at the family gatherings of my youth.\"<ref name=\"Martin17\">Martin, 2010. p. 17</ref> After discovering, with his father, a newspaper advertisement about auditions for commercials, 9-year-old Martin began appearing in Puerto Rican television commercials for products such as soft drinks, toothpaste, and restaurants.<ref name=\"Martin2425\">Martin, 2010. pp. education24-25</ref> In a year and a half, he starred in 11 commercials.<ref name=\"Martin2425\"/>\n\n===1983\u20131990: Menudo===\n{{Listen\n| filename    = Menudo - Rayo de Luna.ogg\n| title       = Menudo \"Rayo de Luna\" (1984)\n| description = At age thirteen, Martin made his recording debut on the song \"Rayo de Luna\", from Menudo's 1984 album, ''[[Evoluci\u00f3n (Menudo album)|Evoluci\u00f3n]]''.<ref name=\"Delatorre34\">De La Torre, 1997. p. 34</ref>\n| format      = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nAfter achieving modest fame in Puerto Rico for his work in television commercials, Martin auditioned for membership in the [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] [[boy band]] [[Menudo (band)|Menudo]]. Although the executives enjoyed his dancing and singing at his first two auditions, Martin was rejected because he was too short.<ref name=\"Martin31\">Martin, 2010. p. 31</ref> By the third audition, his persistence impressed executives, and in 1984, 12-year-old Martin became a member.<ref name=\"Martin3132\">Martin, 2010. pp. 31\u201332</ref> A month after joining Menudo, he made his debut performance with the group at the [[Luis A. Ferr\u00e9 Performing Arts Center]] in San Juan.<ref name=\"Martin33\">Martin, 2010. p. 33</ref> During this performance, he inadvertently disobeyed the choreography by walking around the stage, when it was planned that he would stay still, and was chastised by the band manager after the show: \"The mistake was such a big deal that from that moment on, never again did I move when I wasn't supposed to move...That was the discipline of Menudo: You either did things the way you were told or you were not part of the group.\"<ref name=\"Martin3334\">Martin, 2010. pp. 33\u201334</ref> The song \"Asignatura Pendiente\" from ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003) was inspired by the first time Martin left Puerto Rico to tour with Menudo.<ref name=\"Martin47\">Martin, 2010. p. 47</ref>\n\nAlthough Martin enjoyed traveling and performing onstage with Menudo, he found the band's busy schedule and strict management exhausting, and later reflected that the experience \"cost\" him his childhood.<ref name=\"Martin28\">Martin, 2010. p. 28</ref> He considered leaving the group while on tour in Brazil, but ultimately decided to stay out of fear of media backlash and being sued for breach of contract.<ref name=\"Martin3637\">Martin, 2010. pp. 36\u201337</ref> Martin also began struggling with his sexuality, noting the stark contrast between his status as a [[sex symbol]] and his own emotions.<ref name=VH1behindthemusic>(2002) ''[[Behind the Music]]'': Ricky Martin episode. [[VH1]].</ref> Despite this, Martin acknowledged his \"opportunity to have so many amazing experiences with so many amazing people\" during his time with the group.<ref name=\"Martin37\">Martin, 2010. p. 37</ref>\n\nHe developed an interest in philanthropy when the group became [[UNICEF]] ambassadors, often working with impoverished children in third world countries.<ref name=\"Martin37\"/> His experiences as an ambassador affected him greatly and inspired him to continue working with charities later in life.<ref name=\"Martin37\"/>\n\nBy 1987, Menudo's record sales began to decline, and the group changed its image, adopting an edgier look and performing more rock-influenced songs.<ref name=\"Martin44\">Martin, 2010. p. 44</ref> The band released the album ''[[Somos Los Hijos del Rock]]'' in Spanish, and to appeal to the Menudo's Filipino fanbase, the group released ''[[In Action (Menudo album)|In Action]]'', recording songs in both English and [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]].<ref name=\"Martin44\"/>\n\nAfter recording 11 albums with the group, Martin left Menudo in July 1989, at age 17, hoping to rest and evaluate his career path.<ref name=\"Martin46\">Martin, 2010. p. 46</ref> He performed his final show with the group at the same venue where he'd performed his first performance as a member.<ref name=\"Martin46\"/> Martin returned to Puerto Rico to graduate from high school, and 13 days after turning 18, he moved to New York City to celebrate his financial independence; since he was a minor during his time as a member of Menudo, Martin was not allowed to access his own bank accounts.<ref name=\"Martin58\">Martin, 2010. p. 58</ref> He was accepted into [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], but months before classes began, Martin dropped out and moved to [[Mexico City]] to perform in the play ''Mama Ama el Rock'' (''Mom Loves Rock'').<ref name=\"Martin1819\">Martin, 2010, pp. 18\u201319</ref>\n\n===1991\u20131994: Acting and first two solo albums===\nWhile he was performing onstage in ''Mama Ama el Rock'', a producer in the audience took notice of Martin's acting and offered him a role in the Mexican [[telenovela]] ''[[Alcanzar una estrella]]'' after the show.<ref name=\"Martin66\">Martin, 2010. p. 66</ref> He also joined the cast for the second season of the show, titled ''[[Alcanzar una estrella II]]''.<ref name=\"Martin66\"/> A film based on the TV series, titled ''M\u00e1s que alcanzar una estrella'', was also produced in which Martin starred and in 1993 earned an El Heraldo Award for his role.<ref name=\"Martin67\">Martin, 2010. p. 67</ref> The show centered around a fictional musical group called [[Mu\u00f1ecos de Papel]], in which Martin played Pablo Loredo, one of the six members; the group toured several cities in Mexico and recorded two albums.<ref name=\"Martin66\"/> Although he had hoped to take a break from touring after Menudo, Martin enjoyed the experience because he got along with the other members well.<ref name=\"Martin67\"/>\n\n{{Quote box |bgcolor=#bbccff |salign=right |width=240px |align=right | quote = I was so excited about getting back into the music world that I didn't care what the conditions were...All of the hard work and passion I had exerted was finally now starting to come to fruition, and music came back to my life powerfully and definitively. | source =\u2013 Martin, on recording his debut album.<ref name=\"Martin70\">Martin, 2010. p. 70</ref>}}\n\nIn 1990, Martin was signed to [[Sony Music Latin|Sony Discos]], the [[Sony Music Entertainment]]'s Latin imprint. Eager to make his first solo album, Martin signed the contract without reading it and inadvertently signed a deal in which he would only be awarded one cent of royalties for each album sold.<ref name=\"Martin70\"/> Despite viewing the contract as unfair, Martin referred to the record as \"the start of something phenomenal\" for him.<ref name=\"Martin70\"/> After working \"around the clock\" to finish filming ''Alcanzar una estrella II'' and recording music, Martin released his debut solo album, the Spanish-language ''[[Ricky Martin (1991 album)|Ricky Martin]]'', in November 1991.<ref name=\"Martin7071\">Martin, 2010, pp. 70\u201371</ref> ''Ricky Martin'' included the singles: \"[[Fuego Contra Fuego]]\" and \"[[El Amor de Mi Vida (song)|El Amor de Mi Vida]]\". \"Fuego Contra Fuego\" was certified Gold in Mexico, Argentina, Puerto Rico, and the United States.<ref name=\"Martin71\">Martin, 2010. p. 71</ref> To promote the album, Martin toured throughout Latin America, which the singer referred to as \"an indescribable feeling, almost like coming home.\"<ref name=\"Martin71\"/>\n\nAfter the success of ''Ricky Martin'' and its subsequent tour, Martin's record company met him with acclaimed producer Juan Carlos Calder\u00f3n on his second solo album, ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]''. Although Martin felt \"very grateful\" for the opportunity to work with Calder\u00f3n, he noted, \"I always felt that that record was more his than mine.\"<ref name=\"Martin87\">Martin, 2010, p. 87</ref> Released in May 1993, ''Me Amaras'' features a Spanish-language cover of the [[Laura Branigan]] song \"[[Self Control (Raf song)|Self Control]]\", titled \"[[Self Control (Raf song)#Ricky Martin version|Que Dia Es Hoy]]\".<ref name=\"MeamarasAM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/me-amar%C3%A1s-mw0000100600|title=Review: Ricky Martin \u2013 Me Amaras|last=Henderson|first=Alex|work=AllMusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation |accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> In his review, Alex Henderson of [[AllMusic]] wrote, \"The CD isn't without its pleasures...but on the whole, ''Me Amaras'' is too glossy, too calculated, and much too contrived for its own good.\"<ref name=\"MeamarasAM\"/>\n\nIn 1994, Martin's agent encouraged him to move to Los Angeles to act in an American sitcom called ''[[Getting By]]''.<ref name=\"Martin76\">Martin, 2010. p. 76</ref> The show was canceled after two seasons, but soon afterward, Martin was given the role of singer/bartender Miguel Morez on the soap opera ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref name=\"Martin7778\">Martin, 2010, pp. 77\u201378</ref> Martin felt he lacked chemistry with the rest of the ''General Hospital'' cast and observed that people treated him differently because of his Puerto Rican accent.<ref name=\"Martin7879\">Martin, 2010, pp. 78\u201379</ref> At the time, it was relatively uncommon for Hispanic people to appear on American television, and people suggested that he take accent reduction classes, which he refused.<ref name=\"Martin7778\"/> It was during this time, however, that Martin began his first committed relationship with a man.<ref name=\"Martin81\">Martin, 2010. p. 81</ref> He \"stopped fearing his sexuality\", and soon [[Coming out|came out]] to his mother, who was supportive of him.<ref name=\"Martin81\"/> However, after the relationship ended, Martin \"locked [his] feelings even deeper inside\", and began dating women again.<ref name=\"Martin82\">Martin, 2010. p. 82</ref> He recalled, \"I already felt it was hard to be a Latino in Hollywood; what could have been more difficult than being Latino and gay?\"<ref name=\"Martin84\">Martin, 2010. p. 84</ref>\n\n===1995\u20131998: ''A Medio Vivir'', ''Vuelve'', and breakthrough===\nIn 1995, Martin refocused on his music career, and began work on his third album, ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]''. The first single, the ballad \"[[Te Extra\u00f1o, Te Olvido, Te Amo]]\", written by the producer of [[Lynda Thomas]], Carlos Lara, was reminiscent of his earlier work.<ref name=\"Martin102\">Martin, 2010. p. 102</ref> With the song, Martin furthered his expansion from Latin American and Spanish-speaking audiences to the European and Asian markets.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r224606|pure_url=yes}} AllMusic]</ref> However, the record also made a shift from his traditional ballad-style compositions to a more risky fusion of music centered around traditional Latin sounds, epitomized by the song \"[[Mar\u00eda (Ricky Martin song)|Maria]]\". Taken aback by the starkly different musical style, record label executives felt that the song would ruin Martin's career.<ref name=\"Martin103\">Martin, 2010. p. 103</ref> Despite this, \"Maria\" was chosen as the album's second single, and became a breakthrough hit, reaching number one in France, Spain, Germany, Belgium, Holland, Switzerland, Finland, Italy, Turkey, and the entire continent of South America.<ref name=\"Martin103\"/> With ''A Medio Vivir'', Martin was credited, along with singers [[Chayanne]] and [[Marc Anthony]], for popularizing the music of Puerto Rico in Spain.<ref name=\"spanishmarket\">{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA61-IA2&lpg=RA1-PA61-IA2&dq=ricky+martin+a+medio+vivir&source=bl&ots=bqqrnCl1FZ&sig=fBmYD5iWZNkusJcpy1xthEWLRMI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xa0LUL7rCIfMqAHrtK28Cg&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=ricky%20martin%20a%20medio%20vivir&f=false|title=Breaking Into the Spanish Market|last=Llewellyn|first=Howell|work=Billboard |date=October 7, 2000|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> The album has sold over 3 million copies worldwide.\n\nIn a 1996 interview with ''[[The Miami Herald]]'', Martin expressed an interest in performing on Broadway. Days after the interview was released Martin received a phone call from producer [[Richard Jay-Alexander]], offering him the role of [[Marius Pontmercy]] in the play ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''.<ref name=\"Martin89\">Martin, 2010. p. 89</ref> After the conclusion of a worldwide tour in support of ''A Medio Vivir'', Martin returned to New York to appear in the play in an eleven-week run.<ref name=\"Martin90\">Martin, 2010. p. 90</ref> He greatly enjoyed the experience, calling his time in the play an \"honor\" and \"the role of [his] life\".<ref name=\"Martin90\"/> Martin continued to tour after the conclusion of the show's run, and noted that his audiences were growing in both size and enthusiasm.<ref name=\"Martin104\">Martin, 2010. p. 104</ref> In 1997, Martin was invited to the prestigious [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in [[Sanremo]], Italy. After landing in Milan, Martin's scheduled helicopter trip to Sanremo had to be postponed due to poor weather conditions.<ref name=\"Martin106\">Martin, 2010. p. 106</ref> Hoping to arrive at the festival on time, Martin and his crew drove through the mountainous terrain at over 120 miles per hour. The car then turned too quickly and flipped over.<ref name=\"Martin106\"/> However, \"none of us had more than a couple of scratches and bruises\" and he arrived at the festival on time by taxi later that day.<ref name=\"Martin106\"/> In the summer of 1997, Martin embarked on a tour of Spain, performing 45 shows in 36 cities.<ref name=\"Martin107\">Martin, 2010. p. 107</ref>\n\nWhile on tour, Martin returned to the studio to record his fourth album, ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998). He called the experience of touring and recording at the same time \"brutal and incredibly intense\".<ref name=\"Martin108\">Martin, 2010. p. 108</ref> As he was finishing the record, the singer was contacted by [[FIFA]] to write a song for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]]; Martin subsequently wrote \"[[The Cup of Life|La copa de la vida]]\" with [[K. C. Porter]] and [[Draco Rosa]].<ref name=\"Martin108109\">Martin, 2010. pp. 108\u2013109</ref> He performed the song at the World Cup final in the [[Stade de France]] on July 12, 1998.<ref name=\"Martin109\">Martin, 2010. p. 109</ref> The performance, which was broadcast to over a billion viewers in 187 countries, was described as a \"global moment for Latin pop\".<ref name=\"Holt165\">Holt, 2007. p. 165</ref> \"La copa de la vida\" reached No. 1 on the charts around the world and went gold and platinum in various countries. It was awarded Pop Song of the Year at the 1999 [[Lo Nuestro Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=490994 |title=Lo Nuestro 1999 \u2013 Historia de Premio lo Nuestro |publisher=Univision |accessdate=August 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403132343/http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=490994 |archivedate=April 3, 2010 }}</ref> The [[Vuelve (Ricky Martin song)|title track]] and the ballad \"[[Perdido Sin T\u00ed]]\" both hit number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. Further singles included: \"[[La Bomba (Ricky Martin song)|La Bomba]]\", \"[[Por Arriba, Por Abajo]]\" and \"[[Corazonado]]\". ''Vuelve'' spent twenty-six weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]]. It became Martin's first top forty album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the United States, where it was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. The album also went to number one in Spain and Norway, and sold over eight million copies worldwide.<ref>[http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Ricky+Martin&titel=Vuelve&cat=a/ Ricky Martin \u2013 Vuelve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102155613/http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Ricky+Martin&titel=Vuelve&cat=a%2F |date=January 2, 2016 }}. norwegiancharts.com. Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nMartin was nominated for his first Grammy Award for ''Vuelve'' in the category of [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Pop Album|Best Latin Pop Album]], and was booked to sing on the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards]] live TV broadcast. His acclaimed performance of \"La copa de la vida\" earned Martin an unexpected standing ovation and introduced him to the mainstream American audience. Being aware of performing on the Grammy, he said that:\"The excitement is more than being nominated for the award. The audience in front of me are people who are hard to please. [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]! [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]! [[Luciano Pavarotti]]! To get the acceptance of your peers really means a lot.\"<ref name=\"smashing\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/01/entertainment/ca-34681|title=A Smashing Start for Ricky Martin|work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 1, 1999|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Martin115\">Martin, 2010. p. 115</ref> Martin won the Grammy Award later that evening, and even superstars [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] went backstage to congratulate him.<ref name=\"Martin116\">Martin, 2010. p. 116</ref> His appearance sparked nationwide interest in Latin music. Writing for ''Billboard'' on April 24, 1999, Michael Paoletta noted, \"In the weeks since [the performance], it seems like every record label exec has been in a heated search for the next Latin hottie.\"<ref name=\"paoletta\">{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eigEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=ricky+martin+sensation&source=bl&ots=-XoJZ-_KcN&sig=YqsasIUw3LbdUP1fhkzilnoqdAM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZPkbUJjdB4GciQLV9YDoCg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=ricky%20martin%20sensation&f=false|title=Can New Jersey's Spicy Sin Match Martin's Latin Sizzle?|work=Billboard |last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=April 24, 1999|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1999\u20132002: Crossover to English===\n{{Listen\n| filename    = Ricky Martin Livin La Vida Loca.ogg\n| title       = Ricky Martin \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" (1999)\n| description = \n| format      = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nAfter receiving commercial success throughout [[Asia]], [[Europe]], and [[Latin America]], Martin prepared his first English album in 1999 in an attempt to cross over to the United States market.<ref name=\"Martin112\">Martin, 2010. p. 112</ref> The [[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|self-titled]] album, which debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and sold 661,000 copies in its first week of release, became the most successful album debut on the ''Billboard'' charts by a Hispanic artist.<ref name=\"debuts\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1999-05-21/news/9905210215_1_ricky-martin-pop-music-charts-divorce|title=Ricky Martin Debuts As No. 1|work=Orlando Sentinel |publisher=Tribune Company|date=May 21, 1999|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> It contained material by writers and producers such as [[Desmond Child]], [[Diane Warren]], [[William Orbit]], [[George Noriega]] and his longtime childhood friend [[Draco Rosa]]. The album also featured special guests: [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] on the Spanish-English duet \"Be Careful (Cuidado con mi Coraz\u00f3n)\" and [[Sertab Erener]] on \"[[Private Emotion]]\".<ref name=\"rickymartinrev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ricky-martin-1999-mw0000238986|title=Ricky Martin \u2013 Album Review|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|work=AllMusic |publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> Two weeks after the album's release, Martin was featured on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' with the title \"Latin Music Goes Pop!\".<ref name=\"timecover\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/covers/0,16641,19990524,00.html|title=Time Magazine Cover: Ricky Martin \u2013 May 24, 1999|work=Time|publisher=Time, Inc.|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref> Before the album's release, [[Janet Jackson]] collaborated with Ricky Martin for the Latin American version of \"[[Ask for More]]\", a promotional single and commercial released as part of an advertising campaign for soft drink company [[Pepsi]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xXQnfMiZIos Janet Jackson & Ricky Martin \u2013 \"Ask for More\" Pepsi Ad (Latin American Version)]. Retrieved on June 17, 2013</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Basham |first=David |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431862/ricky-martin-inks-endorsement-deal-with-pepsi-preps-fall-tour.jhtml |title=Ricky Martin Inks Endorsement Deal With Pepsi, Preps For Fall Tour |publisher=Mtv.com |date=October 15, 1999 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe first and most prominent single was \"[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]\", which reached number one in many countries around the world, including the United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Ireland and New Zealand. \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" is Ricky Martin's biggest hit. The video for \"Livin 'La Vida Loca\" was directed by [[Wayne Isham]] and starring model [[Nina Moric]]. It was followed by \"[[She's All I Ever Had]]\" which peaked at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Both tracks peaked at number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. \"Livin' la Vida Loca\" is generally seen as the song that began the [[Latin pop]] explosion of 1999 and made the transition of other Latin artists (first [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Enrique Iglesias]], then later [[Shakira]]) into the English-speaking market easier. ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' became one of the top-selling albums of 1999, and was certified 7\u00d7 platinum in the United States, selling over 15 million copies worldwide. In October 1999, Martin embarked on a very successful year-long [[Livin' la Vida Loca Tour]].\n\nAfter this success, a new English-language album, ''[[Sound Loaded]]'', was released in November 2000. It debuted at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and was certified 2\u00d7 platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]. \"[[She Bangs]]\" and \"[[Nobody Wants to Be Lonely]]\" (duet with [[Christina Aguilera]]) peaked at number twelve and thirteen on the Billboard Hot 100, respectively. Both singles reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs. ''Sound Loaded'' has sold over 8 million copies worldwide.\n\nIn February 2001, Martin released a Spanish greatest hits album entitled ''[[La Historia (Ricky Martin album)|La Historia]]'', which went to number one for five weeks on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] and debuted at number eighty-three on the Billboard 200. It also topped the chart in Sweden for three weeks. The album contained reworkings of two of his early songs \"[[Fuego Contra Fuego]]\" and \"[[El Amor de Mi Vida (song)|El Amor de Mi Vida]]\". In November 2001, an English-language greatest hits album, ''[[The Best of Ricky Martin]]'' was released outside North America. It contained two new remixes of \"[[Amor (Ricky Martin song)|Amor]]\".\n\n===2003\u20132006: ''Almas del Silencio''===\n[[File:Ricky Martin 2005.jpg|thumb|Ricky Martin in 2005.]]\n\nIn May 2003 Martin released a new Spanish album ''[[Almas del Silencio]].'' The first single \"[[Tal Vez]]\" debuted at number one on the [[Hot Latin Songs]] and stayed there for eleven weeks becoming the best performing Latin single of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/yearendcharts/2003/htltitl.jsp|title=Year-End Charts: Hot Latin Songs|date=December 27, 2003|work=Billboard |accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref> Martin said of the new album: \"I really needed to go back to focus, to my center, to the beginning. I had the need to search within, and really dig deep, and find those emotions that, because of the adrenaline and the euphoria that I lived for a couple of years, were probably sabotaged.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2003/vol7n26/LivinSerious-en.html |title=Livin' The Serious Life; Ricky Martin's New Album Matches His Outlook |publisher=Puertorico-herald.org |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' debuted at number twelve on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and reached number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] where it stayed for six weeks. The album sold more than one million copies worldwide.<ref name=BB>Adams, Steve: \"Martin's World View\", ''Billboard'' magazine, November 4, 2006, pp. 64\u201366.</ref> The next singles, \"[[Jaleo (Ricky Martin song)|Jaleo]]\" and \"[[Y Todo Queda en Nada]],\" reached number one on the Hot Latin Songs. \"[[Jaleo (Ricky Martin song)|Jaleo]]\" also topped the chart in Spain for four weeks.\n\nIn October 2005, he released his album [[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]. He commented on the album: \"I was really in touch with my emotions. I think this album is very multi-layered, just like life is. It's about feeling anger. It's about feeling joy. It's about feeling uncertainty. It's about feeling. And all my emotions are part of this production.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/11/11/earlyshow/leisure/music/main1038774.shtml|title=Ricky Martin Lets 'Life' Happen|author=Tatiana Morales|date=November 11, 2005|accessdate=February 15, 2010|publisher=Cbsnews.com}}</ref> The album debuted at number six on the [[Billboard 200]]. The first single from the album \"[[I Don't Care (Ricky Martin song)|I Don't Care]]\" featured rap verses by [[Fat Joe]] and [[Amerie]]. It peaked at number three on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] and number sixty-five on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Another song from the album \"[[It's Alright (Ricky Martin song)|It's Alright]]\" was re-recorded as a duet with French singer [[M. Pokora]]. It was successful in French-speaking countries and reached #4 in France.\n\n===2006\u20132007: ''MTV Unplugged'' and a world tour===\nOn August 17, 2006, Ricky Martin taped his ''[[MTV Unplugged (Ricky Martin album)|MTV Unplugged]]'' concert in Miami. It premiered on [[MTV Latin America]], [[Tr3s|MTV Tr3s]] and [[WJPX|MTV Puerto Rico]] in October 2006 and was released on CD and DVD in November 2006. The album was a critical and commercial success. It debuted at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]] and number thirty-eight on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. At the [[Latin Grammy Awards of 2008]], ''MTV Unplugged'' received [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Album]] and for [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Long Form Music Video|Best Long Form Music Video]]. The first single, \"[[Tu Recuerdo (Ricky Martin song)|Tu Recuerdo]]\" which featured La Mari of [[Chambao]], reached number one for three weeks on the [[Hot Latin Songs]]. The next single, \"[[P\u00e9gate]]\" peaked at number six on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].\n\nOn February 19, 2007, Martin began his worldwide [[Black and White Tour]]<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> which started with a performance at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum]] in Puerto Rico and concluded with a presentation at the [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City on October 14, 2007.<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> He also recorded a duet with [[Eros Ramazzotti]], \"[[Non siamo soli]]\" which topped the Italian chart for eleven consecutive weeks.\n\n===2007\u20132010: Career break===\nAfter finishing his worldwide tour, Martin took a break from the music industry and focused on his private life. In November 2007, [[Sony Music Latin|Sony BMG Norte]] released ''[[Ricky Martin Live: Black and White Tour]]'' on CD, DVD, and Blu-ray Disc. One year later, a Spanish-language greatest hits album was released, titled ''[[17 (Ricky Martin album)|17]]''. It was a summary of 17 years of Martin's musical career, which included mostly Spanish-language songs.\n\n===2010\u20132013: Autobiography, ''M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo'' and ''Evita''===\n[[File:Ricky Martin Chicago.jpg|thumb|180px|Martin performing in Chicago on April 19, 2011.]]\nRicky Martin's autobiography, ''Me'', was published on November 2, 2010. The book became part of [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2010-11-21/hardcover-nonfiction/list.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jennifer | last=Schuessler | title=Hardcover}}</ref> debuting at number five on the Hardcover Nonfiction list. A Spanish-language edition entitled ''Yo'' was published simultaneously.\n\nMartin's single, \"[[Lo Mejor de Mi Vida Eres T\u00fa]]\" featuring [[Natalia Jimenez]] also premiered on November 2, 2010 and peaked at number seventy-four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and topped the [[Hot Latin Songs]] for two weeks. It was followed by a new studio album, ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' released on January 31, 2011.<ref name = \"2011 album\">[http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/content_display/industry/e3i1c1499752deb3a60c4f4222c2ce37750 Leila Cobo, \"Ricky Martin Confirms Bilingual Album\"], ''Billboard'', October 20, 2010</ref> It debuted at number three on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and became the highest charting, primarily-Spanish language album in the United States, since ''[[Dreaming of You (Selena album)|Dreaming of You]]'' by [[Selena]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473151/nicki-minaj-hits-no-1-on-billboard-200-crosses-1-million-sales Nicki Minaj Hits No. 1 on Billboard 200, Crosses 1 Million Sales]. Retrieved February 11, 2011.</ref> ''M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo'' also represents the highest ever chart debut on the Billboard 200 for a [[Sony Music Latin]] release.<ref>[http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/Blog/Post/ec65e9ba-ec27-42da-9908-4ef3431c4c02 Ricky Martin delivers Latin music's highest chart debut in the last 15 years] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129190129/http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/Blog/Post/ec65e9ba-ec27-42da-9908-4ef3431c4c02 |date=January 29, 2013 }}. Retrieved February 11, 2011.</ref> It spent two weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums]]. On March 25, 2011, Martin started his [[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo World Tour]], which ended on November 12, 2011. The second single from the album, \"[[M\u00e1s (Ricky Martin song)|M\u00e1s]]\" was released on April 5, 2011 and peaked at number seven on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs]]. \"[[Fr\u00edo (song)|Fr\u00edo]]\" featuring [[Wisin & Yandel]] was chosen as the third single.\n\n''[[17: Greatest Hits]]'' was released on July 11, 2011 exclusively in the United Kingdom. Ricky Martin was playing [[Che Guevara in popular culture#In theater|Ch\u00e9]] in the Broadway revival of the show ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'', scheduled to begin previews on Broadway in March 2012, ahead of an opening in April 2012.<ref>[http://broadwayworld.com/article/EVITA_w_Martin_Roger_Begins_Previews_Mar_2012_Opens_Apr_2012_20110121 EVITA w/ Martin & Roger Begins Previews Mar. 2012; Opens Apr. 2012 2011/01/21]. Broadwayworld.com. Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> He received mixed reviews.\n\nMartin guest-starred as a Spanish teacher on the Fox TV show ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode \"[[The Spanish Teacher]]\" on February 7, 2012. Martin premiered his \"Ricky's Lip Conditioner\" lip balm in April 2012 as part of the M.A.C Cosmetics \"Ricky and Nicki for Viva Glam\" campaign. The advertisements for the range paired him with rapper [[Nicki Minaj]]. Martin's signature is featured on the lip balm packaging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maccosmetics.com/vivaglam2012/collection.html |title=M.A.C Viva Glam Collection |publisher=Maccosmetics.com |date= |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126195524/http://www.maccosmetics.com/vivaglam2012/collection.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013: ''The Voice Australia'', \"Come with Me\" and an Australian tour===\n[[File:Ricky Martin cropped1.jpg#mediaviewer/File:Ricky Martin cropped1.jpg|thumb|Martin in 2011]]\nIn November 2012, Martin was announced as a coach on ''[[The Voice (Australian TV series)|The Voice Australia]]'' and debuted in the first episode of season two, on April 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/ricky-martin-replaces-keith-urban-on-the-voice/story-e6frg6n6-1226526911581 | work=The Australian | title=Ricky Martin replaces Keith Urban on The Voice | date=November 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/first-review-of-the-voice-2013/news-story/f1438bae17f1b6710ef2313695cfb5ab|title=First review of The Voice 2013|date=2013-04-05|website=Daily Telegraph |language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> The finale aired on June 17. His finalist was former [[Ten Tenors]] singer [[Luke Kennedy]]. He became Runner-up losing to eventual winner [[Harrison Craig]].\n\nIn April 2013, Martin released his ''[[Greatest Hits: Souvenir Edition]]'' album in Australia, where it reached number two on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified Gold. In June 2013, he released a new English single titled \"[[Come with Me (Ricky Martin song)|Come with Me]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin-notas/1566940/ricky-martins-new-single-come-with-me-listen |title=Ricky Martin's New Single, 'Come With Me': Listen |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> He also embarked on the [[2013 Australian Tour]] in October 2013. In February 2014, he appeared with [[Jennifer Lopez]] & [[Wisin]] on the single and video \"[[Adrenalina (Wisin song)|Adrenalina]]\" taken from Wisin's album ''[[El Regreso del Sobreviviente]]''. The album version contains Spanish lyrics but the single was also made available in a [[Spanglish]] version. In April 2014, the single & video were released for \"[[Vida (Ricky Martin song)|Vida]]\", from the FIFA compilation album ''[[One Love, One Rhythm \u2013 The 2014 FIFA World Cup Official Album]]''. Here, the album version contains Spanglish lyrics, but the digital EP contained versions in Spanish & Portuguese as well as various dance remixes.\n\n===2014\u20132018: ''The Voice Mexico'', ''A Quien Quiera Escuchar'', One World Tour and The Assassination of Gianni Versace===\nIn July 2014, Martin was announced as a coach on ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico|The Voice Mexico]]''. The first episode of season four was aired on September 9, 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.tvnotas.com.mx/2014/09/07/C-65520-todos-los-detalles-del-gran-inicio-de-la-voz-mexico-2014.php | work=TV Notas | title=Todos los detalles del gran inicio de 'La Voz... M\u00e9xico 2014' | date=September 7, 2014}}</ref> On October 3, 2014, Martin started his Mexican One World Tour on [[Mexico City]], followed by [[Guadalajara]], [[Monterrey]] and [[Ensenada, Baja California|Ensenada]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/ | work=Ricky Martin Music | title= Ricky Martin: One World Tour Dates | date=September 7, 2014}}</ref> In November 2014, he was the closing act of the opening ceremony for the 22nd [[Central American and Caribbean Games]] \"[[2014 Central American and Caribbean Games|Veracruz 2014]]\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2264821-central-american-and-caribbean-games-2014-dates-schedule-events-and-countries | work=Bleacher Report | title=Central American and Caribbean Games 2014: Dates, Schedule, Events and Countries | date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince Martin's debut as a coach on [[The Voice Australia]] in 2013, he continued as a coach on [[The Voice (Australia season 3)|Season 3]], in 2014, alongside [[will.i.am]], [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Joel Madden]]. He returned to the panel alongside [[Delta Goodrem]], [[Benji Madden]] (teamed up with his brother [[Joel Madden]]), and newcomer [[Jessie J]] in 2015; before leaving the show before the [[The Voice (Australia season 5)|fifth series]] to focus on music commitments.\n\nMartin released his album ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' in February 2015. The album won the [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Latin Pop Album]], making this Martin's second Grammy win to date.\n\nIt was announced on December 24, 2015 that he would not return to The Voice Australia in 2016 and will be replaced by [[Ronan Keating]].\n\nOn September 22, 2016, Martin released a new song \"[[Vente Pa' Ca]]\" with Colombian singer, [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]]. The song skyrocketed in music charts with over 1.6 billion views on the music video as of February 2020.\n\nIn November 2016, Martin announced a Las Vegas residency show, [[All In (residency show)|All In]], which began on April 4, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7580424/ricky-martin-las-vegas-residency-dates-monte-carlo|title=Ricky Martin Reveals Las Vegas Residency Dates: 'I Have Been Thinking About This for Years'|date=November 16, 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Martin portrayed [[Antonio D'Amico]], partner of fashion designer [[Gianni Versace]], in the second season of the true crime television series ''[[American Crime Story]]'', subtitled ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]''. The show was praised but Martin's performance and characterization of D'Amico received mixed reception. Despite this, Martin was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie]], his first ever nomination.\n\nMartin released his single, \"[[Fiebre (Ricky Martin song)|Fiebre]]\", on February 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ricky Martin&nbsp;\u2013 Fiebre (feat. Wisin & Yandel)|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/fiebre-feat-wisin-yandel-single/1350862364|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]|accessdate=February 23, 2018}}</ref> And its music video has over 100 million views on YouTube as of November 2019.\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Movimiento'' and Movimiento Tour===\n\nMartin announced his new album will be released on 2020 and he started his world tour, [[Movimiento Tour]] on February 7, 2020.\n\n==Musical style==\nMartin possesses a [[tenor]] vocal range.<ref name=\"books.google.ca\">{{Cite book|title=Rock-N-Roll Gold Rush |last=Dean |first= Maury|authorlink= |coauthors= |year= 2003|publisher= Algora Publishing|location= |isbn= 0-87586-207-1|page= 34|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&dq=Rock-N-Roll+Gold+Rush+mariah+carey&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&q=whitney+houston#PPA34,M1}}</ref> Martin cites a variety of the Latin music genres as influences, including salsa, merengue, and bolero.<ref name=\"Martin72\">Martin, 2010. p. 72</ref> He also is inspired by artists such as the [[Fania All-Stars]], [[Celia Cruz]], [[El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico]], and [[Gilberto Santa Rosa]], some of which his mother played for him as a child.<ref name=\"Martin72\"/> Martin credits these musicians with helping him \"appreciate the richness of [his] island's culture.\"<ref name=\"Martin72\"/>\n\nSome of Martin's additional influences include [[Michael Jackson]], [[Cher]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Elvis Presley]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Barbra Streisand]] and [[Daniel Day-Lewis]].\n\n==Other media==\nRicky Martin's first children's book, ''Santiago the Dreamer in Land Among the Stars'', was published in November 2013 with its Spanish-language edition, ''Santiago El So\u00f1ador en Entre Las Estrellas'', released simultaneously. The book was illustrated by Patricia Castelao.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.diariodepontevedra.es/articulo/noticias/patricia-castelao-la-dibujante-pontevedresa-del-nino-de-ricky-martin/20140115170800245779.html|title=Patricia Castelao, la dibujante pontevedresa del ni\u00f1o de Ricky Martin|last=Alvarez|first=Miguel|date=January 15, 2014|website=Diario de Pontevedra |accessdate=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMartin was raised Catholic but says he is open to all sorts of religious beliefs, especially the [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] philosophy.<ref name=\"buddhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=9,3467,0,0,1,0|title=Ricky Martin admires Buddhist philosophy|work=The Buddhist Channel|publisher=Asian News International|date=November 28, 2006}}</ref> He feels that subscribing to a specific religion can \"limit\" an individual in certain aspects, and noted in 2006, \"I really like the Buddhist philosophy but that doesn't mean that I am of the religion. If I subscribe to Buddhism, I can't be of anything else...I am not going to follow those rules.\"<ref name=\"buddhist\"/> Martin began practicing [[yoga]] after a trip to Thailand in 1997.<ref name=\"zen\"/>\n\nIn November 2011, he acquired [[Spanish nationality law|Spanish nationality]] in recognition of his artistic talents and for having roots in the country \u2013 Martin's grandmother is Spanish, and he owns a residence in [[Madrid]]. In September 2011, he sold his home in Miami.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.miamism.com/ricky-martins-golden-beach-home-for-sale/|title =Ricky Martin's Golden Beach Home For Sale|author =Ines Hegedus-Garcia|date =September 21, 2011|accessdate =January 22, 2012|archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20111227081420/http://www.miamism.com/ricky-martins-golden-beach-home-for-sale/|archive-date =December 27, 2011|url-status =dead}}</ref> In a public statement, written in Spanish, Martin explicitly stated that he has not abandoned his Puerto Rican identity: \"I was born in Puerto Rico, I am a Puerto Rican, and Puerto Rico is my homeland. I made the request for Spanish citizenship some time ago, I was just waiting for a response. This step is part of planning for the future within a global community of whom I am part. Spain is a country with which I share many memories and strong ties born of my roots and the love they have given me since I first visited.\"<ref name=galaz/> In January 2013, he relocated to [[Sydney, Australia]] to accommodate his position on [[The Voice Australia|''The Voice'' Australia]]. In 2018, he relocated permanently to [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref>{{Cite av media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2dkl0fUKHAM|title= Inside Ricky Martin's Serene Los Angeles Home}}</ref>\n\n===Coming out===\nMartin was in an on-off platonic relationship with Mexican TV host [[Rebecca de Alba]] for more than 14&nbsp;years. The pair had spoken of starting a family together,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.ca/profiles/rickymartin/|title=Ricky Martin |publisher=Hellomagazine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.ca/music/2003/06/20/rickymartin/|title=Ricky Martin |publisher=Hellomagazine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telemundo52.com/cotorreando/4537195/detail.html |title=Rebeca de Alba saw Ricky Martin as the father of their children (translated) |publisher=TelemundoLA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006021124/http://www.telemundo52.com/cotorreando/4537195/detail.html |archivedate=October 6, 2011 }}</ref> and Martin had at one point considered proposing to her.<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?in_article_id=59812&in_page_id=7&in_a_source=&expand=true Ricky likes being alone]. Metro.co.uk (August 2, 2007). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> In August 2008, Martin became the father of twin boys, Matteo and Valentino, born by a [[Surrogacy|gestational surrogate]] mother.<ref>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2008/12/59800522/1 Ricky Martin has twins babies and 'no nanny' \u2013 USATODAY.com]. Content.usatoday.com (December 10, 2008). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nAfter the success of \"Livin' la Vida Loca\", Martin's personal life became a subject of interest due to his large gay following, and he was questioned about his sexual orientation. In a December 2000 interview with ''[[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]]'', he was asked to comment on the rumors surrounding his sexuality. He replied: \"I don't think I should have to tell anyone if I am gay or not, or who I've slept with or not.\"<ref>Sally Morgan [https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-67755270 \"Ricky Martin \u2013 It's no one's business whether I've been to bed with a cow, a broom or a woman...\",] ''The Mirror'', December 9, 2000</ref><ref>Sally Morgan [http://www.rmtee.com/rmtee/html/press70.shtml \"Ricky Martin \u2013 It's no one's business whether I've been to bed with a cow, a broom or a woman...\",] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043719/http://www.rmtee.com/rmtee/html/press70.shtml |date=March 4, 2016 }} ''The Mirror'', December 9, 2000, as reproduced on rmtee.com</ref> In 2010, [[Barbara Walters]] expressed some regret for pushing Martin in a 2000 interview to admit if he was gay. The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' quoted her as saying, \"When I think back on it now, I feel it was an inappropriate question.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/2010/03/09/barbara-walters-ricky-martin-interview/ |title=Barbara Walters Regrets Ricky Martin Interview |publisher=PopEater.com |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ouzounian |first=Richard |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/article/775131--barbara-walters-what-kind-of-tree-is-she |title=Barbara Walters: What kind of tree is she? |work=Toronto Star |date=March 6, 2010 |accessdate=August 2, 2010 |location=Toronto}}</ref> On March 29, 2010, Martin publicly [[coming out|came out as gay]] in a post on his official website, stating: \"I am proud to say that I am a fortunate homosexual man. I am very blessed to be who I am.\"<ref>[http://www.popeater.com/2010/03/29/ricky-martin-gay/ \"Ricky Martin Gay Bombshell: 'I am a Fortunate Homosexual Man'\"], PopEater.com Staff, March 29, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/29/ricky-martin-comes-out-im_n_517625.html |title=Ricky Martin Comes Out: \"I'm A Fortunate Homosexual Man\" |work=Huffington Post |date= March 29, 2010|accessdate=August 2, 2010 |first=Katherine |last=Thomson}}</ref> Martin said that \"these years in silence and reflection made me stronger and reminded me that acceptance has to come from within, and that this kind of truth gives me the power to conquer emotions I didn't even know existed.\"<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14639/81249 Yep, He's Gay: Ricky Martin Comes Out of the Closet | Rolling Stone Music] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208161915/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/14639/81249 |date=December 8, 2010 }}. Rollingstone.com (March 29, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref>\n\nAlso in 2010, Martin said that for many years he thought he was [[bisexual]], telling [[Oprah Winfrey]] that \"I felt it with a woman, I felt passion and it felt good. And I'm sure I'm not the only gay man that felt attraction towards women...Sometimes I really did fall in love with women, for many years I did.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/commentary/2016/1/25/ricky-martin-bi-closet |title=Is Ricky Martin in the Bi Closet? |publisher=The Advocate |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/ricky-martin-loved-his-affairs-with-women-but-hes-definitely-not-bisexual-20101102 |title=Ricky Martin Loved His Affairs With Women, But He's Definitely Not Bisexual |publisher=Queerty |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref> He announced on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' that he was in a relationship.<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/Ricky-Martin-on-Coming-Out/10 Ricky Martin on Love]. Oprah.com (November 2, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> In 2011, during his acceptance speech of the Vito Russo Award at the [[22nd GLAAD Media Awards]], Martin publicly thanked his boyfriend, Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez Abella, an economist.<ref>[http://www.elnuevodia.com/secasarickymartin-1156746.html Se casa Ricky Martin] on ''[[El Nuevo D\u00eda]]'' (January 1, 2012)</ref><ref>[http://www.popeater.com/2011/03/21/ricky-martin-partner-glaad-media-awards/ Ricky Martin thanks partner at GLAAD Awards] on PopEater; Mitchell, John (March 21, 2011)</ref> His relationship with Gonz\u00e1lez Abella ended in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ricky-martin-splits-from-boyfriend-carlos-gonzalez-abella/|title=Ricky Martin splits from boyfriend Carlos Gonzalez Abella|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, during an interview with ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Spanish Vanity Fair]]'', Martin stated, \"I don't regret anything, any of the relationships I've lived. They taught me a lot, both men and women equally.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pagesix.com/2012/03/22/ricky-martin-ive-slept-with-women-and-felt-wonderful-things/ |title=Ricky Martin: 'I've slept with women and felt wonderful things' |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/la-revista/articulos/exclusiva-ricky-martin-su-novio-y-sus-hijos-en-una-sesio-n-de-fotos-u-nica/16297 |title=LA NUEVA VIDA DE RICKY |publisher=Spanish Vanity Fair |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref> In 2016, he stated that he is attracted to both men and women, but, because he is only interested in romantic relationships with men, he does not identify as bisexual. \"I know that I like both men and women, I'm against sexual labels, we are simply human beings with emotional and sexual needs,\" he stated in an interview with the Mexican magazine ''Fama!'' He added that \"I am gay, men fascinate me, but I like to enjoy sex in total freedom, so I'm open to having sex with a woman if I feel desire.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.advocate.com/people/2016/1/19/ricky-martin-open-sex-women-doesnt-call-himself-bi |title=Ricky Martin 'Open' to Sex With Women, But Doesn't Call Himself Bi |publisher=The Advocate |accessdate=2018-10-14}}</ref>\n\nMartin has also expressed support for [[same-sex marriage]] in an interview on ''[[Larry King Live]]''.<ref name=\"LK_Live\">{{cite web|url = http://www.samesame.com.au/news/international/6110/Let_Ricky_Martin_get_married|title = Let Ricky Martin Get Married!|publisher = samesame.com.au|author = Akersten, M.|date = November 11, 2010|accessdate = November 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101113135622/http://www.samesame.com.au/news/international/6110/Let_Ricky_Martin_get_married|archivedate = November 13, 2010|df = mdy-all}}</ref> Martin delivered a speech at the United Nations Homophobia Conference on November 12, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/12/ricky-martin-united-nations-i-lived-in-fear_n_2284350.html | work=Huffington Post | title=Ricky Martin to United Nations: 'I Lived In Fear' | date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Beginning April 2016, he started dating [[Jwan Yosef]], a Syrian-Swedish painter of Kurdish and Armenian descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902041630/http://www.umagmag.com/2015/08/a-conversation-with-artist-jwan-yosef/|title=U+MAG {{!}} A conversation with artist Jwan Yosef|date=2015-09-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/ricky-martin-confirms-dating-handsome-7793026|title=Ricky Martin confirms he is dating handsome artist Jwan Yosef|first=Simon|last=Keegan|date=April 20, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The two announced their engagement on November 16, 2016, while on the ''[[Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/809694/ricky-martin-engaged-to-jwan-yosef|title=Ricky Martin Engaged to Jwan Yosef|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2018, Martin announced that he and Yosef are married.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ricky Martin & Jwan Yosef Are Married|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8093813/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-are-married|work=Billboard|accessdate=2018-01-11}}</ref> On December 31, 2018, Martin and Yosef announced, via [[Instagram]], the birth of their daughter Luc\u00eda Martin-Yosef.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Instagram|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BsEY2hjnRtW|work=Instagram}}</ref>\nOn February 2018, in an interview with E. Alex Jung of Vulture, Martin discussed working on ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' as [[Antonio D'Amico]] and how he wanted his portrayal to help normalize open relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/02/ricky-martin-on-american-crime-story-versace-and-coming-out.html|title=Ricky Martin on ACS: Versace, Coming Out, and 'Normalizing' Open Relationships|publisher=Vulture|date=Feb 14, 2018|access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\nIn 2019, while accepting an award during a human rights dinner in Washington DC, Martin announced he and his husband are expecting their fourth child together and on October 29, 2019, Martin and Yosef announced, via [[Instagram]], the birth of their son Renn Martin-Yosef.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://people.com/parents/ricky-martin-jwan-yosef-welcome-baby-son-renn| title=Ricky Martin and Husband Jwan Yosef Announce the Birth of Their Fourth Child, Son Renn| accessdate=October 30, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===Humanitarian work and impact===\n[[File:Ricky Martin at the National Puerto Rican Day Parade.jpg|thumb|left|Ricky Martin at a [[Puerto Rican Day Parade|Puerto Rican Day annual parade]] in New York City]]\nMartin is the founder of ''Fundaci\u00f3n Ricky Martin'' (''Ricky Martin Foundation''), a non-profit organization. Among the events promoted by the foundation was a summer camp, which included Martin's personal participation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.primerahora.com/noticia/farandula/espectaculosasi/ricky_martin_sorprende_a_sus_ahijados/208318 |title=Ricky Martin sorprende a sus \"ahijados\" |newspaper=Primera Hora |language=Spanish |date=July 9, 2008 |accessdate=July 14, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719114639/http://www.primerahora.com/noticia/farandula/espectaculosasi/ricky_martin_sorprende_a_sus_ahijados/208318 |archivedate=July 19, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nMartin has been honored with accolades including: Leadership in the Arts Award, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'''s Spirit of Hope Award, [[ALMA Award]], [[GLAAD Media Award|Vanguard Award]], International Humanitarian Award by the [[International Centre for Missing & Exploited Children]], Hispanic Heritage Award for his humanitarian work through the Sabera Foundation in rescuing three orphan girls from the streets of [[Kolkata]] (September 2002).{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn December 2003, Martin was appointed a UNICEF [[Goodwill Ambassador]]. In his role as UNICEF Goodwill Ambassador, Ricky Martin has supported [[UNICEF]]'s efforts in fighting for children's rights, especially in the area of child trafficking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ricky Martin Goodwill Ambassador |url=https://www.unicef.org/people/people_51425.html |website=UNICEF |accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMartin has also collaborated with the [[International Organization for Migration]] on the ''Llama y Vive'' (''Call and Live''), a campaign which is aimed to facilitate prevention of human trafficking, protection of the youngest victims of child trafficking, and prosecution of the traffickers. For his work against [[human trafficking]], the [[United States Department of State]] named Martin one of its Heroes in Ending Modern-Day Slavery in 2005.\n\n[[File:Ricky Martin Foundation.jpg|180px|Foundation logo|thumb]]\nThe Ricky Martin Foundation was founded by Ricky Martin, with the mission to advocate for the well-being of children around the world.\n\n===Politics===\n[[File:Ricky Martin in Congress.jpg|thumb|right|Ricky Martin (''mid-right'') in Congress, with [[Luis Fortu\u00f1o]] (''far left''), [[Tom Lantos]] (''mid-left'') and [[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Chris Smith]] (''far right'').]]\nMartin was a headliner in the 2001 inauguration celebration for President [[George W. Bush]]; he even invited the newly elected president to join him on stage to dance. Photographs of this moment were broadcast throughout the world, and Martin wrote about it in his song \"[[Asignatura Pendiente]]\". Martin's view of President Bush changed over the [[Iraq War]], as expressed in his declaration to the [[Associated Press]] that he will \"always condemn war and those who promulgate it.\"<ref name=\"NewsMax\">{{cite news|url = http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2007/2/16/85325.shtml|title = Singer Ricky Martin 'Fingers' Bush for Iraq Criticism|newspaper = [[NewsMax]], [[Associated Press]]|date = February 16, 2007|url-status=dead|archivedate = February 18, 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070218092851/http://newsmax.com/archives/ic/2007/2/16/85325.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work = [[BBC News]]|date = February 16, 2007|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6369705.stm|accessdate = August 9, 2017|title = Ricky Martin defends Bush gesture}}</ref>\n\nDuring his appearance at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] on April 29, 2010, Martin expressed his disagreement with the [[Arizona SB 1070]] bill, a proposed law that would have required police officers to request documents from individuals whom they suspected to be illegal immigrants.<ref name=\"speaksout\">{{cite news|title=Ricky Martin Criticizes Arizona's Immigration Law|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/958416/ricky-martin-criticizes-arizonas-immigration-law|newspaper = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher = [[Prometheus Global Media]]|date = April 30, 2010|accessdate = August 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Ricky Martin albums discography|Ricky Martin singles discography|Ricky Martin videography}}\n{{see also|Menudo (band)#Discography}}\n* ''[[Ricky Martin (1991 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Me Amaras (album)|Me Amaras]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[A Medio Vivir (album)|A Medio Vivir]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Vuelve (album)|Vuelve]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Ricky Martin (1999 album)|Ricky Martin]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Sound Loaded]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Almas del Silencio]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Life (Ricky Martin album)|Life]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[A Quien Quiera Escuchar]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Movimiento]]'' (2020)\n\n==Filmography==\n*1985: ''[[The Love Boat]]'' (TV series) as Ricky\n*1987: ''Por siempre amigos'' (Argentinian TV series) as Ricky\n*1991: ''[[Alcanzar una estrella II]]'' (TV series) as Pablo Loredo\n*1992: ''M\u00e1s que alcanzar una estrella'' as Enrique\n*1993: ''[[Getting By]]'' (TV series) as Martin\n*1994: ''[[General Hospital]]'' (TV series) as Miguel Morez (1994\u201395)\n*1996: ''Barefoot in Paradise'' (TV series) as Sandoval\n*1997: ''[[Hercules (1997 film)|Hercules]]'' (Latin American dub, voice role) as Hercules\n*1999: ''[[Idle Hands]]'' as Man in Car Park\n*2006: ''[[Sos mi vida]]'' (Argentinian TV series) as himself\n*2011: ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'': guest\n*2011: ''[[Susana Gim\u00e9nez]]'': guest\n*2011: ''[[American Dad!]]'' as himself (uncredited)\n*2012: ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' (TV series) as David Mart\u00ednez\n*2013: ''[[The Voice (Australia series 2)|The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' (TV series) as Himself (Judge)\n*2014: ''[[The Voice (Australia series 3)|The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[La Voz... M\u00e9xico]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2014: ''[[The Voice Ahla Sawt|The Voice Arabia]]'' as Himself (guest judge) \n*2015: ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' (Latin American dub, voice role) as Herb Overkill\n*2015: ''[[The Voice Australia]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n*2015: ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]]'' as himself (judge and executive producer)\n*2015: ''[[Nuestra Belleza Latina 2015]]'' as himself (Celebrity guest)\n*2017: ''[[Lip Sync Battle]]'' as himself (winner vs. [[Kate Upton]])\n*2018: ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' as [[Antonio D'Amico]]\n*2019: ''[[Amici di Maria De Filippi]]'' as Himself (Coach)\n\n==Theatre==\n*''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'' (1996), Broadway&nbsp;\u2013 [[Marius Pontmercy]]\n*''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'', (2012), Broadway&nbsp;\u2013 Ch\u00e9\n\n==Tours==\n* Ricky Martin Tour (1992)\n* Me Amaras Tour (1993\u20131994)\n* A Medio Vivir Tour (1995\u20131997)\n* [[Vuelve World Tour]] (1998)\n* [[Livin' la Vida Loca Tour]] (1999\u20132000)\n* [[One Night Only with Ricky Martin]] (2005\u20132006)\n* [[Black and White Tour]] (2007)\n* [[M\u00fasica + Alma + Sexo World Tour]]<ref>[https://twitter.com/ricky_martin/status/13011345884581888 Twitter / Ricky Martin: First stop on my \"Music+So]. Twitter.com (December 9, 2010). Retrieved on February 25, 2011.</ref> (2011)\n* [[Ricky Martin Live]] (2013\u20132014)\n* Live in Mexico (2014)\n* [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|One World Tour]] (2015\u20132017)\n* Ricky Martin en Concierto (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rickymartinmusic.com/events/|title=Events {{!}} Ricky Martin|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/hashtag/RickyMartinEnConcierto?src=hash&lang=en|title=#RickyMartinEnConcierto hashtag on Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n* [[Movimiento Tour]] (2020)\n* [[Enrique Iglesias and Ricky Martin Live in Concert]] {{small|(with [[Enrique Iglesias]])}} (2020)\n\n==Honors and awards==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Ricky Martin}}\nRicky Martin has received numerous awards, including 2 [[Grammy Award]]s, 4 [[Latin Grammy Awards]], 5 [[MTV Video Music Awards]], 3 [[Billboard Music Awards]], 9 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], 2 [[American Music Awards]], 2 [[Latin American Music Awards]], 8 [[World Music Awards]] and has been [[Emmy]]-nominated.\n*Martin was chosen along with [[F\u00e9lix Trinidad]] in 1999, to lead Puerto Rico's worldwide tourism campaign, both exemplifying Puerto Rico's youthfulness, enthusiasm and indefatigable character.\n*In February 2004, Martin received the [[Lo Nuestro Excellence Award|Excellence Award]] at the [[Lo Nuestro Awards]] in Miami.\n*Martin was honored as the 2006 [[Latin Recording Academy Person of the Year]] by the [[Latin Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences|Latin Recording Academy]] on November 1, 2006. He was chosen for his accomplishments as a world-renowned entertainer, consummate performer and passionate humanitarian. A portion of the proceeds from the evening's tribute dinner was used for benefitting Ricky Martin's charitable efforts.\n*On October 16, 2007, Martin received the 2351st [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] star,<ref>[http://www.boston.com/ae/celebrity/articles/2007/10/16/ricky_martin_gets_walk_of_fame_star/ Ricky Martin gets Walk of Fame star \u2013 Boston.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=February 2010}}</ref> shortly after receiving the [[Freedom of the City|key to the city]] of [[Miami Beach, Florida]] on October 11. The star is located beside the Hollywood and Highland complex. Los Angeles mayor [[Antonio Villaraigosa]] and [[Rita Moreno]] were invited to the unveiling ceremony.<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite book| title=Ricky Martin: Bien ubicada su estrella| publisher=El Nuevo D\u00eda| location=Puerto Rico| chapter=Flash!/Cine| language=Spanish| date=October 14, 2007| page=94}}</ref>\n*In 2011, Martin was awarded Spanish citizenship by the Council of Ministers, to honor his contributions to the arts.<ref name=\"NE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lne.es/sociedad-cultura/2011/11/04/ricky-martin-benicio-toro-nacionalidad-espanola/1152213.html |title=Ricky Martin y Benicio del Toro ya tienen la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola|publisher=lne.es |date=November 4, 2011|accessdate=November 4, 2011|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico|Latin music|LGBT}}\n*[[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n*[[List of Puerto Ricans]]\n*[[White Latin American]]\n*[[Corsican immigration to Puerto Rico]]\n*[[Cultural diversity in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite 