{"title_page": "Simon Kukes", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Simon Kukes\n| residence   = \n| image       = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| known       = \n| occupation  = oil business manager, consultant\n| title       = Chief Executive\n| salary      = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| children    = \n| relations   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n| employer    = \n}}\n'''Simon Gregory Kukes''' (Russian: \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u043a\u0435\u0441; born 5 December 1946) is a Russian-born American chemist and retired oil industry businessman. He immigrated to the US to work in the oil industry in the late seventies, and returned to Russia with [[AMOCO]] in 1995. He became vice president at [[YUKOS]], president of [[TNK-BP]] from 1998 until 2003, and returned to head Yukos, replacing [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]]. Officially retired he is still consulting oil businesses. \n\nHolding various positions over the years, Dr. Simon Kukes has served as the principal of his personal investment company, SK Energy LLC, since April 2013. He is the CEO and Director of PEDEVCO Corp. <ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/person/1790711</ref>. \n\nHis commitment to the oil and gas industry has inspired Dr. Simon Kukes to publish more than 60 scientific papers and two books on the oil and gas industry of Russia and the United States. <ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2003/nov/13/russia.oilandpetrol</ref> He is also the holder of more than 130 patents, primarily in Oil and Petrochemical Processing. <ref>http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-bool.html&r=0&f=S&l=50&TERM1=Kukes&FIELD1=INNM&co1=AND&TERM2=&FIELD2=&d=PALL</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSimon Kukes was born in [[Moscow]] to [[History of the Jews in Russia|Jewish]] parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2018/05/22/news-opinion/know-oligarch-guide-jewish-machers-russia-probe|title=Know your oligarch: A guide to the Jewish machers in the Russia probe|author=[[Ron Kampeas]]|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=2018-09-01|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> He studied at [[D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia|Mendeleev Moscow Chemical & Technological Institute]] and at [[Nesmeyanov Institute of Organoelement Compounds|Nesmeyanov Institute of Hetero-Organic Compounds]] for his postgraduate studies.<ref name=\"komm\">{{cite web | url=http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_/ | title=Simon Kukes Prefers Drugs to Oil | work=Kommersant | date=25 January 2005 | access-date=1 October 2016 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930153358/http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_ | archive-date=30 September 2016 | df= }}</ref>\n\nKukes attended several prestigious universities all over the globe, receiving his Bachelor of Science in Chemical Engineering from the [[D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia]], where he graduated with Honors. \n\nFrom there, he pursued his PhD in Physical Chemistry at the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]], where he would later be a Research Associate for Nuclear and Electronic Resonance. \n\nKukes then attended [[Rice University]] in Houston, Texas where he was a Postdoctoral Fellow.\n<ref>https://www.pedevco.com/template_files/480/about-us/management-team.php</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKukes immigrated to the US in the late seventies, and became an American citizen,<ref name=\"os\" /> giving up his Russian passport.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cfr.org/russian-federation/conversation-simon-kukes/p6759 | title=A Conversation with Simon Kukes ( Transcript) | work=Council on Foreign Relations | date=9 February 2004 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> He briefly taught at [[Rice University]], in Houston, Texas. From 1979 to 1987, he was the Technical Director of oil-refining and petro-chemistry for [[Phillips Petroleum]] and in 1987 became Vice-President over marketing and business development for [[Amoco]]. In 1995, he became vice president of its Moscow Office. From 1996 to 1998, he was vice president at [[YUKOS]]. He was also the President and Chief Executive of Tyumen Oil Company (TNK) from 1998 until it combined with British Petroleum in 2003 to create [[TNK-BP]]. <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160930153358/http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_</ref>\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6-8 September 2000-26.jpg|thumb|TNK President Simon Kukes with Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6\u20138 September 2000 signing an agreement between TNK and Eximbank USA.]]\n \nIn November 2003 after being elected to the board of [[YUKOS]] he replaced [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] to head the company for a year.<ref name=\"komm\" /><ref name=\"os\">{{cite web | url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2016/09/russian-born-oil-magnate-gives-big-to-trump-victory/ | title=Russian-born oil magnate gives big to Trump Victory | publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics |website=[[OpenSecrets.org]] | date=26 September 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Ashley Balcerzak}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2004 he became co-owner of the Russian oil company ZAO Samara-Nafta,<ref name=\"komm\" /> a subsidiary of [[Lukoil]].<ref name=\"os\" /> As of 2005, Kukes owned 8 percent in [[Amarin Corporation]], then a neurology drug developer.<ref name=\"komm\" /> \nHe also was a partner at [[Hess Corporation]], a New York-based oil and gas company.<ref name=\"os\" />\n\nAs of 2016 he is a consultant for oil businesses in the US and Russia,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.naftallc.com/ | title=About NAFTA Consulting | publisher=NAFTA LLC | work=website | date=n.d. | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> as well as [[Leverate]], a [[FinTech]] company for foreign exchange brokers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.financemagnates.com/binary-options/technology/oil-magnate-simon-kukes-explains-why-he-became-a-major-leverate-investor/ | title=Oil Magnate Simon Kukes Explains Why He Became a Major Leverate Investor | publisher=Finance Magnates Ltd | date=2 July 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Avi Mizrahi}}</ref>\n\nFrom January 2005 to April 2013, Kukes was the CEO at Samara-Nafta, a Russian oil company that partnered with US-based international oil company, Hess Corporation. <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160930153358/http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_</ref>\n\nFollowing his time at TNK, Kukes joined Yukos Oil Company in Moscow presiding as the CEO and Chairman. <ref>https://www.ogj.com/general-interest/article/17255881/yukos-names-simon-kukes-its-new-ceo</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Kukes invested in an Israeli company, GLAMZ, a platform connecting customers to local beauty service providers. <ref>https://www.jpost.com/Special-Content/GLAMZ-Top-beauty-professionals-online-610467</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the Wall Street Journal voted Kukes as one of the Top 10 Central European Executives. He is also the recipient of the Medal of the Ministry for Natural Resources of the Russian Federation, as well as the American Society of Competition Development Award for Leadership. In 2003, he was named by The Financial Times and PricewaterhouseCoopers as one of the 64 most respected business leaders in the world. \n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, Kukes bought a 4-room condominium in [[Trump Parc]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://observer.com/2000/03/steve-wynn-bets-on-820-fifth-avenue-and-loses-big/ | title=Steve Wynn Bets on 820 Fifth Avenue and Loses Big; Upper East Side | work=The Observer | date=27 March 2000 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Deborah Schoeneman}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kukes, Simon}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American political fundraisers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Simon Kukes\n| residence   = \n| image       = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1946}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| death_cause = \n| known       = \n| occupation  = oil business manager, consultant\n| title       = Chief Executive\n| salary      = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| partner     = \n| children    = \n| relations   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n| employer    = \n}}\n'''Simon Grigorievich Kukes''' (Russian: \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u043a\u0435\u0441; born 5 December 1946) is a Russian-born American chemist and retired oil industry businessman. He immigrated to the US to work in the oil industry in the late seventies, and returned to Russia with [[AMOCO]] in 1995. He became vice president at [[YUKOS]], president of [[TNK-BP]] from 1998 until 2003, and returned to head Yukos, replacing [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]]. Officially retired he is still consulting oil businesses. He has contributed to [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump\u2019s presidential campaign]] and [[Elizabeth Cheney]]'s 2016 run for a congressional seat.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSimon Kukes was born in [[Moscow]] to [[History of the Jews in Russia|Jewish]] parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jta.org/2018/05/22/news-opinion/know-oligarch-guide-jewish-machers-russia-probe|title=Know your oligarch: A guide to the Jewish machers in the Russia probe|author=[[Ron Kampeas]]|date=May 22, 2018|accessdate=2018-09-01|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency|JTA]]}}</ref> He studied at [[D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia|Mendeleev Moscow Chemical & Technological Institute]] and at [[Nesmeyanov Institute of Organoelement Compounds|Nesmeyanov Institute of Hetero-Organic Compounds]] for his postgraduate studies.<ref name=\"komm\">{{cite web | url=http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_/ | title=Simon Kukes Prefers Drugs to Oil | work=Kommersant | date=25 January 2005 | access-date=1 October 2016 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930153358/http://www.kommersant.com/p541561/r_500/Simon_Kukes_Prefers_Drugs_to_Oil_ | archive-date=30 September 2016 | df= }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKukes immigrated to the US in the late seventies, and became an American citizen,<ref name=\"os\" /> giving up his Russian passport.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cfr.org/russian-federation/conversation-simon-kukes/p6759 | title=A Conversation with Simon Kukes ( Transcript) | work=Council on Foreign Relations | date=9 February 2004 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> He briefly taught at [[Rice University]], in Houston, Texas. From 1979 to 1986, he worked for [[Phillips Petroleum]], thereafter for [[Amoco]]. In 1995, he became vice president of its Moscow Office. From 1996 to 1998, he was vice president at [[YUKOS]]. From February 1998 until June 2003 he was president of [[TNK-BP]] or Tyumen Oil Company, and  brokered a joint venture with [[BP]]=that year.<ref name=\"komm\" />\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6-8 September 2000-26.jpg|thumb|TNK President Simon Kukes with Vladimir Putin at the Millennium Summit 6\u20138 September 2000 signing an agreement between TNK and Eximbank USA.]]\n \nIn November 2003 after being elected to the board of [[YUKOS]] he replaced [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]] to head the company for a year.<ref name=\"komm\" /><ref name=\"os\">{{cite web | url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2016/09/russian-born-oil-magnate-gives-big-to-trump-victory/ | title=Russian-born oil magnate gives big to Trump Victory | publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics |website=[[OpenSecrets.org]] | date=26 September 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Ashley Balcerzak}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2004 he became co-owner of the Russian oil company ZAO Samara-Nafta,<ref name=\"komm\" /> a subsidiary of [[Lukoil]].<ref name=\"os\" /> As of 2005, Kukes owned 8 percent in [[Amarin Corporation]], then a neurology drug developer.<ref name=\"komm\" /> \nHe also was a partner at [[Hess Corporation]], a New York-based oil and gas company.<ref name=\"os\" />\n\nAs of 2016 he is a consultant for oil businesses in the US and Russia,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.naftallc.com/ | title=About NAFTA Consulting | publisher=NAFTA LLC | work=website | date=n.d. | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> as well as [[Leverate]], a [[FinTech]] company for foreign exchange brokers.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.financemagnates.com/binary-options/technology/oil-magnate-simon-kukes-explains-why-he-became-a-major-leverate-investor/ | title=Oil Magnate Simon Kukes Explains Why He Became a Major Leverate Investor | publisher=Finance Magnates Ltd | date=2 July 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Avi Mizrahi}}</ref>\n\n==Political contributions==\nIn 2003 Kukes had said in an interview with the Guardian: \"I am not a political animal. I spent one year in Siberia [sorting out operational oil issues for TNK] in 2001. That is not what someone interested in politics does.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2003/nov/13/russia.oilandpetrol | title=Oligarch? I wish | work=The Guardian | date=13 November 2003 | accessdate=2 October 2016 | author=Terry Macalister}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Kukes gave more than $150,000 to [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump\u2019s presidential campaign]] and fundraising committee called [[Trump Victory Committee]].<ref name=\"os\" />\n\nHe has also contributed to [[Elizabeth Cheney]]'s 2016 run for a congressional seat in Wyoming.<ref name=\"os\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, Kukes bought a 4-room condominium in [[Trump Parc]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://observer.com/2000/03/steve-wynn-bets-on-820-fifth-avenue-and-loses-big/ | title=Steve Wynn Bets on 820 Fifth Avenue and Loses Big; Upper East Side | work=The Observer | date=27 March 2000 | accessdate=1 October 2016 | author=Deborah Schoeneman}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kukes, Simon}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American political fundraisers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:D. Mendeleev University of Chemical Technology of Russia alumni]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "PRBhtx", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated career milestones and correct some information.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Kukes"}
{"title_page": "Sine-Saloum", "text_new": "{{coord|14|11|N|16|15|W|display=title}}\n\n'''Sine-Saloum''' is a region in [[Senegal]] located north of [[the Gambia]] and south of the [[Petite C\u00f4te]]. It encompasses an area of 24,000 square [[kilometer]]s, about 12% of Senegal, with a population in the 1990s of 1,060,000.<ref name=ngos>{{cite book|author1=Kate Wellard|author2=James G. Copestake|title=Non-governmental organizations and the state in Africa: rethinking roles in sustainable agricultural development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JdSqAYPnagUC&pg=PA270|accessdate=29 September 2011|year=1993|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-08849-7|pages=270\u2013272}}</ref>\n\nThe western portion contains the [[Saloum Delta]], a [[river delta]] at the junction of the [[Saloum River|Saloum]] and the North Atlantic. It is in this region that the [[Saloum Delta National Park]] is located. 145,811 [[hectares]] of the Delta were designated a [[UNESCO Heritage Site]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1359/|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|title=Saloum Delta|accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref> Because it flows so slowly, this delta allows saltwater to travel deep inland.\n\nLong ago, the [[Serer people|Serer]] kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]] and [[Saloum]] were rivals. In 1984, the area was divided into two administrative regions: [[Kaolack Region|Kaolack]] and [[Fatick Region|Fatick]].\n\n==Economy==\n\nPrimary economic activities in the 2000s consisted of fishing, salt production, [[peanut]] farming, and [[millet]] farming.<ref name=ngos/><ref name=mitch>{{cite book|author1=William J. Mitsch|author2=James G. Gosselink|title=Wetlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1cSKeTCi894C&pg=PA92|accessdate=28 September 2011|year=2007|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=978-0-471-69967-5|page=92}}</ref>\n\nTransportation is difficult because of the many islands.\n\nA secondary economy is the construction of fishing boats.\n\n==Ecosystem==\n[[Image:SaloumSalt.JPG|thumb|300px|[[Salt well]]s (view from an [[ultralight aviation|ultralight aeroplane]])]]\nMuch of the region consists of [[mangrove swamp]]s.<ref name=mitch/> The upper reaches of the rivers adjoin the [[Sahel]] region and are affected by its [[desertification]]. The salinity of the water increased during the 1970s instance of the [[Sahel drought]] and mismanagement of the rivers upstream has been described as a factor.<ref name=mitch/> Mangroves are disappearing, and [[freshwater fish]] are disappearing with them. The villagers have difficulty obtaining [[Fresh water|freshwater]]. Sometimes water pumps are donated by international organizations, but spare parts are difficult to find when the pumps fail. The change in water salinity is affecting the ecosystem as much as it is changing the lifestyle of the inhabitants of the region.\n\n==Navigation==\n\nSine-Saloum has long been feared by even Europe's most distinguished mariners because the sandbanks move, particularly in [[Point of Sangomar|Sangomar]]. This danger to outsiders has long protected the region and preserved its individual villages.\n\n==See also==\n\n===Related articles===\n* [[Labour Party of Sine Saloum]]\n* [[Tourism in Senegal]]\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|author=M. Klein|title=Islam and Imperialism in Senegal. Sine-Saloum, 1847-1914|location=Stanford|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1968|pages=285}}\n*{{Cite book|author=Mohamed Mbodj|title=Un exemple d\u2019\u00e9conomie coloniale, le Sine-Saloum (S\u00e9n\u00e9gal), de 1887 \u00e0 1940. Cultures arachidi\u00e8res et mutations sociales|location=Paris|publisher=Universit\u00e9 de Paris VII|year=1978|volume=2|language=fr}}\n*{{Cite book|author=Frans J. Schepers|title=Oiseaux d'eau dans le Delta du Sine-Saloum et la Petite C\u00f4te, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal|publisher=WIWO|date=January 1997|location=Dakar|year=1998|pages=240|language=fr}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.au-senegal.com/le-sine-saloum,025.html?lang=fr Sine-Saloum at Au-Senegal.com]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.senegalaisement.com/senegal/sine_saloum.html Sine-Saloum at Senegalaisement.com]\n\n[[Category:Geography of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Serer country]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|14|11|N|16|15|W|display=title}}\n\n'''Sine-Saloum''' is a region in [[Senegal]] located north of [[the Gambia]] and south of the [[Petite C\u00f4te]]. It encompasses an area of 24,000 square [[kilometer]]s, about 12% of Senegal, with a population in the 1990s of 1,060,000.<ref name=ngos>{{cite book|author1=Kate Wellard|author2=James G. Copestake|title=Non-governmental organizations and the state in Africa: rethinking roles in sustainable agricultural development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JdSqAYPnagUC&pg=PA270|accessdate=29 September 2011|year=1993|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-08849-7|pages=270\u2013272}}</ref>\n\nThe western portion contains the [[Saloum Delta]], a [[river delta]] at the junction of the [[Saloum River|Saloum]] and the North Atlantic. It is in this region that the [[Saloum Delta National Park]] is located. 145,811 [[hectares]] of the Delta were designated a [[UNESCO Heritage Site]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1359/|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|title=Saloum Delta|accessdate=2011-09-28}}</ref> Because it flows so slowly, this delta allows saltwater to travel deep inland.\n\nLong ago, the [[Serer people|Serer]] kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Sine|Sine]] and [[Saloum]] were rivals. In 1984, the area was divided into two administrative regions: [[Kaolack Region|Kaolack]] and [[Fatick Region|Fatick]].\n\n==Economy==\n\nPrimary economic activities in the 2000's consisted of fishing, salt production, [[peanut]] farming, and [[millet]] farming.<ref name=ngos/><ref name=mitch>{{cite book|author1=William J. Mitsch|author2=James G. Gosselink|title=Wetlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1cSKeTCi894C&pg=PA92|accessdate=28 September 2011|year=2007|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=978-0-471-69967-5|page=92}}</ref>\n\nTransportation is difficult because of the many islands.\n\nA secondary economy is the construction of fishing boats.\n\n==Ecosystem==\n[[Image:SaloumSalt.JPG|thumb|300px|[[Salt well]]s (view from an [[ultralight aviation|ultralight aeroplane]])]]\nMuch of the region consists of [[mangrove swamp]]s.<ref name=mitch/> The upper reaches of the rivers adjoin the [[Sahel]] region and are affected by its [[desertification]]. The salinity of the water increased during the 1970s instance of the [[Sahel drought]] and mismanagement of the rivers upstream has been described as a factor.<ref name=mitch/> Mangroves are disappearing, and [[freshwater fish]] are disappearing with them. The villagers have difficulty obtaining [[Fresh water|freshwater]]. Sometimes water pumps are donated by international organizations, but spare parts are difficult to find when the pumps fail. The change in water salinity is affecting the ecosystem as much as it is changing the lifestyle of the inhabitants of the region.\n\n==Navigation==\n\nSine-Saloum has long been feared by even Europe's most distinguished mariners because the sandbanks move, particularly in [[Point of Sangomar|Sangomar]]. This danger to outsiders has long protected the region and preserved its individual villages.\n\n==See also==\n\n===Related articles===\n* [[Labour Party of Sine Saloum]]\n* [[Tourism in Senegal]]\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book|author=M. Klein|title=Islam and Imperialism in Senegal. Sine-Saloum, 1847-1914|location=Stanford|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1968|pages=285}}\n*{{Cite book|author=Mohamed Mbodj|title=Un exemple d\u2019\u00e9conomie coloniale, le Sine-Saloum (S\u00e9n\u00e9gal), de 1887 \u00e0 1940. Cultures arachidi\u00e8res et mutations sociales|location=Paris|publisher=Universit\u00e9 de Paris VII|year=1978|volume=2|language=fr}}\n*{{Cite book|author=Frans J. Schepers|title=Oiseaux d'eau dans le Delta du Sine-Saloum et la Petite C\u00f4te, S\u00e9n\u00e9gal|publisher=WIWO|date=January 1997|location=Dakar|year=1998|pages=240|language=fr}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.au-senegal.com/le-sine-saloum,025.html?lang=fr Sine-Saloum at Au-Senegal.com]\n* {{in lang|fr}} [http://www.senegalaisement.com/senegal/sine_saloum.html Sine-Saloum at Senegalaisement.com]\n\n[[Category:Geography of Senegal]]\n[[Category:Serer country]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine-Saloum"}
{"title_page": "Muir of Ord", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = Scotland\n|official_name= Muir of Ord\n|gaelic_name= Am Bl\u00e0r Dubh \n|scots_name=\n|static_image=Muir of Ord.jpg\n|static_image_caption=The centre of the village\n|population = 2,690\n|population_ref = (2016)<ref name=pop>{{cite web |url=https://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-scotland.php?cityid=S19001077 |title=Muir of Ord (Highland, Scotland, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information |website=www.citypopulation.de |access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n|edinburgh_distance_mi = 118\n|london_distance = {{convert|450|mi|km|abbr=on|0}}\n|os_grid_reference= NH5250\n|map_type=Ross and Cromarty\n|coordinates = {{coord|57.52|-4.46|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n|unitary_scotland= [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland= [[Inverness]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Ross, Skye and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Lochaber]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Ross, Skye and Inverness West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Inverness West]]\n|post_town= Muir of Ord\n|postcode_district = IV6\n|postcode_area= IV\n|dial_code= 01463\n}}\n'''Muir of Ord''' ({{lang-gd|Am Bl\u00e0r Dubh}}) is a village in [[Highland (council area)|the Highlands]] of [[Scotland]]. It is situated near the western boundary of the [[Black Isle]], about {{convert|9|mi|km}} west of the city of [[Inverness]] and {{convert|5 + 1/2|mi|km|0}} south of [[Dingwall]].<ref name=os>{{cite map|title= OS Explorer map: 432: Black Isle | publisher = [[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref> The village has a population of 2,690<ref name=pop/> and sits {{convert|35|m|ft}} above sea level.<ref name=os/> The Scottish geologist, Sir [[Roderick Murchison]] was born in the village in 1792. \n\n==History==\nNamed ''Tarradale'' until 1862,<ref name=us>{{cite web|url=https://www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/muiroford/muiroford/index.html |title= Muir of Ord |website= Undiscovered Scotland| accessdate= 2 September 2018}}</ref> historically access to the village was limited by the natural obstacles of the [[River Beauly]] and the [[River Conon]]. This changed in 1814 with the construction of the [[Conon Bridge]]. [[Cattle drive]]rs used the new routes to transport livestock and markets were set up in 1820 close to where the village now lies.<ref name=us /> In 1835 [[Scotch whisky|whisky]] distilling operations were legally granted in the village and by 1885 the ''Mill of Ord'' produced {{convert|80000|impgal|l}} per year. The village grew extensively in the 19th century due to the establishment of the [[distillery]] and goods industries.<ref name=fb>{{cite web |url=http://www.ambaile.org.uk/detail/en/39964/1/EN39964-muir-of-ord-rovers-football-club.htm|title=Muir of Ord Drovers Football Club|date=2004|website=Ambaile, Highland history and culture}}</ref>\n\n===Castle Hill Henge===\nAlso known as the ''Muir of Ord Fort'', it is a [[Neolithic]] or [[Bronze-age]] henge and national monument of Scotland situated {{convert|300|yd|m}} from [[Muir of Ord railway station]].<ref name=CHH>{{cite web|url=https://muirofordgolfclub.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Castle-Hill-Henge_3rdEdit.pdf|date=March 2018| title= Our 13th Green - Castle Hill Henge A Scheduled National Monument|website = muirofordgolfclub.co.uk}}</ref> Today it is situated on the green of the Muir of Ord golf course. The henge measures {{convert|85|by|65|ft|0}} and is surrounded by an {{convert|18|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide ditch which is {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=on}} deep.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/12670/castle-hill-muir-of-ord| title=Castle Hill, Muir Of Ord| website=Canmore.org | accessdate= 2 September 2018}}</ref> There also are two [[standing stones]] about {{convert|3/4|mi}} away from the henge.<ref name=CHH />\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:Glen Ord Distillery 2 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|The Glen Ord Distillery Visitor Centre]]\n\nJust outside of the centre of the village is the [[Glen Ord Distillery]], one of the few remaining whisky distilleries on the [[Black Isle#Economy|Black Isle]].<ref>[http://www.whisky.com/distilleries/glen_ord_distillery.html Glen Ord Distillery]</ref>  The [[Black Isle Show]],<ref>[http://www.blackisleshow.info Black Isle Show]</ref> one of the largest [[agricultural show]]s in Scotland, is held every August in a showground near Muir of Ord. The showground is a popular exhibition site thanks to the surrounding flower fields.\n\nMuir of Ord used to have a local football team in the 2000s, [[Muir of Ord Rovers F.C.]], that competed in the [[North Caledonian Football League]].<ref name=fb />\n\n==Transport==\nThe major route of the [[A9 road]] passed through the village until 1982, when it was bypassed by the [[Kessock Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brocklehurst|first1=Steven|title=Life and death on the A9|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-26389280|website=BBC News (Scotland - Highlands & Islands)|date=6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe village is served by [[Muir of Ord railway station]], which is on the [[Kyle of Lochalsh Line]] and the [[Far North Line]] between {{Stnlnk|Dingwall}} and {{Stnlnk|Inverness}}.{{sfn|Brailsford|2017|loc=map 18C}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.muiroford.org.uk The Muir of Ord community website]\n\n{{Scottish provinces|minor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muir Of Ord}}\n[[Category:Populated places on the Black Isle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = Scotland\n|official_name= Muir of Ord\n|gaelic_name= Am Bl\u00e0r Dubh \n|scots_name=\n|static_image=Muir of Ord.jpg\n|static_image_caption=The centre of the village\n|population = 2,690\n|population_ref = (2016)<ref name=pop>{{cite web |url=https://www.citypopulation.de/php/uk-scotland.php?cityid=S19001077 |title=Muir of Ord (Highland, Scotland, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information |website=www.citypopulation.de |access-date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n|edinburgh_distance_mi = 118\n|london_distance = {{convert|450|mi|km|abbr=on|0}}\n|os_grid_reference= NH5250\n|map_type=Ross and Cromarty\n|coordinates = {{coord|57.52|-4.46|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n|unitary_scotland= [[Highland (council area)|Highland]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland= [[Inverness]]\n|constituency_westminster= [[Ross, Skye and Lochaber (UK Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Lochaber]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Ross, Skye and Inverness West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Ross, Skye and Inverness West]]\n|post_town= Muir of Ord\n|postcode_district = IV6\n|postcode_area= IV\n|dial_code= 01463\n}}\n'''Muir of Ord''' ({{lang-gd|Am Bl\u00e0r Dubh}}) is a village in [[Highland (council area)|the Highlands]] of [[Scotland]]. It is situated near the western boundary of the [[Black Isle]], about {{convert|9|mi|km}} west of the city of [[Inverness]] and {{convert|5 + 1/2|mi|km|0}} south of [[Dingwall]].<ref name=os>{{cite map|title= OS Explorer map: 432: Black Isle | publisher = [[Ordnance Survey]]}}</ref> The village has a population of 2,690<ref name=pop/> and sits {{convert|35|m|ft}} above sea level.<ref name=os/> The Scottish geologist, Sir [[Roderick Murchison]] was born in the village in 1792. \n\n==History==\nNamed ''Tarradale'' until 1862,<ref name=us>{{cite web|url=https://www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/muiroford/muiroford/index.html |title= Muir of Ord |website= Undiscovered Scotland| accessdate= 2 September 2018}}</ref> historically access to the village was limited by the natural obstacles of the [[River Beauly]] and the [[River Conon]]. This changed in 1814 with the construction of the [[Conon Bridge]]. [[Cattle drive]]rs used the new routes to transport livestock and markets were set up in 1820 close to where the village now lies.<ref name=us /> In 1835 [[Scotch whisky|whisky]] distilling operations were legally granted in the village and by 1885 the ''Mill of Ord'' produced {{convert|80000|impgal|l}} per year. The village grew extensively in the 19th century due to the establishment of the [[distillery]] and goods industries.<ref name=fb>{{cite web |url=http://www.ambaile.org.uk/detail/en/39964/1/EN39964-muir-of-ord-rovers-football-club.htm|title=Muir of Ord Drovers Football Club|date=2004|website=Ambaile, Highland history and culture}}</ref>\n\n===Castle Hill Henge===\nAlso known as the ''Muir of Ord Fort'', it is a [[Neolithic]] or [[Bronze-age]] henge and national monument of Scotland situated {{convert|300|yd|m}} from [[Muir of Ord railway station]].<ref name=CHH>{{cite web|url=https://muirofordgolfclub.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Castle-Hill-Henge_3rdEdit.pdf|date=March 2018| title= Our 13th Green - Castle Hill Henge A Scheduled National Monument|website = muirofordgolfclub.co.uk}}</ref> Today it is situated on the green of the Muir of Ord golf course. The henge measures {{convert|85|by|65|ft|0}} and is surrounded by an {{convert|18|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide ditch which is {{convert|4|ft|m|abbr=on}} deep.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/12670/castle-hill-muir-of-ord| title=Castle Hill, Muir Of Ord| website=Canmore.org | accessdate= 2 September 2018}}</ref> There also are two [[standing stones]] about {{convert|3/4|mi}} away from the henge.<ref name=CHH />\n\n==Amenities==\n[[File:Glen Ord Distillery 2 - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|The Glen Ord Distillery Visitor Centre]]\n\nJust outside of the centre of the village is the [[Glen Ord Distillery]], one of the few remaining whisky distilleries on the [[Black Isle#Economy|Black Isle]].<ref>[http://www.whisky.com/distilleries/glen_ord_distillery.html Glen Ord Distillery]</ref>  The [[Black Isle Show]],<ref>[http://www.blackisleshow.info Black Isle Show]</ref> one of the largest [[agricultural show]]s in Scotland, is held every August in a showground near Muir of Ord. The showground is a popular exhibition site thanks to the surrounding flower fields.\n\nMuir of Ord used to have a local football team in the 2000's, [[Muir of Ord Rovers F.C.]], that competed in the [[North Caledonian Football League]].<ref name=fb />\n\n==Transport==\nThe major route of the [[A9 road]] passed through the village until 1982, when it was bypassed by the [[Kessock Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brocklehurst|first1=Steven|title=Life and death on the A9|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-26389280|website=BBC News (Scotland - Highlands & Islands)|date=6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe village is served by [[Muir of Ord railway station]], which is on the [[Kyle of Lochalsh Line]] and the [[Far North Line]] between {{Stnlnk|Dingwall}} and {{Stnlnk|Inverness}}.{{sfn|Brailsford|2017|loc=map 18C}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.muiroford.org.uk The Muir of Ord community website]\n\n{{Scottish provinces|minor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muir Of Ord}}\n[[Category:Populated places on the Black Isle]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muir_of_Ord"}
